<script>

const QBANK = {
airway: [
// EASY
{d:1,q:"What is the most common cause of airway obstruction in an unconscious patient?",opts:["Foreign body","Tongue","Vomit","Blood"],ans:1,exp:"In unconscious patients, loss of muscle tone causes the tongue to fall back and obstruct the airway. Head-tilt chin-lift or jaw thrust resolves this."},
{d:1,q:"A normal adult respiratory rate at rest is:",opts:["4–8 breaths/min","10–16 breaths/min","12–20 breaths/min","20–30 breaths/min"],ans:2,exp:"Normal adult respiratory rate is 12–20 breaths/min. Outside this range indicates potential respiratory compromise."},
{d:1,q:"The jaw-thrust maneuver is preferred when:",opts:["The patient is a child","Spinal injury is suspected","The patient has dentures","The airway is completely obstructed"],ans:1,exp:"Jaw-thrust opens the airway without neck extension, making it the maneuver of choice when cervical spine injury is possible."},
{d:1,q:"Which device delivers the highest concentration of supplemental oxygen?",opts:["Nasal cannula","Simple face mask","Venturi mask","Non-rebreather mask"],ans:3,exp:"A properly fitted non-rebreather mask with a filled reservoir bag delivers up to 90–95% FiO₂."},
{d:1,q:"An oropharyngeal airway (OPA) is contraindicated in patients who:",opts:["Are unconscious","Have a gag reflex","Are apneic","Have facial trauma"],ans:1,exp:"OPAs can trigger vomiting and laryngospasm in patients with an intact gag reflex. Use only in unconscious patients without a gag reflex."},
{d:1,q:"Snoring respirations in an unconscious patient indicate:",opts:["Adequate ventilation","Partial airway obstruction","Complete airway obstruction","Pulmonary edema"],ans:1,exp:"Snoring indicates partial obstruction, typically by the tongue. Reposition the airway with head-tilt chin-lift or jaw thrust."},
{d:1,q:"Nasal cannulas are typically run at which flow rate?",opts:["1–6 L/min","6–10 L/min","10–15 L/min","15–25 L/min"],ans:0,exp:"Nasal cannulas deliver 24–44% FiO₂ at 1–6 L/min. Higher flows cause mucosal drying with minimal benefit."},
{d:1,q:"Tidal volume is defined as:",opts:["Total lung capacity","Volume of one normal breath","Residual air after full exhalation","Maximum inhaled volume"],ans:1,exp:"Tidal volume is the amount of air moved in a single normal breath — approximately 500 mL in an average adult."},
{d:1,q:"Which sign best confirms adequate BVM ventilation?",opts:["Abdominal rise","Visible bilateral chest rise","Resistance in the bag","Audible crackles"],ans:1,exp:"Visible bilateral chest rise with each squeeze confirms effective ventilation with the BVM."},
{d:1,q:"A nasopharyngeal airway (NPA) is tolerated better than an OPA in patients who are:",opts:["Deeply unconscious","Semi-conscious with a gag reflex","Apneic","Intubated"],ans:1,exp:"NPAs are better tolerated in semi-conscious patients because they are less likely to stimulate the gag reflex than OPAs."},
{d:1,q:"The head-tilt chin-lift maneuver should NOT be used when:",opts:["The patient is elderly","Cervical spine injury is suspected","The patient is unresponsive","The patient is obese"],ans:1,exp:"Head-tilt chin-lift extends the cervical spine and should be avoided when spinal injury is suspected."},
{d:1,q:"Gurgling sounds in the airway indicate:",opts:["Bronchospasm","Fluid or secretions in the upper airway","Airway obstruction by the tongue","Normal breath sounds"],ans:1,exp:"Gurgling indicates fluid (blood, secretions, vomit) in the upper airway, requiring immediate suctioning."},
{d:1,q:"When ventilating an adult with a BVM, each breath should be delivered over:",opts:["0.5 seconds","1 second","3 seconds","5 seconds"],ans:1,exp:"Deliver each ventilation over approximately 1 second — just enough to see the chest rise. Faster delivery increases gastric inflation risk."},
{d:1,q:"Stridor is a high-pitched sound heard during:",opts:["Exhalation only","Inhalation, indicating upper airway obstruction","Both phases, indicating bronchospasm","Only in pediatric patients"],ans:1,exp:"Stridor is a high-pitched inspiratory sound caused by partial upper airway obstruction (e.g., croup, epiglottitis, foreign body)."},
// MEDIUM
{d:2,q:"When using a BVM, the E-C clamp technique refers to:",opts:["A valve seal check","Hand positioning to maintain mask seal","Ventilation rate counting","Chest rise confirmation"],ans:1,exp:"The E-C clamp: three fingers form an 'E' lifting the jaw, while thumb and index form a 'C' pressing the mask to the face — ensuring an airtight seal."},
{d:2,q:"What is the maximum time for a suction attempt before re-oxygenating?",opts:["5 seconds","10–15 seconds","30 seconds","1 minute"],ans:1,exp:"Suction attempts should be limited to 10–15 seconds to prevent hypoxia. Preoxygenate before and after suctioning."},
{d:2,q:"The correct size OPA is measured from:",opts:["The corner of the mouth to the earlobe","The center of the mouth to the earlobe or angle of the jaw","The nose to the chin","The chin to the forehead"],ans:1,exp:"OPA size is determined by measuring from the center of the mouth to the earlobe or angle of the mandible."},
{d:2,q:"When inserting an OPA in an adult, the initial technique involves:",opts:["Inserting with the curve toward the tongue","Inserting upside down and rotating 180°","Inserting with a tongue depressor","Inserting sideways"],ans:1,exp:"In adults, the OPA is inserted with the tip pointing toward the roof of the mouth, then rotated 180° as it passes the soft palate — confirmed with tongue depressor alternatively."},
{d:2,q:"A respiratory rate of 8 breaths/min in an adult indicates:",opts:["Mild hyperventilation","Adequate ventilation","Bradypnea requiring assisted ventilation","A normal finding"],ans:2,exp:"A rate below 8 breaths/min is bradypnea and indicates inadequate ventilation. Assisted ventilation with BVM is required."},
{d:2,q:"Cricoid pressure (Sellick maneuver) is applied to:",opts:["Prevent laryngeal spasm","Reduce risk of aspiration during intubation","Open the airway","Assist in chest rise"],ans:1,exp:"Cricoid pressure compresses the esophagus against the vertebra, reducing passive regurgitation and aspiration risk during ventilation or intubation. Its routine use is debated."},
{d:2,q:"Which airway adjunct is most appropriate for a patient with a suspected basilar skull fracture?",opts:["Nasopharyngeal airway","Oropharyngeal airway","Neither — reposition only","Either is appropriate"],ans:1,exp:"Basilar skull fractures are a relative contraindication for nasopharyngeal airways (risk of intracranial placement). OPA is preferred if the patient is unconscious without a gag reflex."},
{d:2,q:"When ventilating a patient with suspected C-spine injury, you should:",opts:["Use the head-tilt chin-lift only","Use the jaw-thrust maneuver while maintaining in-line stabilization","Avoid all airway maneuvers","Use the recovery position"],ans:1,exp:"Jaw-thrust maintains the airway without cervical extension. Inline stabilization must be maintained by a partner throughout."},
{d:2,q:"Adequate minute ventilation depends on:",opts:["Tidal volume only","Respiratory rate only","Both tidal volume and respiratory rate","Inspiratory time alone"],ans:2,exp:"Minute ventilation = tidal volume × respiratory rate. Both must be adequate; a fast rate with shallow breathing or a slow rate with deep breathing can both result in inadequate ventilation."},
{d:2,q:"The correct position for a patient with suspected epiglottitis is:",opts:["Supine with head extended","Position of comfort — typically sitting upright","Recovery position","Trendelenburg"],ans:1,exp:"Patients with epiglottitis prefer an upright, sniffing position. Forcing supine can precipitate complete airway obstruction. Avoid agitating the patient."},
{d:2,q:"A non-rebreather mask requires the reservoir bag to be:",opts:["Deflated before placing on the patient","At least 2/3 full before placing on the patient","Filled completely before and during use","Empty between breaths"],ans:1,exp:"Pre-inflate the reservoir bag before placing the mask. During use, the bag should not fully deflate on inhalation — flow rate should be high enough (12–15 L/min) to keep it at least 2/3 full."},
{d:2,q:"Carbon dioxide retention (hypercapnia) is most commonly caused by:",opts:["Hyperventilation","Hypoventilation","Pulmonary embolism","Anemia"],ans:1,exp:"Hypoventilation reduces CO₂ elimination, causing hypercapnia. This leads to respiratory acidosis and, if severe, respiratory failure."},
{d:2,q:"Which is TRUE regarding positive-pressure ventilation (PPV)?",opts:["It reduces intrathoracic pressure","It increases risk of gastric inflation","It prevents hypoxia in all patients","It should be delivered rapidly"],ans:1,exp:"PPV increases intrathoracic pressure and can cause gastric inflation, especially without a cuffed endotracheal tube. Slow, gentle ventilation minimizes this risk."},
// HARD
{d:3,q:"A patient with COPD who is hypoxic should receive:",opts:["No supplemental oxygen to avoid respiratory drive suppression","High-flow oxygen via NRB mask","Titrated oxygen targeting SpO₂ 88–92%","Oxygen only if SpO₂ <80%"],ans:2,exp:"COPD patients may rely on hypoxic drive. Target SpO₂ 88–92% — enough to prevent hypoxic injury without eliminating respiratory drive. High-flow O₂ can cause CO₂ retention."},
{d:3,q:"Waveform capnography showing a 'shark fin' pattern indicates:",opts:["Normal ventilation","Esophageal intubation","Bronchospasm/obstructive pattern","Cardiac arrest"],ans:2,exp:"A 'shark fin' (sloping plateau) waveform on capnography indicates airflow obstruction, consistent with bronchospasm (asthma, COPD). A normal waveform has a flat plateau."},
{d:3,q:"In a tension pneumothorax, ventilation becomes progressively more difficult because:",opts:["The airway is obstructed","Increasing intrapleural pressure prevents lung expansion and compresses the mediastinum","The diaphragm is paralyzed","Pulmonary edema fills the alveoli"],ans:1,exp:"Air accumulates under pressure, collapsing the affected lung, shifting mediastinum, compressing the heart and great vessels — causing obstructive shock and respiratory failure."},
{d:3,q:"End-tidal CO₂ (ETCO₂) during CPR is useful because:",opts:["It measures blood pH","A sudden rise in ETCO₂ indicates return of spontaneous circulation","It directly measures cardiac output","Values below 20 mmHg indicate effective CPR"],ans:1,exp:"A sudden increase in ETCO₂ during CPR is one of the earliest indicators of ROSC, as cardiac output resumes and CO₂ is transported to the lungs."},
{d:3,q:"Which finding distinguishes complete airway obstruction from severe obstruction?",opts:["Stridor vs. gurgling","Silent chest with no air movement vs. high-pitched stridor","Cyanosis vs. pallor","SpO₂ <90% vs. SpO₂ <80%"],ans:1,exp:"Complete obstruction = silent chest with no air movement (no sound is possible). Partial/severe obstruction still produces stridor, wheezing, or coughing."},
{d:3,q:"When ventilating a patient with increased airway resistance (status asthmaticus), you should:",opts:["Ventilate rapidly to clear CO₂","Use longer expiratory time to prevent air trapping","Increase tidal volume above 600 mL","Apply PEEP aggressively"],ans:1,exp:"Air trapping (breath stacking) is a major risk in asthma. Allow adequate expiratory time (I:E ratio 1:3–1:5) to prevent dynamic hyperinflation and barotrauma."},
{d:3,q:"Hypoxia with normal pulse oximetry may occur in:",opts:["Pneumonia","Carbon monoxide poisoning","Pulmonary edema","Tension pneumothorax"],ans:1,exp:"Pulse oximetry cannot distinguish carboxyhemoglobin (HbCO) from oxyhemoglobin (HbO₂). CO poisoning causes cellular hypoxia despite a falsely normal SpO₂ reading."},
{d:3,q:"The 'sniffing position' optimally aligns:",opts:["The oral and pharyngeal axes only","The oral, pharyngeal, and tracheal axes for intubation","The spine for defibrillation","The patient for BVM ventilation only"],ans:1,exp:"The sniffing position (neck flexed, head extended) aligns three airway axes (oral, pharyngeal, tracheal) to create a straight line of sight for intubation."},
{d:3,q:"Permissive hypercapnia in EMS refers to:",opts:["Allowing CO₂ to rise to prevent over-ventilation","A target ETCO₂ of 20 mmHg","Ventilating at 20 breaths/min","Using room air instead of supplemental O₂"],ans:0,exp:"Permissive hypercapnia accepts elevated PaCO₂ (e.g., in severe asthma or ARDS) to avoid over-distension of alveoli. Over-ventilation in cardiac arrest is associated with worse outcomes."},
,
{d:1,q:"The recovery position is used for:",opts:["Unconscious patients with no spinal injury and spontaneous breathing","All trauma patients","Patients in cardiac arrest","Patients with chest pain"],ans:0,exp:"The recovery (lateral recumbent) position protects the airway of an unconscious, breathing patient by allowing drainage of fluids and preventing tongue occlusion."},
{d:1,q:"Which maneuver opens the airway without moving the neck?",opts:["Head-tilt chin-lift","Jaw thrust","Modified jaw thrust only","Neck extension"],ans:1,exp:"The jaw thrust opens the airway by moving the mandible anteriorly without cervical spine extension — preferred when C-spine injury is possible."},
{d:1,q:"When should a nasopharyngeal airway NOT be used?",opts:["Unconscious patient with gag reflex","Suspected basilar skull fracture","Patient with epistaxis risk","Both B and C"],ans:3,exp:"NPAs are relatively contraindicated in suspected basilar skull fractures (risk of intracranial placement) and used with caution in patients with bleeding disorders or nasal pathology."},
{d:1,q:"Hyperventilation causes:",opts:["Increased CO₂ — respiratory acidosis","Decreased CO₂ — respiratory alkalosis","Increased oxygen delivery","No physiological change"],ans:1,exp:"Hyperventilation blows off CO₂, causing respiratory alkalosis. In TBI, this causes cerebral vasoconstriction — harmful unless specifically indicated for herniation."},
{d:1,q:"Agonal breathing is:",opts:["Normal breathing pattern","Irregular, gasping respirations — not adequate breathing","Rapid shallow breathing","Deep, labored breathing"],ans:1,exp:"Agonal breathing is ineffective, irregular gasping that may occur after cardiac arrest. It is NOT adequate breathing — CPR should be initiated."},
{d:1,q:"The purpose of a reservoir bag on a non-rebreather mask is:",opts:["To store exhaled air","To store supplemental O₂ for inhalation","To provide PEEP","To measure tidal volume"],ans:1,exp:"The reservoir bag collects 100% O₂ between breaths. When the patient inhales, they draw from the reservoir rather than room air, maximizing FiO₂."},
{d:1,q:"A patient has noisy, wet-sounding respirations. Your first action is:",opts:["Insert an OPA","Suction the airway","Administer oxygen","Reposition the head"],ans:1,exp:"Wet/noisy respirations indicate secretions or fluid in the airway. Suction immediately to clear the airway before other interventions."},
{d:1,q:"What does SpO₂ measure?",opts:["Amount of CO₂ in the blood","Peripheral oxygen saturation of hemoglobin","pH of the blood","Partial pressure of oxygen"],ans:1,exp:"SpO₂ (pulse oximetry) measures the percentage of hemoglobin saturated with oxygen in peripheral capillary blood. Normal is 94–100%."},
{d:1,q:"Flow rate for a simple face mask should be at least:",opts:["2 L/min","6 L/min","12 L/min","15 L/min"],ans:1,exp:"Simple face masks require at least 6 L/min to flush exhaled CO₂ from the mask. Lower rates risk CO₂ rebreathing."},
{d:1,q:"Respiratory alkalosis from hyperventilation causes:",opts:["Vasodilation","Peripheral tingling, dizziness, and carpopedal spasm","Bradycardia","Increased CO₂"],ans:1,exp:"Respiratory alkalosis from hyperventilation causes symptoms: peripheral tingling, lightheadedness, carpopedal spasm (hand/foot cramps) due to altered calcium binding."},
{d:2,q:"A patient with smoke inhalation has normal SpO₂ but AMS. You should:",opts:["Reassure the patient — SpO₂ is normal","Administer high-flow O₂ via NRB mask — suspect CO poisoning","Administer nebulized albuterol","Monitor and transport without O₂"],ans:1,exp:"CO poisoning causes falsely normal SpO₂. AMS + smoke exposure = CO poisoning until proven otherwise. High-flow O₂ accelerates CO elimination (half-life: 5 hours on room air vs 60–90 min on 100% O₂)."},
{d:2,q:"Needle cricothyrotomy is performed at:",opts:["The thyroid cartilage","The cricothyroid membrane (between thyroid and cricoid cartilage)","The trachea at C6","The hyoid bone"],ans:1,exp:"The cricothyroid membrane, located between the thyroid cartilage above and the cricoid cartilage below, is the site for emergency surgical airway access."},
{d:2,q:"Which is a sign of right mainstem intubation?",opts:["Bilateral equal breath sounds","Absent breath sounds on the left, unilateral chest rise","Gastric sounds over epigastrium","High ETCO₂"],ans:1,exp:"If the ETT is advanced too far, it enters the right mainstem bronchus (more vertical), ventilating only the right lung: absent left breath sounds and unilateral right chest rise."},
{d:2,q:"During BVM ventilation, gastric inflation can be reduced by:",opts:["Increasing ventilation rate","Slow, gentle breaths of 1 second duration","High-pressure ventilation","Using a smaller mask"],ans:1,exp:"Slow (1-second), low-pressure breaths minimize pressure exceeding the esophageal opening pressure, reducing air entry into the stomach."},
{d:2,q:"SpO₂ readings may be inaccurate in which condition?",opts:["Hypertension","Hypothermia and poor peripheral perfusion","Tachycardia","Anemia only"],ans:1,exp:"Poor peripheral perfusion (hypothermia, shock) reduces signal quality at the probe site, causing unreliable SpO₂ readings. Also inaccurate in CO poisoning and severe anemia."},
{d:2,q:"CPAP in EMS is most indicated for:",opts:["Apneic patients","Pulmonary edema and hypoxic respiratory failure with spontaneous breathing","Cardiac arrest","Cervical spine injuries"],ans:1,exp:"CPAP (Continuous Positive Airway Pressure) improves oxygenation in spontaneously breathing patients with pulmonary edema, severe asthma, or COPD by keeping alveoli open."},
{d:2,q:"In a patient with facial burns and singed nasal hair, you should anticipate:",opts:["Mild irritation only","Progressive upper airway edema requiring early airway management","Pneumonia 24 hours later","No airway concerns"],ans:1,exp:"Inhalation injury causes progressive airway edema that can cause complete obstruction. Early airway management before edema worsens is critical — don't wait for stridor."},
{d:2,q:"The Sellick maneuver (cricoid pressure) should be released if:",opts:["The patient vomits actively","The intubation is difficult","SpO₂ drops below 95%","The patient becomes agitated"],ans:0,exp:"Active vomiting with cricoid pressure applied can rupture the esophagus. Release pressure immediately if the patient vomits."},
{d:3,q:"Auto-PEEP (intrinsic PEEP) during mechanical ventilation is caused by:",opts:["Over-oxygenation","Incomplete exhalation — air trapping from insufficient expiratory time","Excessive PEEP settings","Disconnection of the circuit"],ans:1,exp:"Auto-PEEP develops when the next breath begins before the previous exhalation is complete, progressively increasing lung volume (breath stacking). Dangerous in asthma/COPD."},
{d:3,q:"A patient is intubated and the ETCO₂ waveform suddenly drops to near zero. The MOST likely cause is:",opts:["Pulmonary edema","Esophageal intubation or tube displacement/obstruction","Return of spontaneous circulation","Hyperventilation"],ans:1,exp:"Sudden loss of ETCO₂ waveform after confirmed intubation suggests tube displacement (esophageal, pharyngeal), obstruction (secretions, kinking), or cardiac arrest. Confirm placement immediately."},
{d:3,q:"Dead space ventilation refers to:",opts:["Alveoli that are ventilated but not perfused","Alveoli that are perfused but not ventilated","Tidal volume minus functional residual capacity","Minute ventilation minus alveolar ventilation"],ans:0,exp:"Dead space = ventilated but unperfused areas (anatomical dead space: conducting airways; physiological dead space: includes V/Q mismatch zones). Increased dead space impairs CO₂ elimination."},
,
{d:1,q:"What is the normal oxygen saturation range for a healthy adult?",opts:["85-90%", "94-100%", "80-85%", "90-93%"],ans:1,exp:"Normal SpO2 is 94-100% in healthy adults. Values below 94% warrant supplemental oxygen and further assessment."},
{d:1,q:"Which airway maneuver is safest when cervical spine injury is suspected?",opts:["Head-tilt chin-lift", "Jaw thrust", "Neck extension", "Triple airway maneuver"],ans:1,exp:"The jaw thrust opens the airway by moving the mandible anteriorly without extending the cervical spine, making it the preferred maneuver when spinal injury is possible."},
{d:1,q:"What sound indicates fluid in the upper airway requiring immediate suctioning?",opts:["Stridor", "Wheezing", "Gurgling", "Snoring"],ans:2,exp:"Gurgling indicates fluid such as blood, secretions, or vomit in the upper airway. Immediate suctioning is required to prevent aspiration and maintain a patent airway."},
{d:1,q:"The maximum time for a single suction attempt is:",opts:["5 seconds", "10-15 seconds", "30 seconds", "60 seconds"],ans:1,exp:"Suction attempts should be limited to 10-15 seconds to prevent hypoxia. Pre-oxygenate before suctioning and again immediately after."},
{d:1,q:"An OPA is sized by measuring from:",opts:["Nose to earlobe", "Center of mouth to earlobe or angle of jaw", "Chin to forehead", "Corner of mouth to chin"],ans:1,exp:"Proper OPA sizing: measure from the center of the mouth to the earlobe or angle of the mandible. Correct size prevents airway trauma and ensures proper placement."},
{d:1,q:"Which oxygen delivery device is best for mild respiratory distress?",opts:["Non-rebreather mask", "Nasal cannula", "BVM", "Venturi mask"],ans:1,exp:"Nasal cannula at 1-6 L/min delivers 24-44% FiO2 and is appropriate for mild distress. It is comfortable and allows the patient to eat and speak."},
{d:1,q:"Respiratory rate below 8 breaths per minute in an adult indicates:",opts:["Normal variation", "Mild anxiety", "Bradypnea requiring assisted ventilation", "Hyperventilation"],ans:2,exp:"Bradypnea below 8 breaths per minute indicates inadequate ventilation. Assisted BVM ventilation is required to prevent respiratory failure and hypoxic injury."},
{d:1,q:"Which is a sign of adequate artificial ventilation?",opts:["Abdominal rise only", "Visible bilateral chest rise", "Skin color change alone", "Resistance in the BVM bag"],ans:1,exp:"Visible bilateral chest rise with each ventilation is the primary confirmation that BVM ventilation is effective and delivering adequate tidal volume."},
{d:1,q:"The nasopharyngeal airway is better tolerated than the OPA in patients who are:",opts:["Deeply unconscious", "Semi-conscious with an intact gag reflex", "In cardiac arrest", "Intubated"],ans:1,exp:"NPA is softer and less likely to trigger the gag reflex. It is the preferred adjunct in semi-conscious patients who cannot tolerate an OPA."},
{d:1,q:"Stridor in a child indicates:",opts:["Lower airway obstruction", "Upper airway narrowing or obstruction", "Pulmonary edema", "Normal breathing"],ans:1,exp:"Stridor is a high-pitched inspiratory sound caused by partial upper airway obstruction at or above the larynx. In children it may indicate croup, epiglottitis, or foreign body."},
{d:1,q:"Wheezing on auscultation indicates:",opts:["Upper airway obstruction", "Fluid in the alveoli", "Narrowing of lower airways", "Normal breath sounds"],ans:2,exp:"Wheezing is a high-pitched sound caused by turbulent airflow through narrowed lower airways, as seen in asthma, COPD, or anaphylaxis."},
{d:1,q:"The recovery position is used for unconscious patients who are:",opts:["Not breathing", "Breathing spontaneously with no spinal injury", "In cardiac arrest", "Hypotensive"],ans:1,exp:"The recovery position maintains a patent airway by allowing drainage of fluids and preventing tongue occlusion in unconscious but breathing patients without spinal injury."},
{d:1,q:"Correct flow rate for a non-rebreather mask is:",opts:["2-4 L/min", "4-6 L/min", "10-15 L/min", "1-2 L/min"],ans:2,exp:"Non-rebreather masks require 10-15 L/min to keep the reservoir bag at least 2/3 full and flush exhaled CO2, delivering up to 90-95% FiO2."},
{d:1,q:"Agonal breathing in cardiac arrest means:",opts:["The patient is breathing adequately", "Ineffective gasping that does not constitute breathing", "The patient is recovering", "Rapid shallow breathing"],ans:1,exp:"Agonal gasps are irregular, ineffective brainstem-driven respirations that occur after cardiac arrest. They do not constitute breathing and CPR should be initiated immediately."},
{d:1,q:"Each BVM breath should be delivered over approximately:",opts:["0.5 seconds", "1 second", "3 seconds", "5 seconds"],ans:1,exp:"Each ventilation should be delivered over approximately 1 second, just enough to see visible chest rise. Faster delivery increases gastric inflation and risk of aspiration."},
{d:2,q:"A COPD patient with SpO2 of 84% should receive oxygen targeting:",opts:["SpO2 99-100%", "SpO2 88-92%", "No oxygen", "SpO2 80-85%"],ans:1,exp:"COPD patients may rely on hypoxic drive. Target SpO2 88-92% to relieve dangerous hypoxia without eliminating respiratory drive or worsening CO2 retention."},
{d:2,q:"Cricoid pressure during BVM ventilation is intended to:",opts:["Open the airway wider", "Reduce gastric inflation by occluding the esophagus", "Stabilize the cervical spine", "Increase tidal volume"],ans:1,exp:"Sellick maneuver compresses the esophagus against the vertebral body, reducing passive regurgitation and aspiration risk during positive pressure ventilation."},
{d:2,q:"A smoke inhalation patient has normal SpO2 but altered mental status. You should:",opts:["Reassure the patient", "Administer high-flow O2 via NRB and suspect CO poisoning", "Apply nasal cannula at 2 L/min", "Monitor only"],ans:1,exp:"CO poisoning causes falsely normal SpO2. Pulse oximetry cannot distinguish carboxyhemoglobin from oxyhemoglobin. AMS plus smoke exposure requires immediate high-flow O2."},
{d:2,q:"After intubation, absent left breath sounds with right-only chest rise indicates:",opts:["Proper tube placement", "Right mainstem intubation", "Esophageal intubation", "Left pneumothorax"],ans:1,exp:"Right mainstem intubation ventilates only the right lung, causing absent left breath sounds and unilateral right chest rise. Withdraw the tube slightly and reassess."},
{d:2,q:"CPAP benefits patients with:",opts:["Apnea", "Pulmonary edema with spontaneous breathing", "Cardiac arrest", "Spinal cord injury"],ans:1,exp:"CPAP keeps alveoli open and reduces work of breathing in spontaneously breathing patients with pulmonary edema or COPD exacerbation."},
{d:2,q:"A Venturi mask delivers precise FiO2 by:",opts:["Using a large reservoir bag", "Entraining a fixed ratio of room air through a jet orifice", "Using a one-way valve", "Delivering 100% oxygen"],ans:1,exp:"Venturi masks use the Bernoulli principle to entrain a precise ratio of room air, delivering 24-50% FiO2. They are used when controlled oxygenation is needed in COPD."},
{d:2,q:"Biot (ataxic) breathing suggests:",opts:["Pulmonary edema", "Brainstem injury or severely increased ICP", "Asthma", "Pneumonia"],ans:1,exp:"Biot or ataxic breathing with irregular unpredictable depth and rate with apnea indicates significant brainstem compression. It is a poor prognostic sign."},
{d:2,q:"Ludwig angina (floor of mouth infection) risks:",opts:["Pneumonia only", "Rapid complete airway obstruction from swelling displacing the tongue", "Spontaneous pneumothorax", "Aspiration only"],ans:1,exp:"Ludwig angina causes progressive swelling of the submandibular space, displacing the tongue posteriorly and potentially causing complete airway obstruction. Early airway management is critical."},
{d:2,q:"Pre-oxygenation before intubation extends safe apnea time by:",opts:["Removing CO2 from lungs", "Replacing nitrogen with oxygen in the FRC to create an oxygen reservoir", "Stimulating breathing", "Reducing secretions"],ans:1,exp:"3-5 minutes of 100% O2 washes nitrogen out of the lungs, replacing it with oxygen. This creates an oxygen reservoir in the FRC, extending safe apnea time from about 1 minute to 8 or more minutes."},
{d:2,q:"Orthopnea is most associated with:",opts:["Asthma", "Congestive heart failure", "Pneumonia", "COPD"],ans:1,exp:"Orthopnea (dyspnea when lying flat, relieved by sitting up) is a classic symptom of CHF. The supine position increases venous return, worsening pulmonary congestion."},
{d:2,q:"Barrel chest in COPD results from:",opts:["Fluid accumulation", "Chronic air trapping and hyperinflation pushing ribs outward", "Muscular hypertrophy", "Pleural thickening"],ans:1,exp:"Chronic air trapping causes progressive hyperinflation of the lungs, pushing the ribs outward and increasing the AP diameter of the chest."},
{d:3,q:"ETCO2 above 10 mmHg during CPR indicates:",opts:["Ineffective compressions", "Adequate cardiac output from compressions", "Complete airway obstruction", "Esophageal intubation"],ans:1,exp:"ETCO2 greater than 10 mmHg during CPR suggests adequate cardiac output. A sudden rise to 35-40 mmHg is one of the most reliable indicators of ROSC."},
{d:3,q:"Auto-PEEP during asthma ventilation is prevented by:",opts:["Increasing ventilation rate", "Allowing a longer expiratory phase to prevent air trapping", "Increasing tidal volume", "Using higher oxygen flow"],ans:1,exp:"Obstructed airways need time to empty. A prolonged expiratory phase with I:E ratio of 1:3 to 1:5 prevents breath stacking and auto-PEEP, which can cause hemodynamic collapse in severe asthma."},
{d:3,q:"CO poisoning causes cellular hypoxia despite normal SpO2 because:",opts:["SpO2 measures partial pressure only", "Pulse oximetry cannot distinguish HbCO from HbO2", "CO increases respiratory rate", "CO destroys red blood cells"],ans:1,exp:"Pulse oximeters measure absorbance at two wavelengths. HbCO absorbs similarly to HbO2, causing falsely normal SpO2 readings despite severe cellular hypoxia."},
{d:3,q:"In a tension pneumothorax, positive pressure ventilation:",opts:["Relieves the tension", "Forces more air into the pleural space worsening compression", "Causes bronchospasm", "Reduces cardiac preload"],ans:1,exp:"PPV forces additional air through the defect into the pleural space, rapidly increasing intrapleural pressure and compressing the mediastinum. Needle decompression must precede PPV."}
],

cardiac: [
{d:1,q:"For adult CPR, the compression-to-ventilation ratio (single rescuer) is:",opts:["15:2","30:2","30:1","15:1"],ans:1,exp:"Current AHA guidelines recommend 30:2 for adults to maximize uninterrupted compression time."},
{d:1,q:"Correct hand placement for adult chest compressions is:",opts:["Upper half of the sternum","Lower half of the sternum","Over the xiphoid process","Left side of the chest"],ans:1,exp:"Compress over the lower half of the sternum. Compressing over the xiphoid risks liver laceration."},
{d:1,q:"Recommended compression depth for an adult is:",opts:["1–2 inches","At least 2 inches","3–4 inches","As deep as possible"],ans:1,exp:"AHA guidelines: compress at least 2 inches (5 cm) but no more than 2.4 inches (6 cm)."},
{d:1,q:"After AED shock, you should:",opts:["Check for pulse immediately","Resume CPR immediately","Administer epinephrine","Ventilate for 2 minutes"],ans:1,exp:"Resume CPR immediately after shock. Do not pause for a pulse check — the heart needs perfusion to convert to a perfusing rhythm."},
{d:1,q:"Which rhythm is shockable by an AED?",opts:["Asystole","PEA","Ventricular fibrillation","Normal sinus rhythm"],ans:2,exp:"AEDs detect and shock VF and pulseless VT. Asystole and PEA are not shockable."},
{d:1,q:"Recommended CPR compression rate is:",opts:["60–80/min","80–100/min","100–120/min","120–140/min"],ans:2,exp:"100–120 compressions per minute is the AHA-recommended rate."},
{d:1,q:"Full chest recoil between compressions is important because:",opts:["It prevents rib fractures","It allows the heart to refill with blood","It maintains compression rate","It reduces fatigue"],ans:1,exp:"Full recoil reduces intrathoracic pressure, promoting venous return so the heart can fill — essential for cardiac output."},
{d:1,q:"Signs of AMI include all EXCEPT:",opts:["Diaphoresis","Chest pressure radiating to arm","Sudden high fever","Nausea"],ans:2,exp:"AMI presents with chest pain/pressure, diaphoresis, nausea, and dyspnea. Fever is not typical of AMI."},
{d:1,q:"Cardiogenic shock is best described as:",opts:["Shock from blood loss","Pump failure of the heart","Shock from severe infection","Shock from spinal injury"],ans:1,exp:"Cardiogenic shock occurs when the heart is too damaged to pump adequately, most often after a large MI."},
{d:1,q:"The first action when arriving to a patient in cardiac arrest is:",opts:["Apply AED","Begin CPR","Ensure scene safety","Establish IV access"],ans:2,exp:"Scene safety is always first. Rescuers who become victims worsen the situation."},
{d:1,q:"CPR should be initiated when a patient has:",opts:["A weak pulse and shallow breathing","No pulse and no normal breathing","A pulse but is unconscious","Slow, irregular breathing"],ans:1,exp:"CPR is indicated when there is no pulse AND no normal breathing (agonal gasps do not count as breathing)."},
{d:1,q:"When performing CPR, the rescuer should switch compressors every:",opts:["1 minute","2 minutes","5 minutes","10 minutes"],ans:1,exp:"Rescuers should switch every 2 minutes (when the AED analyzes) to maintain high-quality compressions and prevent fatigue."},
{d:1,q:"The chain of survival begins with:",opts:["Early defibrillation","Recognition and activation of EMS","CPR by bystanders","Advanced life support"],ans:1,exp:"The chain of survival starts with early recognition of cardiac arrest and activation of the emergency response system."},
{d:1,q:"Pulseless ventricular tachycardia (pVT) is treated with:",opts:["Observation","Defibrillation","Cardioversion","Epinephrine only"],ans:1,exp:"pVT, like VF, is a shockable rhythm treated with immediate defibrillation followed by CPR."},
{d:2,q:"During CPR, the chest should be allowed to fully recoil because leaning on the chest:",opts:["Increases compression depth","Impairs venous return to the heart","Prevents rib fractures","Reduces cardiac output"],ans:1,exp:"Residual leaning prevents the heart from filling between compressions, reducing coronary and cerebral perfusion pressure."},
{d:2,q:"A patient in V-fib for 8 minutes without CPR. The BEST initial intervention is:",opts:["Immediate defibrillation","2 minutes of CPR before defibrillation","Epinephrine first","Airway management first"],ans:1,exp:"After prolonged V-fib (>4–5 min), 2 minutes of CPR before defibrillation restores substrate for a shockable rhythm. However, protocols vary — follow local standing orders."},
{d:2,q:"Which is a sign of return of spontaneous circulation (ROSC)?",opts:["Continued absent pulse","Dilated pupils","Sudden increase in ETCO₂","Fine ventricular fibrillation"],ans:2,exp:"A sudden rise in ETCO₂ is one of the earliest and most reliable indicators of ROSC, as cardiac output resumes CO₂ transport."},
{d:2,q:"The most common cause of PEA arrest is:",opts:["Hyperkalemia","Hypovolemia (the 'H's and T's')","Pulmonary embolism","Tension pneumothorax"],ans:1,exp:"The H's and T's guide PEA causes. Hypovolemia and hypoxia are the most common causes. Treat the underlying cause simultaneously with CPR."},
{d:2,q:"In two-rescuer infant CPR, the preferred compression technique is:",opts:["Two-finger technique","Two-thumb encircling technique","Heel of one hand","Full hand compression"],ans:1,exp:"Two-thumb encircling technique provides better compression force and depth for infants when two rescuers are present."},
{d:2,q:"Synchronized cardioversion differs from defibrillation in that it:",opts:["Uses less energy","Delivers shock during the T-wave","Delivers shock during the QRS complex","Is used for pulseless rhythms"],ans:2,exp:"Synchronized cardioversion delivers the shock during the QRS complex, avoiding the vulnerable T-wave period that could trigger VF. Defibrillation is unsynchronized for pulseless rhythms."},
{d:2,q:"A patient has ST-elevation in leads II, III, and aVF. This suggests:",opts:["Anterior MI","Inferior MI","Lateral MI","Posterior MI"],ans:1,exp:"Leads II, III, and aVF reflect the inferior wall of the left ventricle (supplied by the RCA). ST elevation here indicates inferior STEMI."},
{d:2,q:"Nitroglycerin should be withheld if the patient's systolic BP is below:",opts:["100 mmHg","90 mmHg","120 mmHg","80 mmHg"],ans:0,exp:"Most protocols withhold nitroglycerin if systolic BP <90–100 mmHg due to risk of severe hypotension. Always check local protocol."},
{d:2,q:"Aspirin is given to chest pain patients because it:",opts:["Dissolves clots","Prevents platelet aggregation to limit clot growth","Reduces chest pain directly","Lowers blood pressure"],ans:1,exp:"Aspirin inhibits platelet aggregation (thromboxane A2 pathway), limiting further clot formation in coronary arteries during ACS."},
{d:2,q:"Jugular venous distension (JVD) in a cardiac arrest patient suggests:",opts:["Hypovolemia","Obstructive cause (tension pneumothorax, cardiac tamponade)","Distributive shock","Neurogenic shock"],ans:1,exp:"JVD during arrest suggests an obstructive cause preventing venous return: tension pneumothorax or cardiac tamponade. Address these reversible causes."},
{d:3,q:"During cardiac arrest, high-quality CPR is defined as compression depth ≥2 inches, rate 100–120/min, full recoil, and a chest compression fraction (CCF) of:",opts:["≥40%","≥60%","≥80%","≥90%"],ans:1,exp:"AHA recommends minimizing interruptions to achieve a CCF (proportion of resuscitation time with compressions in progress) of ≥60%, ideally >80%."},
{d:3,q:"Beck's triad of cardiac tamponade includes:",opts:["Hypertension, bradycardia, widened pulse pressure","Hypotension, muffled heart sounds, JVD","Tachycardia, hypertension, diaphoresis","Chest pain, dyspnea, hemoptysis"],ans:1,exp:"Beck's triad: hypotension (reduced cardiac output), muffled heart sounds (fluid surrounding heart), and JVD (impaired venous return). Pericardiocentesis is definitive treatment."},
{d:3,q:"Electrical alternans on an ECG is associated with:",opts:["Hyperkalemia","Ventricular hypertrophy","Cardiac tamponade","Myocarditis"],ans:2,exp:"Electrical alternans (alternating QRS complex height) is caused by the heart swinging in a large pericardial effusion — a specific ECG finding for tamponade."},
{d:3,q:"Pulsus paradoxus is defined as a drop in systolic BP during inspiration of more than:",opts:["5 mmHg","10 mmHg","20 mmHg","30 mmHg"],ans:1,exp:"Pulsus paradoxus >10 mmHg during inspiration suggests cardiac tamponade, severe asthma, or tension pneumothorax — conditions that impair cardiac output with respiration."},
{d:3,q:"The H's and T's of PEA: which T is treated with needle decompression?",opts:["Thrombosis (pulmonary)","Tension pneumothorax","Tamponade","Toxins"],ans:1,exp:"Tension pneumothorax is treated with needle decompression (2nd ICS, MCL or 4th/5th ICS, AAL). It is a rapidly reversible cause of PEA arrest."},
{d:3,q:"Targeted Temperature Management (TTM) post-ROSC targets a core temperature of:",opts:["32–36°C","36–38°C","28–32°C","38–40°C"],ans:0,exp:"TTM (formerly therapeutic hypothermia) targets 32–36°C for 24 hours post-ROSC to reduce reperfusion injury and neurological damage. Exact targets vary by protocol."},
{d:3,q:"A rhythm showing wide complex tachycardia at 180 bpm in an unstable patient requires:",opts:["Adenosine","Amiodarone IV","Synchronized cardioversion","Defibrillation"],ans:2,exp:"Unstable wide complex tachycardia (altered mental status, chest pain, hypotension) is treated with immediate synchronized cardioversion regardless of the underlying rhythm."},
,
{d:1,q:"The AED should be applied as soon as available because:",opts:["It replaces the need for CPR","Every minute of V-fib reduces survival by 10% without defibrillation","It measures blood pressure","It administers medications"],ans:1,exp:"V-fib survival decreases approximately 10% per minute without defibrillation. Early defibrillation is the single most important intervention for shockable cardiac arrest."},
{d:1,q:"Which is NOT a reversible cause of cardiac arrest (H's and T's)?",opts:["Hypoxia","Hypertension","Hypothermia","Tension pneumothorax"],ans:1,exp:"Hypertension is not a reversible cause of cardiac arrest. The H's: Hypoxia, Hypovolemia, Hydrogen ion (acidosis), Hypo/Hyperkalemia, Hypothermia. The T's: Tension pneumo, Tamponade, Toxins, Thrombosis."},
{d:1,q:"Normal adult blood pressure is approximately:",opts:["80/50 mmHg","120/80 mmHg","140/90 mmHg","160/100 mmHg"],ans:1,exp:"Normal adult BP is approximately 120/80 mmHg. Hypertension is ≥130/80 mmHg (Stage 1) or ≥140/90 mmHg (Stage 2) by current AHA guidelines."},
{d:1,q:"A patient with syncope (fainting) most commonly has:",opts:["Cardiac tamponade","Brief loss of consciousness from transient decrease in cerebral perfusion","Stroke","Seizure"],ans:1,exp:"Syncope is a transient, self-limited loss of consciousness from reduced cerebral perfusion, usually from a benign vagal episode, orthostatic hypotension, or cardiac cause."},
{d:1,q:"The pulse location checked during adult CPR quality assessment is:",opts:["Radial pulse","Brachial pulse","Carotid pulse","Femoral pulse"],ans:2,exp:"The carotid pulse is assessed during adult CPR (brachial pulse for infants). Checks should be brief (<10 seconds) to minimize interruptions."},
{d:1,q:"An AED pad should NOT be placed over:",opts:["The left chest","An implanted cardiac device or medication patch","The right upper chest","A hairless area"],ans:1,exp:"AED pads placed directly over implanted devices (pacemakers, ICDs) or medication patches (nitroglycerin, fentanyl) may reduce effectiveness or cause skin burns. Place pads at least 1 inch away from devices."},
{d:1,q:"In a patient with chest pain, which information is MOST critical to relay to the receiving hospital?",opts:["Patient's insurance information","12-lead ECG findings and symptom onset time","Patient's medication list only","Vital signs only"],ans:1,exp:"STEMI alerts are activated based on ECG findings and symptom onset time — both are critical for cardiac catheterization lab activation. Early notification reduces door-to-balloon time."},
{d:1,q:"The brachial pulse is assessed in:",opts:["Adults","Infants","Toddlers","All patients"],ans:1,exp:"The brachial pulse (medial upper arm) is used to assess pulse in infants because the carotid pulse is difficult to palpate in their short necks."},
{d:1,q:"Adequate CPR compression quality is best assessed by:",opts:["Watching for chest rise","Rate counter on monitor/AED and ETCO₂","Patient color","Pulse check every 2 minutes"],ans:1,exp:"Modern monitors/AEDs provide real-time CPR feedback (compression rate, depth) and ETCO₂ monitoring (target >10 mmHg during CPR = reasonable compressions)."},
{d:1,q:"Ventricular fibrillation is characterized by:",opts:["Organized, rapid electrical activity","Chaotic, disorganized electrical activity with no effective contraction","Complete absence of electrical activity","Regular rhythm at 300 bpm"],ans:1,exp:"V-fib is completely disorganized electrical activity — the myocardium quivers without effective contraction, producing no cardiac output. Immediate defibrillation required."},
{d:2,q:"A patient with a pacemaker is in cardiac arrest. When applying AED pads:",opts:["Do not use AED on pacemaker patients","Place pads at least 1 inch from the device, then use AED normally","Use only manual defibrillation","Deliver CPR only — no defibrillation"],ans:1,exp:"AEDs can be used on patients with pacemakers. Place pads at least 1 inch from the device to avoid energy shunting. Confirm pacemaker location first (usually subclavicular bulge)."},
{d:2,q:"In a patient with STEMI, time-to-reperfusion (door-to-balloon) should be under:",opts:["30 minutes","90 minutes","180 minutes","240 minutes"],ans:1,exp:"AHA/ACC benchmark: primary PCI (balloon) for STEMI within 90 minutes of first medical contact (FMC). Early EMS notification with 12-lead transmission can activate the cath lab before arrival."},
{d:2,q:"Torsades de Pointes is a type of polymorphic VT associated with:",opts:["Hyperkalemia","Prolonged QT interval","Hypokalemia only","Short PR interval"],ans:1,exp:"Torsades de Pointes (twisting of the points) is associated with prolonged QT interval from electrolyte disturbances (hypokalemia, hypomagnesemia), drugs, or congenital abnormalities."},
{d:2,q:"Atrial fibrillation with rapid ventricular rate in an unstable patient is treated with:",opts:["Rate control medications (diltiazem)","Synchronized cardioversion","Defibrillation","Observation"],ans:1,exp:"Unstable A-fib (hypotension, AMS, acute pulmonary edema, chest pain) is treated with synchronized cardioversion. Stable A-fib is treated with rate control medications."},
{d:2,q:"Third-degree (complete) heart block is characterized by:",opts:["Prolonged PR interval","No relationship between P waves and QRS complexes","Wide QRS only","Fast atrial rate"],ans:1,exp:"In complete heart block, there is no conduction between atria and ventricles — P waves and QRS complexes occur independently at their own rates with no relationship."},
{d:2,q:"A patient with new onset of severe tearing chest pain radiating to the back and a BP difference of 30 mmHg between arms requires:",opts:["Aspirin and nitroglycerin","Immediate transport — suspected aortic dissection; avoid thrombolytics","12-lead ECG and aspirin","Fluid bolus"],ans:1,exp:"Suspected aortic dissection requires rapid transport and surgical consultation. Thrombolytics and anticoagulants are absolutely contraindicated — they worsen hemorrhage. BP management is key."},
{d:2,q:"Hypotension combined with bradycardia after a myocardial infarction suggests:",opts:["Cardiogenic shock","Right ventricular infarction","Vasovagal response","Normal variant"],ans:1,exp:"RV infarction (from RCA occlusion causing inferior MI) presents with hypotension and bradycardia. Critically: avoid nitroglycerin and diuretics — the RV is preload-dependent. Give IV fluids."},
{d:3,q:"The Wellens syndrome pattern on ECG indicates:",opts:["Acute inferior MI","Critical LAD stenosis — high risk for anterior MI","Pulmonary embolism","Complete heart block"],ans:1,exp:"Wellens pattern (Type A: biphasic T-waves in V2–V3; Type B: deep symmetric T-wave inversions V2–V3) indicates significant proximal LAD stenosis — high imminent risk for anterior STEMI."},
{d:3,q:"De Winter T-waves on ECG are significant because they indicate:",opts:["Benign early repolarization","STEMI equivalent — LAD occlusion without ST elevation","Pericarditis","Right heart strain"],ans:1,exp:"De Winter T-waves (upsloping ST depression with tall, symmetric peaked T-waves in precordial leads + ST elevation in aVR) represent an LAD occlusion STEMI equivalent requiring emergent intervention."},
{d:3,q:"Commotio cordis is caused by:",opts:["Electrical shock from power lines","Blunt precordial impact during the vulnerable cardiac cycle phase","Penetrating chest trauma","Myocarditis"],ans:1,exp:"Commotio cordis: blunt chest impact (e.g., baseball, hockey puck) during the vulnerable T-wave window triggers VF. Common in young athletes. Immediate defibrillation is the only treatment."},
,
{d:1,q:"The proper rate for ventilating an apneic adult patient with a BVM is:",opts:["6 breaths/min","10–12 breaths/min","20 breaths/min","30 breaths/min"],ans:1,exp:"Apneic adult: ventilate at 10–12 breaths/min (one breath every 5–6 seconds). Faster rates cause hyperventilation and increased intrathoracic pressure."},
{d:1,q:"Which is TRUE about mouth-to-mask ventilation?",opts:["It delivers less oxygen than a BVM","It delivers approximately 16% oxygen from exhaled air","It is the least preferred method","It requires no seal with the face"],ans:1,exp:"Mouth-to-mask delivers approximately 16% oxygen (exhaled air). It is acceptable when BVM is unavailable or a single rescuer cannot maintain a mask seal with one hand."},
{d:1,q:"The correct technique for inserting a nasopharyngeal airway is:",opts:["Insert with the bevel facing the septum","Insert with the bevel facing the nasal septum, advance gently along the floor of the nostril","Insert straight back into the nostril","Rotate 180° during insertion"],ans:1,exp:"NPA insertion: bevel toward the nasal septum, advance gently along the floor of the nasal passage. Use lubrication to minimize trauma."},
{d:2,q:"A patient with Ludwig's angina (submandibular cellulitis) is at risk for:",opts:["Aspiration pneumonia","Rapidly progressing airway obstruction from floor-of-mouth swelling","Pneumothorax","Pulmonary embolism"],ans:1,exp:"Ludwig's angina: severe infection of the submandibular space causes floor-of-mouth swelling that can rapidly displace the tongue posteriorly, causing complete airway obstruction. Early airway management is critical."},
{d:2,q:"Which patient should receive bag-valve-mask ventilation rather than supplemental O₂ alone?",opts:["SpO₂ 88% on room air","RR 28 with adequate tidal volume","RR 6 with shallow, inadequate respirations","Patient in mild respiratory distress"],ans:2,exp:"BVM is indicated when breathing is inadequate: rate <8 or >30, shallow (inadequate tidal volume), agonal gasps, or apnea. SpO₂ 88% may be correctable with supplemental O₂ alone if breathing is adequate."},
{d:2,q:"The Venturi mask provides a precise FiO₂ because:",opts:["It uses a reservoir bag","It entrains a controlled amount of room air via the jet effect","It has a one-way valve","It is connected to a high-pressure source"],ans:1,exp:"Venturi masks use the Bernoulli principle to entrain a fixed ratio of room air, delivering a precise FiO₂ (24–50%) — useful in COPD to avoid over-oxygenation."},
{d:2,q:"Pulmonary aspiration of gastric contents causes:",opts:["Immediate improvement in oxygenation","Chemical pneumonitis and pneumonia, potentially worsening over hours","Immediate respiratory arrest","No significant harm if quickly suctioned"],ans:1,exp:"Aspiration of acidic gastric contents causes chemical pneumonitis (immediate irritation) which can progress to aspiration pneumonia and ARDS over hours to days."},
{d:3,q:"A trauma patient has paradoxical breathing (flail segment), SpO₂ 86%, and distended neck veins. The MOST likely diagnosis is:",opts:["Flail chest with pulmonary contusion only","Tension pneumothorax — treat immediately with needle decompression","Cardiac tamponade","Hemothorax"],ans:1,exp:"JVD + hypoxia + respiratory distress in chest trauma suggests tension pneumothorax (or tamponade). The flail segment may be distracting — treat the tension pneumo (needle decompression) immediately."},
{d:3,q:"High-frequency oscillatory ventilation (HFOV) in EMS context is relevant because:",opts:["It is used in all field intubations","Understanding it explains why conventional tidal volumes should not exceed 6–8 mL/kg ideal body weight to prevent lung injury","It is performed routinely by paramedics","It applies only to neonatal care"],ans:1,exp:"Lung-protective ventilation (6–8 mL/kg IBW) minimizes ventilator-induced lung injury (VILI) — the same principle behind HFOV in critical care. Over-distension of alveoli causes barotrauma and worsens ARDS."},
{d:1,q:"Cheyne-Stokes respirations are characterized by:",opts:["Rapid deep respirations","Cycles of increasing-decreasing depth with apneic periods","Slow, deep, irregular gasping","Rapid, shallow, regular pattern"],ans:1,exp:"Cheyne-Stokes: crescendo-decrescendo breathing with apneic periods — associated with CHF, increased intracranial pressure, and terminal illness."},
{d:2,q:"Biot's respirations (cluster breathing) indicate:",opts:["Pulmonary edema","Brainstem injury or increased intracranial pressure","Asthma","Pneumonia"],ans:1,exp:"Biot's/ataxic breathing: irregular, unpredictable depth and rate with periods of apnea — indicates significant brainstem compression or injury. A poor prognostic sign."},
,
{d:1,q:"The normal PR interval on an ECG is:",opts:["<0.08 seconds","0.12–0.20 seconds","0.20–0.40 seconds",">0.40 seconds"],ans:1,exp:"Normal PR interval: 0.12–0.20 seconds (3–5 small squares). PR >0.20s = first-degree heart block. PR <0.12s may indicate pre-excitation (WPW)."},
{d:1,q:"Which is TRUE about CPR-induced coronary perfusion pressure?",opts:["It is irrelevant to ROSC likelihood","Higher coronary perfusion pressure during CPR is associated with higher ROSC rates","CPR cannot generate meaningful coronary perfusion","Perfusion pressure peaks during the relaxation phase of compressions"],ans:1,exp:"Coronary perfusion pressure (CPP) during CPR correlates with ROSC likelihood. CPP is generated during the decompression phase — another reason full recoil is critical."},
{d:1,q:"Paroxysmal supraventricular tachycardia (PSVT) is characterized by:",opts:["Gradual onset tachycardia","Sudden onset narrow complex tachycardia (usually 150–250 bpm)","Wide complex irregular rhythm","Sinus tachycardia with rate >150"],ans:1,exp:"PSVT: sudden onset (paroxysmal) narrow complex tachycardia at 150–250 bpm, often with abrupt termination. Caused by re-entry circuits in or near the AV node."},
{d:2,q:"Stable PSVT may be initially treated with:",opts:["Immediate cardioversion","Vagal maneuvers (Valsalva, carotid massage if allowed by protocol)","High-flow oxygen alone","Adenosine 6 mg only"],ans:1,exp:"Stable PSVT initial treatment: vagal maneuvers (cough, Valsalva, bearing down). If unsuccessful, adenosine 6 mg rapid IV push may be used per protocol. Unstable PSVT = synchronized cardioversion."},
{d:1,q:"Which is the fastest-acting vasopressor for cardiac arrest resuscitation?",opts:["Vasopressin","Epinephrine","Dopamine","Norepinephrine"],ans:1,exp:"Epinephrine 1 mg IV/IO every 3–5 minutes is the primary vasopressor in cardiac arrest. It increases coronary and cerebral perfusion pressure by peripheral vasoconstriction."},
{d:2,q:"First-degree AV block is characterized by:",opts:["Some P waves not conducted","Prolonged PR interval (>0.20 s) with all P waves conducted","Dropped QRS complexes","No P waves"],ans:1,exp:"First-degree AV block: prolonged PR interval (>0.20s) with every P wave followed by a QRS — delayed but intact conduction. Usually benign, no treatment required."},
{d:2,q:"Mobitz Type II (second-degree AV block) is dangerous because:",opts:["It always converts to first-degree block","It can progress unpredictably to complete (third-degree) heart block","It causes immediate cardiac arrest","It is only seen in athletes"],ans:1,exp:"Mobitz II: intermittent non-conducted P waves without prior PR lengthening. Unpredictable — can suddenly progress to complete heart block. Transcutaneous pacing may be needed."},
{d:1,q:"Pulseless electrical activity (PEA) is defined as:",opts:["Asystole on the monitor","Organized electrical activity on the monitor without a detectable pulse","Ventricular fibrillation","Sinus bradycardia without a pulse"],ans:1,exp:"PEA: organized (or semi-organized) electrical activity on the ECG with no palpable pulse. Caused by mechanical (obstructive) or metabolic factors — treat the underlying cause."},
{d:2,q:"Which ECG finding is characteristic of hyperkalemia?",opts:["PR shortening","Peaked T-waves (early) progressing to wide QRS and sine wave","ST elevation in all leads","Delta waves"],ans:1,exp:"Hyperkalemia progression: peaked/tall narrow T-waves → PR prolongation → P wave flattening → wide QRS → sine wave → asystole. Each stage is more severe."},
{d:3,q:"The 'door-to-needle' time for thrombolysis in STEMI when PCI is unavailable should be:",opts:["90 minutes","30 minutes","60 minutes","120 minutes"],ans:1,exp:"When PCI is unavailable and transfer time will exceed 120 minutes, thrombolysis should be given within 30 minutes of hospital arrival (door-to-needle <30 min) for STEMI."},
{d:2,q:"Wolf-Parkinson-White (WPW) syndrome on ECG shows:",opts:["Long QT interval","Short PR interval with delta wave (slurred QRS upstroke)","Deep Q waves in V1–V3","ST depression in all leads"],ans:1,exp:"WPW: an accessory pathway (Bundle of Kent) bypasses the AV node — resulting in short PR (<0.12s), delta wave, and wide QRS. Risk of SVT and, if atrial fibrillation develops, rapid conduction causing VF."},
,
{d:1,q:"Rales (crackles) on auscultation indicate:",opts:["Airway narrowing","Fluid in the alveoli or small airways","Bronchospasm","Normal breath sounds"],ans:1,exp:"Crackles are produced by reopening of collapsed or fluid-filled alveoli. They indicate pulmonary edema, pneumonia, or atelectasis."},
{d:1,q:"Rhonchi on auscultation indicate:",opts:["Alveolar fluid","Secretions in larger airways that change with coughing","Bronchospasm","Pleural friction"],ans:1,exp:"Rhonchi are low-pitched rumbling sounds caused by mucus in the larger airways. They often clear with coughing, distinguishing them from crackles."},
{d:2,q:"A patient with smoke inhalation has normal SpO2 but altered mental status. You should:",opts:["Reassure — SpO2 is normal","Give high-flow O2 via NRB — suspect CO poisoning","Give albuterol","Monitor only"],ans:1,exp:"CO poisoning causes falsely normal SpO2. AMS plus smoke exposure equals CO poisoning until proven otherwise. High-flow O2 accelerates CO elimination."},
{d:1,q:"Orthopnea is defined as:",opts:["Dyspnea on exertion","Dyspnea while lying flat relieved by sitting upright","Rapid breathing","Painful breathing"],ans:1,exp:"Orthopnea occurs when lying flat worsens dyspnea. It is caused by increased venous return to the heart in the supine position, worsening pulmonary congestion in CHF."},
{d:1,q:"Cheyne-Stokes respirations are characterized by:",opts:["Rapid deep respirations","Cycles of increasing-decreasing depth with apneic periods","Slow deep gasping","Rapid shallow regular pattern"],ans:1,exp:"Cheyne-Stokes: crescendo-decrescendo breathing with apneic periods. Associated with CHF, increased intracranial pressure, and terminal illness."},
{d:2,q:"The most reliable confirmation of endotracheal tube placement is:",opts:["Bilateral chest rise","Waveform capnography showing consistent CO2 with each breath","Auscultation alone","Fogging of the tube"],ans:1,exp:"Waveform capnography is the most reliable ETT placement confirmation. Consistent ETCO2 waveform with each ventilation confirms tracheal placement. Chest rise and auscultation alone can be misleading."},
{d:2,q:"Upper airway burns from inhalation are most dangerous because:",opts:["They cause immediate pneumonia","Progressive edema can cause complete airway obstruction within hours","They only affect the skin","Oxygen levels drop slowly"],ans:1,exp:"Inhalation burns cause progressive airway edema. Early intubation before swelling makes it impossible is critical — do not wait for stridor to develop."},
{d:1,q:"Central cyanosis (blue lips and mucous membranes) indicates:",opts:["Peripheral vascular disease","Severe systemic hypoxia","Mild oxygen desaturation","Cold exposure only"],ans:1,exp:"Central cyanosis reflects severe systemic hypoxia when deoxyhemoglobin exceeds 5 g/dL in arterial blood. More reliable than peripheral cyanosis which can simply reflect vasoconstriction."},
{d:2,q:"Biot respirations (ataxic breathing) indicate:",opts:["Pulmonary edema","Brainstem injury or severely increased intracranial pressure","Asthma","Pneumonia"],ans:1,exp:"Biot or ataxic breathing — irregular, unpredictable depth and rate with periods of apnea — indicates significant brainstem compression or injury. A poor prognostic sign."},
{d:2,q:"CPAP in EMS is most indicated for:",opts:["Apneic patients","Pulmonary edema with spontaneous breathing","Cardiac arrest","All respiratory complaints"],ans:1,exp:"CPAP improves oxygenation in spontaneously breathing patients with pulmonary edema, severe asthma, or COPD by keeping alveoli open and reducing the work of breathing."},
{d:1,q:"Pneumonia typically presents with:",opts:["Sudden pleuritic pain only","Fever, productive cough, localized crackles, and dyspnea","Rapid onset paralysis","Chest tightness alone"],ans:1,exp:"Pneumonia: fever, productive cough with purulent sputum, localized crackles on auscultation, and dyspnea. May be complicated by sepsis or respiratory failure."},
{d:2,q:"A respiratory rate of 6 per minute in an adult requires:",opts:["Supplemental oxygen only","Assisted BVM ventilation — rate is inadequate","Position change","Observation"],ans:1,exp:"Rate below 8 per minute is bradypnea indicating inadequate ventilation. Assisted ventilation with BVM is required to prevent respiratory failure."},
{d:3,q:"Auto-PEEP during BVM ventilation is caused by:",opts:["Over-oxygenation","Incomplete exhalation with insufficient expiratory time — air trapping","Mask leak","High oxygen flow"],ans:1,exp:"Auto-PEEP develops when the next breath begins before the previous exhalation completes. In obstructive disease this causes progressive air trapping and increasing intrathoracic pressure. Allow adequate expiratory time."},
{d:1,q:"The correct flow rate to pre-fill a non-rebreather reservoir bag is:",opts:["2 L/min","12-15 L/min","6 L/min","1 L/min"],ans:1,exp:"Run flow at 12-15 L/min to pre-inflate the reservoir bag before placing the mask. The bag should not fully collapse during inhalation, ensuring maximum FiO2 delivery."},
{d:2,q:"A Venturi mask provides a precise FiO2 because:",opts:["It uses a reservoir bag","It entrains a fixed ratio of room air via the jet effect","It has a one-way valve","It uses high pressure"],ans:1,exp:"Venturi masks use the Bernoulli principle to entrain a fixed room-air ratio, delivering precise FiO2 of 24-50%. Useful in COPD to avoid excessive oxygenation."}
,
{d:1,q:"Kussmaul respirations are deep, rapid breaths seen in:",opts:["CHF","Diabetic ketoacidosis as compensation for metabolic acidosis","Opioid overdose","Normal exercise"],ans:1,exp:"Kussmaul respirations are deep, rapid, unlabored breaths that blow off CO2 to compensate for metabolic acidosis — most classically seen in DKA."},
{d:2,q:"A patient with epiglottitis should NOT have their mouth examined because:",opts:["It causes pain","It may precipitate complete airway obstruction through agitation or laryngospasm","All of the above","None of the above"],ans:1,exp:"Examining the throat of an epiglottitis patient can cause agitation or laryngospasm, precipitating complete airway obstruction. Keep the patient calm in position of comfort."},
{d:1,q:"Inspiratory stridor is associated with:",opts:["Lower airway obstruction","Upper airway obstruction above the larynx","Bronchospasm","Pulmonary edema"],ans:1,exp:"Inspiratory stridor indicates upper airway obstruction above or at the larynx. Expiratory wheeze indicates lower airway narrowing. Biphasic stridor suggests obstruction at the larynx."},
{d:2,q:"When ventilating a COPD patient with a BVM, you should:",opts:["Ventilate as fast as possible","Ventilate slowly with longer expiratory time to prevent air trapping","All of the above","None of the above"],ans:1,exp:"COPD patients have obstructed airways and are prone to air trapping. Slow ventilation with a longer expiratory phase prevents auto-PEEP and hemodynamic compromise."},
{d:1,q:"A nasopharyngeal airway should be lubricated before insertion to:",opts:["Improve fit","Reduce trauma to the nasal mucosa during insertion","All of the above","None of the above"],ans:1,exp:"Lubrication reduces friction and trauma to the nasal mucosa, minimizing pain, bleeding, and tissue injury during NPA insertion."}
,
{d:1,q:"During CPR, chest compression fraction should be at least:",opts:["40%", "60%", "90%", "50%"],ans:1,exp:"CCF should be at least 60%, ideally above 80%. Minimizing pauses maximizes coronary and cerebral perfusion pressure during resuscitation."},
{d:1,q:"Why is the carotid pulse assessed during adult CPR?",opts:["It is the strongest pulse", "It is most accessible and closest to the heart", "It is the easiest to feel", "It gives the most accurate rate"],ans:1,exp:"The carotid pulse is large, centrally located, and accessible even in the supine position. It remains palpable longer than peripheral pulses in low-output states."},
{d:1,q:"Standard AED pad placement for adults is:",opts:["Both sides of the chest", "Right upper chest below clavicle and left lateral chest", "Both arms", "Upper and lower sternum"],ans:1,exp:"Standard AED placement: right sternal border below the right clavicle, and left lateral chest wall at the 5th intercostal space. This position maximizes current through the heart."},
{d:1,q:"VF survival decreases approximately how much per minute without defibrillation?",opts:["1-2%", "7-10%", "20-25%", "50%"],ans:1,exp:"Every minute of untreated VF reduces survival by approximately 7-10%. This is why early defibrillation is the single most impactful intervention in cardiac arrest."},
{d:1,q:"After AED shock you should immediately:",opts:["Check for a pulse", "Resume CPR starting with compressions", "Check the rhythm", "Give epinephrine"],ans:1,exp:"Resume CPR immediately after shock delivery. Post-shock PEA is common and CPR is needed to generate perfusion pressure for the heart to recover."},
{d:1,q:"Normal sinus rhythm on ECG is characterized by:",opts:["Irregular P waves before each QRS", "Regular rhythm with a P wave before every QRS and normal PR interval", "Wide QRS complexes", "No P waves"],ans:1,exp:"Normal sinus rhythm: regular rate 60-100 bpm, consistent P wave before each QRS, normal PR interval 0.12-0.20 seconds, and normal narrow QRS complex less than 0.12 seconds."},
{d:1,q:"For ACS your first priority interventions are:",opts:["Detailed physical exam first", "12-lead ECG, aspirin, O2 if SpO2 low, IV access, and rapid transport", "Reassurance only", "Wait and see"],ans:1,exp:"ACS management: 12-lead ECG for STEMI identification, aspirin 324mg chewed, supplemental O2 only if SpO2 below 94%, IV access, and rapid transport to a cardiac-capable facility."},
{d:1,q:"Which is a non-shockable cardiac arrest rhythm?",opts:["Ventricular fibrillation", "Pulseless ventricular tachycardia", "Pulseless electrical activity", "Fine VF"],ans:2,exp:"PEA and asystole are non-shockable. They require CPR and treatment of reversible causes. VF and pVT are shockable rhythms that require immediate defibrillation."},
{d:1,q:"Correct infant CPR compression depth is:",opts:["1 inch", "About 1.5 inches or one-third of AP chest diameter", "2 inches", "2.5 inches"],ans:1,exp:"For infants, compress approximately 1.5 inches or 4 cm, which is roughly one-third of the anterior-posterior chest diameter."},
{d:1,q:"When should the AED be applied in cardiac arrest?",opts:["After 30 minutes of CPR", "As soon as it is available", "After epinephrine", "After airway is secured"],ans:1,exp:"Apply the AED as soon as it is available. Every minute without defibrillation in VF or pVT reduces survival. The AED analyzes rhythm and guides the next intervention."},
{d:1,q:"Cardiogenic shock presents with all EXCEPT:",opts:["Hypotension", "JVD and pulmonary crackles", "Warm dry skin and bounding pulse", "Cool clammy skin"],ans:2,exp:"Cardiogenic shock: hypotension, JVD from fluid backup, crackles from pulmonary edema, and cool or clammy skin from low output. Warm dry skin with bounding pulse describes distributive shock."},
{d:1,q:"Routine supplemental oxygen in ACS with SpO2 above 94% is:",opts:["Strongly recommended", "Not recommended and may be harmful", "Only for pain relief", "Required for all chest pain patients"],ans:1,exp:"Current AHA guidelines do not recommend routine supplemental oxygen in ACS patients with SpO2 at or above 94%. Hyperoxia may worsen myocardial injury."},
{d:1,q:"Beck triad in cardiac tamponade includes:",opts:["Hypertension, tachycardia, fever", "Hypotension, muffled heart sounds, JVD", "Chest pain, diaphoresis, nausea", "Bradycardia, hypertension, irregular respirations"],ans:1,exp:"Beck triad: hypotension from reduced cardiac output, muffled heart sounds from pericardial fluid, and JVD from impaired venous return. Caused by compression of the heart in the pericardial sac."},
{d:1,q:"CPR is started when a patient has:",opts:["Weak pulse and shallow breathing", "No pulse AND no normal breathing", "Bradycardia with low BP", "Slow irregular breathing only"],ans:1,exp:"CPR is initiated when a patient has no detectable pulse AND no normal breathing. Agonal gasps are not considered normal breathing."},
{d:1,q:"Synchronized cardioversion differs from defibrillation by:",opts:["Using less energy always", "Delivering a shock timed to the QRS to avoid the vulnerable T-wave period", "Being used for pulseless rhythms", "Not requiring sedation"],ans:1,exp:"Synchronized cardioversion delivers the shock during the QRS complex, avoiding the T-wave vulnerable period that could trigger VF. Defibrillation is unsynchronized and used for pulseless rhythms."},
{d:2,q:"STEMI criteria requires:",opts:["Patient complaint of chest pain alone", "ST elevation of 1mm or more in two contiguous leads or new LBBB", "Any abnormal ECG finding", "Troponin elevation only"],ans:1,exp:"STEMI criteria: ST elevation of at least 1mm in 2 or more contiguous limb leads, or 2mm in precordial leads, or new LBBB in the correct clinical context. Early cath lab activation saves myocardium."},
{d:2,q:"Nitroglycerin must be withheld after PDE-5 inhibitor use because:",opts:["It causes tachycardia", "Combined use causes severe refractory hypotension", "It blocks nitroglycerin absorption", "It causes arrhythmias"],ans:1,exp:"PDE-5 inhibitors such as sildenafil and tadalafil potentiate the vasodilatory effect of nitrates, causing profound and potentially fatal hypotension. This is an absolute contraindication."},
{d:2,q:"ST elevation in leads II, III, and aVF suggests:",opts:["Anterior STEMI", "Inferior STEMI from RCA occlusion", "Lateral STEMI", "Posterior STEMI"],ans:1,exp:"Leads II, III, and aVF reflect the inferior wall supplied by the RCA. Inferior STEMI is associated with bradycardia, AV block, and RV infarction. Avoid nitrates and diuretics."},
{d:2,q:"The Hs and Ts of cardiac arrest identify:",opts:["Types of dysrhythmias", "Reversible causes of PEA and asystole", "Medications for cardiac arrest", "Signs of ROSC"],ans:1,exp:"Hs: Hypoxia, Hypovolemia, Hydrogen ion, Hypo and Hyperkalemia, Hypothermia. Ts: Tension pneumo, Tamponade, Toxins, Thrombosis. Treating these causes can reverse cardiac arrest."},
{d:2,q:"Pulsus paradoxus greater than 10 mmHg suggests:",opts:["Normal variation", "Cardiac tamponade, severe asthma, or tension pneumothorax", "Hypertension", "Aortic regurgitation"],ans:1,exp:"Pulsus paradoxus is an exaggerated drop in systolic BP greater than 10 mmHg during inspiration, indicating conditions that impair cardiac filling with respiration."},
{d:2,q:"Right ventricular MI requires:",opts:["Aggressive diuresis", "IV fluids to maintain preload and avoidance of nitrates and diuretics", "High-dose nitrates", "Immediate cardioversion"],ans:1,exp:"RV infarction is preload-dependent. Vasodilators and diuretics reduce preload and cause severe hypotension. IV fluid boluses are the treatment to maintain RV filling."},
{d:2,q:"Unstable atrial fibrillation with rapid rate requires:",opts:["Rate control medications", "Immediate synchronized cardioversion", "Defibrillation", "Observation"],ans:1,exp:"Unstable A-fib with hypotension, altered mental status, chest pain, or acute pulmonary edema requires immediate synchronized cardioversion."},
{d:2,q:"ROSC is most reliably indicated by:",opts:["Continued effective CPR", "Sudden rise in ETCO2 to 35-40 mmHg", "Fine ventricular fibrillation", "Dilated pupils"],ans:1,exp:"A sudden increase in ETCO2 to 35-40 mmHg during CPR is one of the earliest and most reliable indicators of ROSC as cardiac output resumes CO2 transport to the lungs."},
{d:2,q:"Aspirin in ACS works by:",opts:["Dissolving existing clots", "Inhibiting platelet aggregation to prevent clot growth", "Reducing chest pain directly", "Dilating coronary arteries"],ans:1,exp:"Aspirin irreversibly inhibits cyclooxygenase, reducing thromboxane A2 production and platelet aggregation, limiting further clot propagation in coronary arteries."},
{d:2,q:"Unstable wide complex tachycardia at 180 bpm with hypotension is treated with:",opts:["Adenosine", "Amiodarone IV", "Synchronized cardioversion", "Defibrillation"],ans:2,exp:"Unstable wide complex tachycardia requires immediate synchronized cardioversion. Attempting to identify the exact rhythm before cardioverting wastes critical time."},
{d:3,q:"Wellens syndrome represents:",opts:["Acute inferior MI", "Critical proximal LAD stenosis at high risk for anterior STEMI", "Normal variant", "Complete heart block"],ans:1,exp:"Wellens syndrome: biphasic or deeply inverted T-waves in V2-V3 during a pain-free period indicate significant proximal LAD stenosis with high imminent risk for massive anterior MI."},
{d:3,q:"De Winter T-waves indicate:",opts:["Benign early repolarization", "LAD occlusion STEMI equivalent despite absent ST elevation", "Pericarditis", "Right heart strain"],ans:1,exp:"De Winter T-waves are upsloping ST depression with tall symmetric T-waves in precordial leads plus ST elevation in aVR representing a proximal LAD occlusion requiring emergent intervention."},
{d:3,q:"Targeted temperature management after ROSC targets:",opts:["36-38 degrees C", "32-36 degrees C for 24 hours", "28-32 degrees C", "Normal temperature immediately"],ans:1,exp:"TTM targets 32-36 degrees C for 24 hours post-ROSC to reduce cerebral reperfusion injury and improve neurological outcomes after cardiac arrest."},
{d:3,q:"Electrical alternans on ECG is pathognomonic for:",opts:["Hyperkalemia", "Cardiac tamponade from the heart swinging in a large pericardial effusion", "WPW syndrome", "Myocarditis"],ans:1,exp:"Electrical alternans occurs when the heart swings back and forth in a large pericardial effusion, causing alternating QRS axis and height. Combined with tachycardia and low voltage it strongly suggests tamponade."},
{d:3,q:"Commotio cordis occurs when:",opts:["A patient has a large MI", "A blunt chest impact during the T-wave vulnerable window triggers VF", "Lightning strikes the chest", "Severe hypothermia develops"],ans:1,exp:"Commotio cordis: blunt precordial impact during the narrow T-wave vulnerable period triggers VF without structural cardiac damage. Common in young athletes. Immediate defibrillation is the only treatment."}
],

trauma: [
{d:1,q:"Most effective method to control severe external bleeding is:",opts:["Elevation alone","Pressure bandage","Direct pressure","Tourniquet"],ans:2,exp:"Direct, firm, continuous pressure is the primary method to control external hemorrhage. Tourniquets are used when direct pressure fails or for life-threatening limb bleeding."},
{d:1,q:"A tourniquet should be placed:",opts:["Over a joint","2–3 inches above the wound","Directly over the wound","As distally as possible"],ans:1,exp:"Tourniquets are placed 2–3 inches proximal to the wound (not over a joint) to occlude arterial flow."},
{d:1,q:"Signs of hypovolemic shock include all EXCEPT:",opts:["Tachycardia","Hypotension","Pale/cool/clammy skin","Bradycardia"],ans:3,exp:"Hypovolemic shock causes tachycardia (compensatory), hypotension (late), and pale/cool/clammy skin. Bradycardia is not typical."},
{d:1,q:"A sucking chest wound should be treated with:",opts:["Occlusive dressing on all four sides","Three-sided occlusive dressing","Pressure bandage","Tight circumferential wrap"],ans:1,exp:"A three-sided occlusive dressing creates a flutter valve: seals on inhalation, opens on exhalation — preventing tension pneumothorax."},
{d:1,q:"A closed femur fracture may result in blood loss of up to:",opts:["250 mL","500 mL","1,500 mL","3,000 mL"],ans:2,exp:"Closed femur fractures can cause 1,000–1,500 mL of internal hemorrhage, sufficient to cause significant hypovolemia."},
{d:1,q:"The rule of nines assigns what percentage to an adult's entire leg?",opts:["9%","18%","27%","36%"],ans:1,exp:"Each entire leg = 18% (9% anterior + 9% posterior). The rule of nines estimates TBSA burned."},
{d:1,q:"Evisceration of the bowel should be treated by:",opts:["Pushing organs back in","Dry sterile dressing","Moist sterile dressing","Pressure bandage"],ans:2,exp:"Never push eviscerated organs back in. Cover with a moist sterile dressing, then transport urgently."},
{d:1,q:"A partial-thickness (2nd-degree) burn is characterized by:",opts:["Dry, red, painful skin","Blistering, moist, extremely painful skin","Dry, leathery, painless skin","Charred, insensate skin"],ans:1,exp:"Partial thickness burns involve epidermis and dermis, causing blistering, weeping, and severe pain (nerve endings intact)."},
{d:1,q:"The mechanism of injury (MOI) is important because:",opts:["It determines treatment protocols","It helps predict injury patterns not yet apparent","It establishes legal liability","It determines transport destination"],ans:1,exp:"MOI allows anticipation of hidden injuries based on forces involved, even before physical signs appear."},
{d:1,q:"A sign of tension pneumothorax is:",opts:["Tracheal deviation toward injured side","Tracheal deviation away from injured side","Bilateral absent breath sounds","Hemoptysis"],ans:1,exp:"Accumulated pressure pushes mediastinal structures (trachea) away from the injured side — a late and ominous sign."},
{d:1,q:"Glasgow Coma Scale (GCS) assesses:",opts:["Pupil reactivity, motor strength, sensation","Eye opening, verbal response, motor response","Consciousness, airway, breathing","Blood pressure, pulse, respiratory rate"],ans:1,exp:"GCS measures neurological function via three components: eye opening (1–4), verbal response (1–5), and motor response (1–6). Max = 15, Minimum = 3."},
{d:1,q:"Hemorrhagic shock is classified into four classes. Class III involves estimated blood loss of:",opts:["Up to 750 mL","750–1,500 mL","1,500–2,000 mL",">2,000 mL"],ans:2,exp:"Class III hemorrhage (1,500–2,000 mL, 30–40% blood volume) causes marked tachycardia, tachypnea, decreased BP, and altered mental status."},
{d:1,q:"The primary survey follows the acronym:",opts:["SAMPLE","OPQRST","ABCDE","DCAP-BTLS"],ans:2,exp:"Primary survey: Airway, Breathing, Circulation, Disability (neuro), Expose/Environment — identifies immediately life-threatening conditions."},
{d:1,q:"In trauma, spinal motion restriction is indicated based on:",opts:["Patient age alone","Mechanism of injury and clinical findings","Presence of neck pain only","Protocol — all trauma patients"],ans:1,exp:"Spinal motion restriction is based on clinical criteria: MOI suggesting spinal injury, midline spinal tenderness, neurological deficits, or altered mental status."},
{d:2,q:"A patient with a gunshot wound to the abdomen has a BP of 70/40 mmHg. The highest priority is:",opts:["IV fluid resuscitation","Surgical hemorrhage control (rapid transport)","Detailed assessment","Oxygen therapy"],ans:1,exp:"Penetrating abdominal trauma with hypotension requires rapid transport for surgical hemorrhage control. 'Load and go' — stabilize only what you can en route."},
{d:2,q:"Permissive hypotension in hemorrhagic shock means targeting:",opts:["Normal BP to maintain organ perfusion","Lower-than-normal BP (MAP 50–65 mmHg) to limit further hemorrhage","Zero fluid resuscitation","Vasopressors for BP support"],ans:1,exp:"Permissive hypotension accepts MAP 50–65 mmHg (systolic ~80–90 mmHg) to maintain minimal perfusion while avoiding excess fluid that worsens dilutional coagulopathy and re-bleeds clots."},
{d:2,q:"DCAP-BTLS is used during:",opts:["Primary survey","Rapid trauma assessment/secondary survey","Patient history gathering","Documentation"],ans:1,exp:"DCAP-BTLS (Deformities, Contusions, Abrasions, Punctures/penetrations, Burns, Tenderness, Lacerations, Swelling) guides systematic trauma physical assessment."},
{d:2,q:"An open book pelvic fracture can cause blood loss of up to:",opts:["500 mL","1,000 mL","3,000–4,000 mL","6,000 mL"],ans:2,exp:"Pelvic ring disruptions can cause life-threatening hemorrhage of 3,000–4,000+ mL due to proximity to major vessels and the pelvic venous plexus."},
{d:2,q:"Traumatic brain injury (TBI) management should avoid:",opts:["Supplemental oxygen","Spinal motion restriction","Hypotension and hypoxia","Rapid transport"],ans:2,exp:"Hypotension (SBP <90 mmHg) and hypoxia (SpO₂ <90%) each independently worsen TBI outcomes. Maintain adequate BP and oxygenation aggressively."},
{d:2,q:"A tension pneumothorax in a trauma patient is treated prehospitally by:",opts:["Oxygen and observation","Needle decompression","Chest tube insertion","Intubation"],ans:1,exp:"Needle thoracostomy (2nd ICS, MCL or 4th–5th ICS, AAL) is the prehospital treatment for tension pneumothorax. Formal chest tube is placed in-hospital."},
{d:2,q:"Cullen's sign (periumbilical bruising) indicates:",opts:["Pelvic fracture","Retroperitoneal or intraabdominal hemorrhage","Aortic dissection","Hepatic injury"],ans:1,exp:"Cullen's sign (periumbilical ecchymosis) and Grey Turner's sign (flank bruising) indicate retroperitoneal hemorrhage, often from pancreatic injury or abdominal aortic rupture."},
{d:2,q:"A patient has a knife impaled in the chest. You should:",opts:["Remove it and apply pressure","Stabilize it in place and transport","Push it in further to control bleeding","Apply circumferential bandage"],ans:1,exp:"Impaled objects should never be removed in the field — they may be tamponading a vessel. Stabilize in place and transport."},
{d:2,q:"In a high-energy MVC, which injury pattern is associated with unrestrained front-seat occupants?",opts:["Lap belt injuries","Down-and-under pathway (knees/femur) or up-and-over pathway (chest/head)","Cervical hyperextension only","Isolated limb fractures"],ans:1,exp:"Unrestrained front-seat occupants travel along down-and-under (striking dash: knees, femur, hip) or up-and-over (striking wheel/windshield: chest, head, C-spine) pathways."},
{d:3,q:"In hemorrhagic shock, the last vital sign to change is:",opts:["Heart rate","Respiratory rate","Blood pressure","Skin color"],ans:2,exp:"Blood pressure is maintained until 30–40% of blood volume is lost (Class III). Early shock presents with tachycardia, anxiety, and pale skin before hypotension develops."},
{d:3,q:"Damage control resuscitation includes which principle?",opts:["Aggressive crystalloid administration","1:1:1 ratio of PRBCs:FFP:Platelets","Normal saline as primary resuscitation fluid","Avoid blood products until BP is <60"],ans:1,exp:"Damage control resuscitation uses balanced blood product resuscitation (1:1:1 PRBCs:FFP:Platelets) to restore all coagulation components and prevent trauma-induced coagulopathy."},
{d:3,q:"The lethal triad in trauma consists of:",opts:["Hypoxia, hypotension, hypovolemia","Hypothermia, acidosis, coagulopathy","Hyperthermia, alkalosis, thrombocytopenia","Hyperglycemia, hyponatremia, hypothermia"],ans:1,exp:"The lethal triad — hypothermia, acidosis, and coagulopathy — is a self-perpetuating cycle in severe trauma. Each worsens the others, leading to refractory hemorrhage."},
{d:3,q:"Tranexamic acid (TXA) in trauma is most effective when given:",opts:["Within 30 minutes","Within 3 hours of injury","Any time during resuscitation","Only post-operatively"],ans:1,exp:"The CRASH-2 trial showed TXA (an antifibrinolytic) significantly reduces mortality when given within 3 hours of injury. Benefit diminishes after 3 hours; it may be harmful after 4–6 hours."},
{d:3,q:"A patient with a spinal cord injury at C4 will likely require:",opts:["Lower extremity rehabilitation only","Permanent mechanical ventilation support","Partial diaphragm function — may need ventilatory support","Full independence with assistive devices"],ans:2,exp:"The phrenic nerve (C3–C5) innervates the diaphragm. C4 injury may spare some phrenic function, but respiratory failure is common and ventilatory support is often required."},
,
{d:1,q:"The primary survey in trauma is designed to identify and treat:",opts:["All injuries systematically","Immediately life-threatening conditions","Chronic conditions","Social history"],ans:1,exp:"The primary survey (ABCDE) rapidly identifies and treats life-threatening conditions in priority order. It is performed before the secondary survey."},
{d:1,q:"In blunt abdominal trauma, the organ most commonly injured is:",opts:["Stomach","Liver and spleen","Kidneys","Bladder"],ans:1,exp:"The spleen and liver are the most commonly injured abdominal organs in blunt trauma due to their size and relatively fixed positions. The spleen is most commonly ruptured in sport injuries."},
{d:1,q:"Pneumothorax means:",opts:["Air in the pericardial sac","Air in the pleural space","Blood in the pleural space","Fluid in the pericardial sac"],ans:1,exp:"Pneumothorax: air enters the pleural space (between lung and chest wall), causing lung collapse. It can be simple (non-tension) or tension (life-threatening with pressure buildup)."},
{d:1,q:"A flail chest is caused by:",opts:["A single rib fracture","Two or more ribs fractured in two or more places, creating a free-floating segment","Fracture of the sternum only","Hemothorax"],ans:1,exp:"Flail chest: multiple rib fractures creating a chest segment that moves paradoxically (opposite to normal respiratory movement). Underlying pulmonary contusion is the primary threat."},
{d:1,q:"Hemothorax is blood accumulating in:",opts:["The pericardial sac","The pleural space","The peritoneal cavity","The chest wall muscles"],ans:1,exp:"Hemothorax: blood in the pleural space from chest wall, pulmonary, or great vessel injury. A massive hemothorax (>1,500 mL) causes both hemorrhagic shock and respiratory compromise."},
{d:1,q:"Seat belt injuries in MVC are associated with which abdominal injury?",opts:["Liver laceration only","Hollow organ (bowel) injuries and lumbar spine fractures","Kidney contusion","Splenic rupture only"],ans:1,exp:"Lap belt injuries can cause bowel perforation (from crushing against the spine) and Chance fractures (flexion-distraction lumbar spine fractures). Always look for the seat belt sign."},
{d:1,q:"What does 'mechanism of injury' tell the EMT?",opts:["The patient's past medical history","Forces involved and potential injury patterns","Transport priority","Scene safety information only"],ans:1,exp:"MOI describes the forces applied to the body, helping predict injury patterns before all signs are apparent. High-energy MOI = high index of suspicion for serious injuries."},
{d:1,q:"The preferred fluid for initial resuscitation of hemorrhagic shock in EMS is:",opts:["D5W","Normal saline or lactated Ringer's solution","Dextran","Albumin"],ans:1,exp:"Isotonic crystalloids (normal saline or lactated Ringer's) are the standard prehospital resuscitation fluids for hemorrhagic shock. Blood products are preferred when available."},
{d:1,q:"A 'battle sign' indicates:",opts:["Periorbital bruising","Bruising over the mastoid process — suggests basilar skull fracture","A positive Kernig's sign","Abdominal rigidity"],ans:1,exp:"Battle's sign: retroauricular (behind the ear, over the mastoid) ecchymosis from basilar skull fracture. Raccoon eyes (periorbital bruising) is also a delayed sign of basilar skull fracture."},
{d:1,q:"When is a pressure dressing used instead of a tourniquet for extremity bleeding?",opts:["Never — always use tourniquet first","When direct pressure alone fails but the wound is not life-threatening and is in a location unsuitable for tourniquet","Always — pressure dressings are preferred","Only for arterial bleeding"],ans:1,exp:"Pressure dressings are used when bleeding is not immediately life-threatening or the wound is in a location where tourniquet is not feasible (proximal extremity/junction areas). Life-threatening limb bleeding gets an immediate tourniquet."},
{d:2,q:"A trauma patient with absent breath sounds on the right, hypotension, tracheal deviation left, and JVD has:",opts:["Right hemothorax","Right tension pneumothorax","Cardiac tamponade","Right pneumothorax without tension"],ans:1,exp:"Tension pneumothorax: absent breath sounds on the affected side, hypotension (impaired cardiac output), tracheal deviation AWAY from the injury, and JVD (impaired venous return). Requires immediate needle decompression."},
{d:2,q:"A stab wound to the left side of the chest with hypotension, muffled heart sounds, and JVD indicates:",opts:["Left tension pneumothorax","Cardiac tamponade (penetrating)","Left hemothorax","Myocardial contusion"],ans:1,exp:"Beck's triad in penetrating trauma (stab to the cardiac box): hypotension, muffled heart sounds, JVD. Pericardiocentesis or emergency thoracotomy may be required."},
{d:2,q:"A patient with a traumatic amputation has active arterial bleeding. Your immediate action is:",opts:["Direct pressure and elevation","Apply tourniquet proximal to the amputation","Wrap the stump tightly","Apply ice to the stump"],ans:1,exp:"Traumatic amputation with arterial bleeding requires immediate tourniquet application 2–3 inches above the amputation — direct pressure is inadequate for amputations."},
{d:2,q:"Spinal cord injury at T4 and above causes neurogenic shock because:",opts:["Blood loss is severe","Loss of sympathetic tone causes vasodilation and bradycardia","Pain causes vasovagal response","Blood pressure regulation is centrally impaired"],ans:1,exp:"High thoracic/cervical spinal cord injury disrupts sympathetic outflow (T1–L2), causing loss of vascular tone (vasodilation, hypotension) and loss of cardiac acceleration — resulting in bradycardia + hypotension (neurogenic shock)."},
{d:2,q:"During transport of a TBI patient, you should avoid:",opts:["SpO₂ >98%","Hypotension (SBP <90 mmHg) and hypoxia","Supplemental O₂","Rapid transport"],ans:1,exp:"Secondary brain injury is worsened by hypotension (impairs cerebral perfusion) and hypoxia (increases ischemic injury). Maintain SBP >90 mmHg and SpO₂ >95%."},
{d:3,q:"The concept of 'damage control surgery' parallels prehospital 'damage control resuscitation,' which means:",opts:["Full surgical repair in the field","Stopping the bleed and restoring physiology before definitive repair","Delaying all treatment until hospital","Using maximal IV fluids"],ans:1,exp:"Damage control resuscitation: stop hemorrhage (tourniquet, pressure), restore coagulation (blood products, TXA), avoid hypothermia/acidosis, and get to the operating room quickly rather than attempting full correction prehospitally."},
{d:3,q:"Traumatic asphyxia presents with which characteristic signs?",opts:["Tracheal deviation and JVD","Cyanosis of the face, neck, and upper chest with subconjunctival hemorrhage","Pale, cool, clammy skin with tachycardia","Kussmaul respirations"],ans:1,exp:"Traumatic asphyxia from severe compressive thoracic trauma (e.g., crush injury) forces blood retrograde into the head and neck, causing characteristic cyanosis, subconjunctival hemorrhage, and facial petechiae."},
,
{d:1,q:"The normal PR interval on an ECG is:",opts:["Less than 0.08 seconds","0.12 to 0.20 seconds","0.20 to 0.40 seconds","Greater than 0.40 seconds"],ans:1,exp:"Normal PR interval: 0.12-0.20 seconds. Greater than 0.20 seconds indicates first-degree heart block. Less than 0.12 seconds may indicate pre-excitation as in WPW."},
{d:1,q:"Ventricular fibrillation on ECG shows:",opts:["Organized rapid electrical activity","Chaotic disorganized electrical activity with no effective contraction","Complete absence of electrical activity","Regular rhythm at 300 bpm"],ans:1,exp:"V-fib is completely disorganized electrical activity. The myocardium quivers without effective contraction producing no cardiac output. Immediate defibrillation required."},
{d:1,q:"The brachial pulse is used to assess pulse in:",opts:["Adults","Infants because the carotid is difficult to palpate","Toddlers","All patients"],ans:1,exp:"The brachial pulse in the medial upper arm is used for infants because their short necks make carotid pulse assessment difficult."},
{d:2,q:"Stable PSVT may be initially treated with:",opts:["Immediate cardioversion","Vagal maneuvers such as Valsalva or carotid massage if allowed","High-flow oxygen alone","Epinephrine IV"],ans:1,exp:"Stable PSVT initial treatment: vagal maneuvers including cough, Valsalva, or bearing down. If unsuccessful, adenosine may be used per protocol. Unstable PSVT requires synchronized cardioversion."},
{d:2,q:"First-degree AV block is characterized by:",opts:["Some P waves not conducted","Prolonged PR interval greater than 0.20 seconds with all P waves conducted","Dropped QRS complexes","No P waves visible"],ans:1,exp:"First-degree AV block: prolonged PR interval greater than 0.20 seconds with every P wave followed by a QRS. Delayed but intact conduction. Usually benign and requires no treatment."},
{d:2,q:"Mobitz Type II second-degree AV block is dangerous because:",opts:["It always converts to first-degree block","It can progress unpredictably to complete third-degree heart block","It causes immediate cardiac arrest","It only occurs in athletes"],ans:1,exp:"Mobitz Type II: intermittent non-conducted P waves without prior PR lengthening. Can suddenly progress to complete heart block. Transcutaneous pacing may be required."},
{d:1,q:"An AED pad should NOT be placed over:",opts:["The left lateral chest wall","An implanted cardiac device or medication patch","The right upper chest","Any hairless area"],ans:1,exp:"Pads placed over implanted devices or medication patches may reduce effectiveness or cause skin burns. Place pads at least one inch away from implanted devices."},
{d:2,q:"Atrial fibrillation with rapid ventricular rate in an UNSTABLE patient is treated with:",opts:["Rate-control medications like diltiazem","Synchronized cardioversion","Defibrillation","Observation and monitoring"],ans:1,exp:"Unstable A-fib with hypotension, AMS, acute pulmonary edema, or severe chest pain is treated with immediate synchronized cardioversion. Stable A-fib is managed with rate control medications."},
{d:3,q:"Commotio cordis is caused by:",opts:["Electrical shock from power lines","Blunt precordial impact during the vulnerable T-wave period triggering VF","Penetrating chest trauma","Myocarditis"],ans:1,exp:"Commotio cordis: blunt chest impact during the vulnerable T-wave window triggers VF. Common in young athletes struck by projectiles. Immediate defibrillation is the only treatment."},
{d:3,q:"Post-ROSC care should avoid which of the following?",opts:["SpO2 greater than 94 percent","Hyperventilation — over-breathing causes cerebral vasoconstriction and worsens outcome","SBP greater than 90 mmHg","Passive rewarming"],ans:1,exp:"Post-ROSC: avoid hyperventilation — target normal ETCO2 of 35-45 mmHg. Hyperventilation causes cerebral vasoconstriction and worsens neurological outcomes after cardiac arrest."},
{d:2,q:"Torsades de Pointes is associated with:",opts:["Hyperkalemia","Prolonged QT interval from electrolyte disturbances or drugs","Short QRS complex","Normal QT interval"],ans:1,exp:"Torsades de Pointes is associated with prolonged QT interval from hypokalemia, hypomagnesemia, certain drugs, or congenital channelopathies. Treatment includes magnesium sulfate."},
{d:1,q:"Pulseless electrical activity requires treatment of:",opts:["Immediate defibrillation","The underlying reversible cause while performing CPR","Synchronized cardioversion","Atropine only"],ans:1,exp:"PEA has organized electrical activity but no pulse. CPR continues while identifying and treating reversible causes using the H and T framework. Defibrillation is not indicated."},
{d:2,q:"WPW syndrome on ECG shows:",opts:["Long QT interval","Short PR interval with a delta wave — slurred QRS upstroke","Deep Q waves","ST depression in all leads"],ans:1,exp:"WPW: accessory pathway bypasses the AV node producing short PR, delta wave, and wide QRS. Risk of rapid SVT and potentially lethal conduction during atrial fibrillation."},
{d:1,q:"Cardiogenic shock is distinguished from hypovolemic shock by:",opts:["Identical presentation","Cardiogenic shock has JVD, pulmonary edema, and warm or cool extremities depending on phase — not improved by fluids","Faster heart rate","Lower blood pressure"],ans:1,exp:"Cardiogenic shock: pump failure causes both pulmonary congestion (JVD, crackles) and reduced output (hypotension, pallor). Aggressive fluids worsen pulmonary edema unlike hypovolemic shock."},
{d:2,q:"The recommended ETCO2 target during CPR to assess compression quality is:",opts:["Less than 10 mmHg","Greater than 10 mmHg indicating reasonable compressions","Greater than 40 mmHg","Zero mmHg"],ans:1,exp:"ETCO2 greater than 10 mmHg during CPR suggests adequate cardiac output from compressions. A sudden rise to 35-40 mmHg during CPR is a reliable indicator of ROSC."}
,
{d:1,q:"Sinus bradycardia in a symptomatic patient (hypotensive, AMS) is treated prehospitally with:",opts:["Observation only","Atropine 0.5 mg IV per protocol and transcutaneous pacing if refractory","All of the above","None of the above"],ans:1,exp:"Symptomatic sinus bradycardia: atropine 0.5 mg IV (repeat up to 3 mg total). If refractory, transcutaneous pacing (TCP) is the bridge to definitive transvenous pacing."},
{d:1,q:"The purpose of the AED analyze phase is to:",opts:["Measure blood pressure","Detect the presence of a shockable rhythm before delivering energy","All of the above","None of the above"],ans:1,exp:"The AED analyze phase uses an algorithm to detect VF or pulseless VT. It must complete without interruption — movement or CPR during analysis produces artifact and false readings."},
{d:2,q:"Right ventricular MI patients should avoid nitroglycerin because:",opts:["It causes tachycardia","The RV is preload-dependent — vasodilation causes severe refractory hypotension","All of the above","None of the above"],ans:1,exp:"RV infarction requires adequate preload to maintain cardiac output. Nitroglycerin and diuretics reduce preload and can cause profound hypotension. IV fluids are the treatment."},
{d:1,q:"Atropine works in symptomatic bradycardia by:",opts:["Directly stimulating the SA node","Blocking vagal (parasympathetic) tone, allowing the SA node to increase its rate","All of the above","None of the above"],ans:1,exp:"Atropine is an anticholinergic that blocks the muscarinic receptors of the vagus nerve, removing parasympathetic suppression and allowing the intrinsic heart rate to increase."},
{d:2,q:"The universal do not shock rhythm in cardiac arrest is:",opts:["Ventricular fibrillation","Asystole and PEA — non-shockable rhythms require CPR and treatment of reversible causes","All of the above","None of the above"],ans:1,exp:"Asystole and PEA are non-shockable. Defibrillation requires a chaotic electrical substrate to reset. There is nothing to reset in asystole and PEA. CPR and H and T management are the treatments."}
,
{d:1,q:"Class II hemorrhagic shock involves estimated blood loss of:",opts:["Up to 750 mL", "750-1500 mL", "1500-2000 mL", "More than 2000 mL"],ans:1,exp:"Class II hemorrhage (750-1500 mL, 15-30% blood volume) causes tachycardia, tachypnea, decreased pulse pressure, and anxiety. Blood pressure is maintained by compensatory vasoconstriction."},
{d:1,q:"Immediate treatment for femoral artery hemorrhage is:",opts:["Elevation only", "Tourniquet application 2-3 inches above the wound", "Wound packing alone", "Direct pressure for 30 minutes"],ans:1,exp:"Life-threatening extremity hemorrhage requires immediate tourniquet application. Note the time of application. Tourniquets applied early save lives."},
{d:1,q:"Maximum GCS score is:",opts:["10", "12", "15", "20"],ans:2,exp:"Maximum GCS is 15: Eye opening 4 plus Verbal 5 plus Motor 6 equals 15. Minimum is 3. GCS 8 or below indicates severe TBI and inability to protect the airway."},
{d:1,q:"A seat belt sign across the abdomen raises concern for:",opts:["Only soft tissue bruising", "Hollow organ injury and lumbar spine fractures", "Kidney laceration only", "Liver injury only"],ans:1,exp:"The lap belt concentrates force over the lower abdomen, causing bowel perforation, mesenteric tears, and Chance fractures of the lumbar vertebrae."},
{d:1,q:"A flail chest segment moves:",opts:["With the rest of the chest", "Paradoxically inward on inspiration and outward on exhalation", "Only during coughing", "Only on expiration"],ans:1,exp:"A flail segment with 2 or more ribs fractured in 2 or more places moves opposite to the chest wall due to negative intrapleural pressure. Underlying pulmonary contusion is the primary threat."},
{d:1,q:"DCAP-BTLS stands for:",opts:["A medication list", "Deformities, Contusions, Abrasions, Punctures, Burns, Tenderness, Lacerations, Swelling", "A vital sign assessment", "A documentation tool"],ans:1,exp:"DCAP-BTLS is a systematic physical assessment tool used during the rapid trauma survey to find all injuries."},
{d:1,q:"An impaled object should be:",opts:["Removed if in the extremity", "Stabilized in place and never removed in the field", "Pushed deeper to control bleeding", "Removed only if it impairs the airway"],ans:1,exp:"Never remove impaled objects in the field as they may be tamponading blood vessels. Stabilize in place with bulky dressings and transport. Exception: objects impeding the airway."},
{d:1,q:"Chemical burns should be treated with:",opts:["Neutralizing acid or base", "Copious water irrigation for at least 20 minutes", "Dry dressings only", "Ice packs"],ans:1,exp:"Neutralizing agents cause additional thermal injury from the exothermic reaction. Copious water irrigation for at least 20 minutes dilutes and removes the chemical agent most safely."},
{d:1,q:"The primary goal of traction splinting for femur fracture is:",opts:["Realigning the bone", "Reducing blood loss and muscle spasm by restoring normal length", "Preventing infection", "Allowing the patient to walk"],ans:1,exp:"Femur fractures can cause 1000-1500 mL of blood loss and severe muscle spasm. Traction splinting restores normal bone length, reduces hemorrhage potential, and relieves pain."},
{d:1,q:"Burns covering face, neck, and anterior chest are approximately what TBSA?",opts:["9%", "18%", "27%", "4.5%"],ans:1,exp:"Using rule of nines: anterior head and neck approximately 9%, anterior chest 9%, totaling approximately 18% TBSA. Facial burns also carry high risk of inhalation injury."},
{d:1,q:"Primary blast injury is caused by:",opts:["Flying debris", "The pressure wave directly affecting air-filled organs", "The body being thrown by the blast", "Burns from the explosion"],ans:1,exp:"Primary blast injury is caused by the pressure wave (barotrauma) and affects air-filled organs: lungs causing blast lung, GI tract, and ears causing tympanic membrane rupture."},
{d:1,q:"An open pneumothorax (sucking chest wound) occurs when:",opts:["Internal air from a ruptured alveolus", "Air enters the pleural space through a chest wall defect with each breath", "Hemothorax only", "Broken ribs alone"],ans:1,exp:"An open pneumothorax occurs when a chest wall defect allows air to enter and exit the pleural space during ventilation, creating the characteristic sucking sound and impairing respiratory mechanics."},
{d:1,q:"Diving accidents most commonly cause which spinal injury pattern?",opts:["Lumbar compression", "Cervical hyperflexion or hyperextension", "Thoracic rotation", "All spinal levels equally"],ans:1,exp:"Diving into shallow water causes forceful cervical hyperflexion or hyperextension against the bottom, commonly causing cervical fracture-dislocation and spinal cord injury."},
{d:1,q:"Battle sign (retroauricular bruising) is a delayed sign of:",opts:["Temporal bone contusion", "Basilar skull fracture", "Middle ear infection", "Mandible fracture"],ans:1,exp:"Battle sign appears 12-24 hours after basilar skull fracture indicating bleeding tracking into the mastoid air cells. Also look for raccoon eyes and CSF otorrhea or rhinorrhea."},
{d:1,q:"Neurogenic shock is characterized by:",opts:["Tachycardia and vasoconstriction", "Hypotension with bradycardia and warm skin from loss of sympathetic tone", "Hypotension and cold clammy skin", "Hypertension and bradycardia"],ans:1,exp:"High thoracic or cervical spinal cord injury disrupts sympathetic outflow causing vasodilation with warm skin, hypotension, and paradoxical bradycardia, unlike hypovolemic shock which causes tachycardia."},
{d:2,q:"Permissive hypotension in penetrating hemorrhagic shock means targeting:",opts:["Normal BP", "SBP 80-90 mmHg until surgical hemorrhage control", "Zero fluid resuscitation", "SBP below 60 mmHg"],ans:1,exp:"Permissive hypotension accepts SBP 80-90 mmHg until surgical hemorrhage control. Aggressive fluid resuscitation worsens coagulopathy and re-bleeds fresh clots."},
{d:2,q:"The lethal triad in severe trauma consists of:",opts:["Hypoxia, hypotension, hypovolemia", "Hypothermia, acidosis, and coagulopathy", "Hypertension, alkalosis, thrombocytopenia", "Hyperglycemia, hyponatremia, hypothermia"],ans:1,exp:"The lethal triad: hypothermia, acidosis, and coagulopathy are self-reinforcing and each worsens the others. This triad causes refractory hemorrhage and death."},
{d:2,q:"Tranexamic acid is most effective when given:",opts:["Within 30 minutes of injury", "Within 3 hours of injury", "Any time during resuscitation", "Only post-operatively"],ans:1,exp:"TXA significantly reduces mortality when given within 3 hours of injury. After 3 hours the benefit diminishes and after 6 hours it may increase bleeding risk."},
{d:2,q:"A pelvic binder is most effective for:",opts:["Vertical shear pelvic fracture", "Open-book AP compression pelvic fracture", "Isolated acetabular fracture", "Lateral compression fracture"],ans:1,exp:"Pelvic binders reduce pelvic ring volume in open-book fractures where the symphysis is disrupted. They tamponade venous hemorrhage by restoring pelvic volume."},
{d:2,q:"C5 spinal cord injury affects which function?",opts:["Only sensory below the neck", "Motor function of deltoids and biceps with some limited arm movement", "Full respiratory function requiring ventilator support", "No significant function"],ans:1,exp:"C5 controls deltoids and biceps. Injuries at C5 may spare some shoulder and elbow flexion. C3-C4 injuries affect the phrenic nerve and may compromise diaphragm function."},
{d:2,q:"Blast lung from primary blast injury presents with:",opts:["Concussion only", "Hemoptysis, hypoxia, and bilateral pulmonary infiltrates", "Secondary fragmentation injury", "Quaternary burns"],ans:1,exp:"Blast lung is the most lethal primary blast injury. Air-filled lungs are particularly susceptible to pressure waves. Hemoptysis, hypoxia, and bilateral infiltrates may develop within 48 hours."},
{d:2,q:"Traumatic asphyxia presents with:",opts:["Tracheal deviation", "Cyanosis and petechiae of face and upper chest from venous backflow", "Hemoptysis and pneumothorax", "Abdominal rigidity"],ans:1,exp:"Severe compressive thoracic trauma forces blood retrograde into the head and neck, causing cyanosis, subconjunctival hemorrhage, facial petechiae, and a characteristic plethoric appearance."},
{d:2,q:"The most critical cause of secondary brain injury after TBI is:",opts:["Hyperglycemia", "Hypotension and hypoxia each independently worsening outcomes", "Hyperthermia alone", "Seizures"],ans:1,exp:"Hypotension with SBP below 90 mmHg and hypoxia with SpO2 below 90% are the two most critical causes of secondary brain injury. Each doubles mortality when present after TBI."},
{d:2,q:"Damage control resuscitation uses which blood product ratio?",opts:["PRBCs only", "1:1:1 PRBCs to FFP to Platelets", "4:1:1 PRBCs to FFP to Platelets", "Crystalloids only"],ans:1,exp:"1:1:1 balanced transfusion replaces red cells, clotting factors, and platelets simultaneously, preventing trauma-induced coagulopathy and dilutional effects of giving only packed red cells."},
{d:3,q:"FAST exam in trauma detects:",opts:["Rib fractures", "Free fluid in pericardial, hepatorenal, splenorenal, and pelvic spaces", "Pneumothorax only", "Aortic injury"],ans:1,exp:"FAST provides four windows looking for free fluid indicating hemorrhage. Extended FAST adds bilateral pleural windows for pneumothorax detection."},
{d:3,q:"C4 spinal cord injury will likely require:",opts:["Lower extremity rehab only", "Ventilatory support as C3-C5 innervates the phrenic nerve and diaphragm", "Full independence with devices", "Only pain management"],ans:1,exp:"The phrenic nerve originates from C3-C5. Injuries at or above C4 may compromise or eliminate diaphragm function requiring mechanical ventilation."},
{d:3,q:"Zone II neck injury carries high risk for:",opts:["Esophageal injury only", "Vascular, airway, and esophageal injuries", "Spinal cord injury only", "Brachial plexus injury only"],ans:1,exp:"Zone II is the most vulnerable neck zone. Injuries here risk the carotid artery, jugular vein, trachea, larynx, esophagus, and spinal cord."},
{d:3,q:"Compartment syndrome requires fasciotomy when compartment pressure reaches:",opts:["10 mmHg", "30 mmHg or within 30 mmHg of diastolic BP", "50 mmHg", "Any elevation above normal"],ans:1,exp:"Compartment syndrome: pressure above 30 mmHg or within 30 mmHg of diastolic pressure causes neurovascular compromise. Fasciotomy is emergent. The 6 Ps are Pain, Pressure, Pallor, Paresthesia, Paralysis, and Pulselessness."}
],

medical: [
{d:1,q:"The Cincinnati Prehospital Stroke Scale assesses:",opts:["Level of consciousness, pupils, vital signs","Facial droop, arm drift, speech abnormality","Pupils, reflexes, motor strength","Blood pressure, pulse, temperature"],ans:1,exp:"CPSS uses three findings: facial droop, arm drift, and abnormal speech. One abnormal finding = 72% probability of stroke."},
{d:1,q:"Hypoglycemia is generally defined as blood glucose below:",opts:["50 mg/dL","60 mg/dL","70 mg/dL","80 mg/dL"],ans:2,exp:"Most protocols define hypoglycemia as BGL <70 mg/dL. Treat before levels drop further."},
{d:1,q:"Status epilepticus is defined as:",opts:["Any seizure >2 minutes","Seizure >5 min or two seizures without regaining consciousness","Any tonic-clonic seizure","Seizures from hypoglycemia"],ans:1,exp:"Status epilepticus: seizure lasting >5 minutes, or recurrent seizures without regaining consciousness. Requires immediate intervention."},
{d:1,q:"Heat stroke presents with:",opts:["Pale, cool, moist skin; normal mental status","Hot/dry/flushed skin, altered mental status, hyperthermia","Profuse sweating, weakness, normal temperature","Cool, clammy skin, confusion, mild hyperthermia"],ans:1,exp:"Heat stroke: hot/dry/flushed skin, AMS, temperature >104°F. The cooling mechanism has failed — life-threatening emergency."},
{d:1,q:"First-line treatment for anaphylaxis in the prehospital setting is:",opts:["Diphenhydramine IM","Albuterol nebulization","Epinephrine 1:1,000 IM","Corticosteroids IV"],ans:2,exp:"Epinephrine 1:1,000 IM (anterolateral thigh) is first-line for anaphylaxis, reversing bronchospasm and vasodilation rapidly."},
{d:1,q:"SAMPLE history stands for:",opts:["Signs/Symptoms, Allergies, Medications, Pertinent history, Last oral intake, Events","Scene, Airway, Monitor, Pupils, Labs, Exam","Sex, Age, Medical history, Pulse, Level, Exam","None of the above"],ans:0,exp:"SAMPLE: Signs/Symptoms, Allergies, Medications, Pertinent history, Last oral intake, Events leading to illness."},
{d:1,q:"DKA is characterized by:",opts:["Cold clammy skin","Kussmaul breathing and fruity breath","Pinpoint pupils","Hypertension"],ans:1,exp:"DKA causes deep, rapid Kussmaul respirations and acetone/fruity odor from ketone production."},
{d:1,q:"Opioid toxidrome presents with:",opts:["Tachycardia, hyperthermia, dilated pupils","Pinpoint pupils, respiratory depression, altered consciousness","Tachycardia, diaphoresis, anxiety","Bradycardia, hypertension, bradypnea"],ans:1,exp:"Opioid toxidrome: pinpoint pupils, respiratory depression, AMS. Naloxone is the reversal agent."},
{d:1,q:"Nitroglycerin should NOT be given to a chest pain patient who:",opts:["Has BP >160 mmHg","Took sildenafil (Viagra) within 24–48 hours","Has HR >100","Is diaphoretic"],ans:1,exp:"Nitrates combined with PDE-5 inhibitors cause severe refractory hypotension — absolute contraindication."},
{d:1,q:"OPQRST is used to:",opts:["Assess mental status","Characterize a patient's pain or chief complaint","Document vital signs","Assess respiratory quality"],ans:1,exp:"OPQRST — Onset, Provocation, Quality, Radiation, Severity, Time — fully characterizes pain or chief complaint."},
{d:1,q:"A patient with altered mental status and a blood glucose of 40 mg/dL should receive:",opts:["Nothing by mouth","Oral glucose if they can swallow","Insulin","IV epinephrine"],ans:1,exp:"If the patient can protect their airway and swallow, oral glucose is appropriate. If unconscious or unable to swallow, dextrose IV or glucagon IM is used."},
{d:1,q:"The classic triad of a diabetic emergency includes:",opts:["Polyuria, polydipsia, polyphagia","Headache, chest pain, diaphoresis","Fever, confusion, stiff neck","Dyspnea, cough, hemoptysis"],ans:0,exp:"The classic triad of hyperglycemia: polyuria (excessive urination), polydipsia (excessive thirst), and polyphagia (excessive hunger)."},
{d:1,q:"A patient with asthma who is not responding to initial bronchodilators and has a silent chest is:",opts:["Improving","In mild distress","In severe, life-threatening bronchospasm","Normal for asthma"],ans:2,exp:"A silent chest in asthma indicates no air movement — the patient is in severe respiratory failure. Positive pressure ventilation and rapid transport are required."},
{d:1,q:"Wheezing on auscultation is caused by:",opts:["Upper airway obstruction","Narrowing of the lower airways (bronchospasm)","Fluid in the alveoli","Normal breath sounds"],ans:1,exp:"Wheezing results from turbulent airflow through narrowed lower airways — seen in asthma, COPD, anaphylaxis, and CHF."},
{d:2,q:"A patient with ALOC, high blood glucose, and no ketones on urine dipstick most likely has:",opts:["DKA","Hyperosmolar Hyperglycemic State (HHS)","Addisonian crisis","Thyroid storm"],ans:1,exp:"HHS (formerly HONK) occurs in type 2 DM — extreme hyperglycemia (often >600 mg/dL), severe dehydration, AMS, but minimal ketosis unlike DKA."},
{d:2,q:"The Cushing's reflex (triad) in TBI includes:",opts:["Tachycardia, hypotension, tachypnea","Hypertension, bradycardia, irregular respirations","Hypotension, bradycardia, apnea","Tachycardia, hypertension, miosis"],ans:1,exp:"Cushing's triad (hypertension, bradycardia, irregular respirations) indicates severely elevated intracranial pressure with brainstem herniation — a late and ominous sign."},
{d:2,q:"Which intervention is a priority for a suspected stroke patient en route to the hospital?",opts:["Administer aspirin","Check and treat blood glucose","Begin IV fluid bolus","Apply ice packs"],ans:1,exp:"Hypoglycemia mimics stroke. Always check blood glucose in suspected stroke patients. Hypoglycemia requires immediate correction; tPA cannot be given if stroke is actually hypoglycemia."},
{d:2,q:"A patient on dialysis collapses. His ECG shows peaked T-waves and wide QRS. You suspect:",opts:["STEMI","Hyperkalemia","Hyponatremia","Hyperglycemia"],ans:1,exp:"Hyperkalemia ECG changes: peaked/narrow T-waves → PR prolongation → wide QRS → sine wave → asystole. Dialysis patients are at high risk."},
{d:2,q:"Anaphylaxis with persistent hypotension after epinephrine should be treated with:",opts:["Repeat epinephrine + IV fluid bolus","Diphenhydramine alone","High-flow oxygen only","Repeat corticosteroids"],ans:0,exp:"Repeat epinephrine q5–15 min and aggressive IV fluid resuscitation (1–2L normal saline bolus) address the distributive shock of anaphylaxis."},
{d:2,q:"Meningitis in a patient presents with fever, stiff neck, and altered mental status — you should also look for:",opts:["Petechial or purpuric rash","Jaundice","Papilledema","Hematuria"],ans:0,exp:"A non-blanching petechial or purpuric rash suggests meningococcal meningitis — a life-threatening emergency. Initiate antibiotics (if in-scope) and transport rapidly."},
{d:2,q:"In a patient with chest pain, which finding most strongly suggests aortic dissection?",opts:["Gradual onset pressure radiating to the left arm","Tearing/ripping pain radiating to the back with BP differential between arms","Crushing substernal pain with diaphoresis","Pleuritic chest pain worse with breathing"],ans:1,exp:"Aortic dissection: sudden, severe tearing/ripping chest or back pain, BP difference >20 mmHg between arms. Differs from ACS — do not give thrombolytics."},
{d:2,q:"ETOH (alcohol) intoxication can mask:",opts:["Hypertension","Traumatic injuries and hypoglycemia","Tachycardia","Diaphoresis"],ans:1,exp:"Alcohol intoxication can mask signs of traumatic injury (distracting injury, reduced pain perception) and mimic/mask hypoglycemia. Always check glucose in intoxicated patients."},
{d:2,q:"A patient with COPD has a barrel-shaped chest because of:",opts:["Fluid accumulation","Air trapping causing lung hyperinflation","Muscular hypertrophy","Pleural thickening"],ans:1,exp:"Chronic air trapping in COPD leads to hyperinflation, pushing the ribs outward over time, creating a characteristic barrel chest with an increased AP diameter."},
{d:3,q:"A patient presents with confusion, hyperthermia, diaphoresis, tachycardia, and tremors after starting a new antidepressant. You suspect:",opts:["Neuroleptic malignant syndrome","Serotonin syndrome","Anticholinergic toxidrome","Sympathomimetic toxidrome"],ans:1,exp:"Serotonin syndrome triad: mental status changes, autonomic instability (hyperthermia, diaphoresis, tachycardia), and neuromuscular abnormalities (tremors, clonus, hyperreflexia). Associated with SSRIs/MAOIs."},
{d:3,q:"Anticholinergic toxidrome is remembered as:",opts:["Wet, cool, small pupils","Hot as Hades, dry as a bone, blind as a bat, red as a beet, mad as a hatter","Slow and sleepy","SLUDGE"],ans:1,exp:"Anticholinergic toxidrome (from atropine, diphenhydramine, jimsonweed): hyperthermia, anhidrosis, mydriasis, flushing, delirium/hallucinations."},
{d:3,q:"Thyroid storm signs include all EXCEPT:",opts:["Hyperthermia","Tachycardia and atrial fibrillation","Tremors and agitation","Hypothermia and bradycardia"],ans:3,exp:"Thyroid storm: extreme hyperthermia, tachycardia/dysrhythmias, agitation, tremors, heart failure. Hypothermia/bradycardia describe myxedema coma (hypothyroid crisis) — the opposite."},
{d:3,q:"Addisonian crisis (acute adrenal insufficiency) is characterized by:",opts:["Hypertension, hyperkalemia, hypernatremia","Hypotension, hyponatremia, hyperkalemia","Hypertension, hypokalemia, hyperglycemia","Hypotension, hypernatremia, hypokalemia"],ans:1,exp:"Adrenal crisis: loss of cortisol and aldosterone causes refractory hypotension, hyponatremia, hyperkalemia, and hypoglycemia. Treat with hydrocortisone and IV fluids."},
{d:3,q:"A patient with end-stage renal disease presents in respiratory distress. Crackles bilaterally, JVD, 3+ pitting edema. Best prehospital treatment is:",opts:["IV fluid bolus","High-flow O₂, position of comfort, consider CPAP, urgent dialysis transport","Furosemide IV push","Morphine and nitroglycerin only"],ans:1,exp:"Fluid overload/pulmonary edema in renal failure requires symptomatic relief (O₂, CPAP, vasodilators if BP allows) and urgent dialysis. Avoid large fluid boluses."},
,
{d:1,q:"Signs of left-sided heart failure include:",opts:["Peripheral edema and JVD","Pulmonary edema and dyspnea","Ascites and hepatomegaly","All of the above"],ans:1,exp:"Left heart failure causes pulmonary congestion (dyspnea, crackles, orthopnea). Right heart failure causes systemic venous congestion (peripheral edema, JVD, ascites). Both can coexist."},
{d:1,q:"A patient with altered mental status and a blood sugar of 600 mg/dL without ketones most likely has:",opts:["DKA","Hyperosmolar hyperglycemic state (HHS)","Hypoglycemia","Normal finding"],ans:1,exp:"HHS (type 2 DM): extreme hyperglycemia (often >600 mg/dL), severe dehydration, AMS, but minimal ketosis. Mortality is higher than DKA."},
{d:1,q:"Syncope preceded by nausea, pallor, and slow heart rate is most consistent with:",opts:["Cardiac syncope","Vasovagal syncope","Stroke","Hypoglycemia"],ans:1,exp:"Vasovagal syncope (common faint): triggered by emotional stress, pain, or prolonged standing. Preceded by prodrome (nausea, pallor, diaphoresis, bradycardia). Benign but requires assessment to rule out cardiac cause."},
{d:1,q:"A patient is found unconscious with miosis, bradycardia, excessive secretions, and urinary incontinence. You suspect:",opts:["Sympathomimetic toxidrome","Anticholinergic toxidrome","Organophosphate (cholinergic) toxidrome","Opioid toxidrome"],ans:2,exp:"SLUDGE (organophosphate/cholinergic): Salivation, Lacrimation, Urination, Defecation, GI upset, Emesis + bradycardia, miosis. Caused by organophosphate pesticides or nerve agents. Treat with atropine."},
{d:1,q:"Which medication can reverse opioid overdose?",opts:["Naloxone (Narcan)","Flumazenil","Activated charcoal","Epinephrine"],ans:0,exp:"Naloxone (Narcan) is an opioid antagonist that reverses respiratory depression, AMS, and miosis from opioid overdose. Titrate carefully — aggressive dosing precipitates acute withdrawal."},
{d:1,q:"The primary concern in a seizure patient post-ictal phase is:",opts:["Seizure recurrence","Airway protection and possible hypoglycemia","Medication administration","IV access"],ans:1,exp:"Post-ictal patients are unresponsive or confused. Protect the airway (recovery position, suction if needed) and check glucose — hypoglycemia is a treatable cause of seizures."},
{d:1,q:"Pulmonary embolism (PE) classically presents with:",opts:["Gradual onset bilateral leg edema","Sudden onset pleuritic chest pain, dyspnea, and tachycardia","Gradual onset dull chest pressure","Bradycardia and hypotension only"],ans:1,exp:"PE: sudden-onset pleuritic chest pain (worse with breathing), dyspnea, tachycardia, hypoxia. Risk factors: DVT, prolonged immobility, recent surgery, malignancy, pregnancy."},
{d:1,q:"Hypertensive emergency (crisis) is defined by:",opts:["Any BP over 140/90 mmHg","Severely elevated BP with evidence of end-organ damage","BP over 160/100 mmHg without symptoms","Any BP over 180 mmHg"],ans:1,exp:"Hypertensive emergency: severely elevated BP (usually >180/120 mmHg) WITH evidence of acute end-organ damage (stroke, MI, aortic dissection, acute pulmonary edema, encephalopathy)."},
{d:1,q:"A patient with severe abdominal pain, pulsatile abdominal mass, and hypotension suggests:",opts:["Appendicitis","Abdominal aortic aneurysm (AAA) rupture","Bowel obstruction","Mesenteric ischemia"],ans:1,exp:"Ruptured AAA triad: severe abdominal/back pain, pulsatile abdominal mass, hypotension. Highly lethal — immediate transport. Do not delay for IV access; mobilize the OR team by radio."},
{d:1,q:"Which is NOT a sign of meningitis?",opts:["Photophobia","Nuchal rigidity","Petechial rash","Hemiplegia without fever"],ans:3,exp:"Meningitis presents with fever, headache, nuchal rigidity (stiff neck), photophobia, and possibly rash. Hemiplegia without fever is more characteristic of stroke, not meningitis."},
{d:2,q:"Acute coronary syndrome (ACS) is an umbrella term that includes:",opts:["Stable angina only","Unstable angina, NSTEMI, and STEMI","STEMI only","Any chest pain"],ans:1,exp:"ACS includes: unstable angina (no troponin rise), NSTEMI (troponin rise, no ST elevation), and STEMI (ST elevation, requires emergent reperfusion). All involve partial or complete coronary occlusion."},
{d:2,q:"A patient with known COPD is in acute exacerbation with RR 36, using accessory muscles, and SpO₂ 84%. Your treatment priority is:",opts:["Oxygen to SpO₂ 99%","Titrated O₂ targeting 88–92%, bronchodilators, and consider CPAP/BiPAP","Breathing exercises only","IV steroids and transport only"],ans:1,exp:"COPD exacerbation: titrate O₂ to SpO₂ 88–92% (avoid hypercapnia), administer bronchodilators (albuterol, ipratropium), consider CPAP/BiPAP if severe, early transport."},
{d:2,q:"Spontaneous pneumothorax is most common in:",opts:["Obese middle-aged patients","Tall, thin young males","Elderly females","Athletes"],ans:1,exp:"Primary spontaneous pneumothorax occurs most often in tall, thin young males (due to tall, narrow lung anatomy causing apical blebs). Secondary spontaneous pneumothorax occurs in COPD, asthma, etc."},
{d:2,q:"Sepsis is defined as:",opts:["Fever and fast heart rate","Life-threatening organ dysfunction from dysregulated host response to infection","Any bacterial infection","Infection with positive blood cultures"],ans:1,exp:"Sepsis (Sepsis-3 definition): life-threatening organ dysfunction caused by a dysregulated host response to infection. Septic shock: sepsis + vasopressor requirement + lactate >2 mmol/L."},
{d:2,q:"Signs of inferior MI may include:",opts:["ST depression in V1–V6 only","ST elevation in II, III, aVF with possible bradycardia from vagal stimulation","ST elevation in I, aVL, V5, V6","Right bundle branch block"],ans:1,exp:"Inferior STEMI (RCA): ST elevation in II, III, aVF. The RCA also supplies the SA/AV nodes, so bradycardia, heart block, and vagal responses are common."},
{d:3,q:"Acute angle-closure glaucoma mimics stroke and presents with:",opts:["Sudden bilateral vision loss","Severe unilateral eye pain, headache, nausea, vision loss, and halo effect around lights","Painless monocular vision loss","Gradual bilateral vision loss"],ans:1,exp:"Acute angle-closure glaucoma: sudden severe eye pain, headache, nausea/vomiting, blurred vision with halos, fixed mid-dilated pupil. Can cause permanent vision loss — emergent treatment required."},
{d:3,q:"Neuroleptic Malignant Syndrome (NMS) differs from serotonin syndrome by:",opts:["NMS is faster onset","NMS has lead-pipe rigidity and slow onset over days; serotonin syndrome has clonus/hyperreflexia and rapid onset","NMS only affects the elderly","NMS requires opioid use"],ans:1,exp:"NMS (antipsychotic-induced): hyperthermia, 'lead-pipe' rigidity, AMS, autonomic instability — develops over days. Serotonin syndrome: clonus, hyperreflexia, rapid onset over hours. Both require dantrolene/cyproheptadine respectively."},
,
{d:1,q:"Rear-impact MVC most commonly causes injury to:",opts:["The abdomen","The cervical spine (hyperextension/flexion injury)","The lower extremities","The thorax"],ans:1,exp:"Rear-end collisions cause cervical hyperextension (then rebound hyperflexion) — the classic mechanism for cervical whiplash and potential C-spine fracture/cord injury."},
{d:1,q:"Rollover MVC is considered high-risk because:",opts:["It only affects drivers","Unrestrained occupants can be ejected, and multiple impacts occur from multiple directions","Airbags always deploy","It only occurs at high speed"],ans:1,exp:"Rollover MVC: multiple directional impacts and high risk of ejection (ejection increases mortality by 8x). Consider serious multisystem trauma regardless of apparent external injuries."},
{d:2,q:"A penetrating gunshot wound to zone II of the neck (between the clavicle and angle of the jaw) is high risk for:",opts:["Esophageal injury only","Vascular (carotid, jugular), airway, and esophageal injuries","Spinal cord injury only","Lymphatic injury"],ans:1,exp:"Zone II neck (most common): highest risk of vascular injury (carotid artery, jugular vein), airway (trachea, larynx), and esophagus. Apply direct pressure — do not probe or remove impaled objects."},
{d:1,q:"Secondary brain injury after TBI is caused by:",opts:["The initial impact","Hypoxia, hypotension, and increased ICP following the primary injury","Medications given in the field","Cervical spine movement"],ans:1,exp:"Primary injury occurs at impact. Secondary injury develops hours to days later from hypoxia, hypotension, hyperglycemia, hyperthermia, and elevated ICP — all preventable with proper treatment."},
{d:1,q:"Spinal shock differs from neurogenic shock in that:",opts:["They are the same condition","Spinal shock is temporary loss of ALL spinal cord function; neurogenic shock is hypotension from sympathetic disruption","Neurogenic shock has bradycardia only","Spinal shock always resolves within hours"],ans:1,exp:"Spinal shock: temporary flaccid paralysis and loss of reflexes below injury level (can last days to weeks). Neurogenic shock: cardiovascular instability (hypotension, bradycardia) from sympathetic tone loss."},
{d:2,q:"A penetrating abdominal injury with evisceration requires:",opts:["Immediate reduction of organs","Moist sterile dressing, no reduction, rapid transport","Dry dressing and observation","Abdominal binder"],ans:1,exp:"Evisceration: never replace organs — risk of further damage and contamination. Cover with moist sterile dressing to prevent drying, transport urgently. Keep patient supine with knees flexed if possible."},
{d:2,q:"The most common fatal injury from falls in elderly patients is:",opts:["Lower extremity fractures","Traumatic brain injury","Spinal cord injury","Thoracic aortic rupture"],ans:1,exp:"Falls are the leading cause of traumatic death in elderly patients. TBI (particularly subdural hematoma) is common and lethal in elderly due to cerebral atrophy, anticoagulant use, and vascular fragility."},
{d:1,q:"PASG (Pneumatic Anti-Shock Garment) use has declined because:",opts:["They are too expensive","Evidence showed they worsen outcomes in penetrating trauma and delay definitive care","They are too difficult to apply","They only work on females"],ans:1,exp:"PASG (MAST trousers) fell out of favor due to evidence of harm in penetrating trauma (forcing blood into injured areas), and for delaying transport without improving outcomes in hemorrhagic shock."},
{d:2,q:"A patient with burns covering the face, neck, and anterior chest has:",opts:["5% TBSA","Approximately 18% TBSA but, more importantly, a high-risk inhalation injury","9% TBSA","27% TBSA"],ans:1,exp:"Face/neck/anterior chest: ~18% TBSA, but the critical concern is inhalation injury (singed nasal hair, stridor, hoarse voice, carbonaceous sputum) — which can be more immediately lethal than the burn size."},
{d:1,q:"In trauma, 'load and go' transport is indicated when:",opts:["The patient has stable vital signs","The patient has internal hemorrhage, penetrating abdominal/thoracic injury, or shock not responding to treatment","All trauma patients require rapid transport","Only when C-spine is not involved"],ans:1,exp:"'Load and go': rapid transport is indicated for internal hemorrhage, penetrating torso wounds, and hemodynamic instability — conditions requiring surgical intervention that cannot be corrected in the field."},
{d:3,q:"Damage control resuscitation in massive transfusion uses which ratio to minimize trauma-induced coagulopathy?",opts:["4:1:1 PRBCs:FFP:Platelets","1:1:1 PRBCs:FFP:Platelets","10:1:1 PRBCs:FFP:Platelets","Blood products are not used prehospitally"],ans:1,exp:"1:1:1 balanced transfusion replaces all blood components simultaneously, preventing the dilutional coagulopathy caused by giving only PRBCs. TXA further reduces fibrinolysis."},
,
{d:1,q:"Right-sided heart failure signs include:",opts:["Pulmonary edema and orthopnea","Peripheral edema, JVD, hepatomegaly, ascites","All of the above","None of the above"],ans:1,exp:"Right heart failure causes systemic venous congestion: peripheral (pitting) edema, JVD, hepatomegaly, ascites. Left heart failure causes pulmonary edema."},
{d:1,q:"The Beck Depression Inventory (BDI) in EMS context refers to:",opts:["A medication","A suicide risk assessment tool — identifying patients at risk","A cardiac scoring system","A trauma scoring system"],ans:1,exp:"Various depression/suicide risk screening tools help EMS identify patients at risk. Columbia Suicide Severity Rating Scale (C-SSRS) or similar tools may guide transport decisions for psychiatric patients."},
{d:1,q:"Epistaxis (nosebleed) is best initially managed by:",opts:["Tilting the head back","Pinching the soft part of the nose and leaning forward","Packing the nostril with gauze","Cold compress to the back of the neck"],ans:1,exp:"Pinch the soft nasal tissue and lean forward (prevents blood from running into the throat) for 10–15 minutes of continuous pressure. Tilting back risks aspiration of blood."},
{d:2,q:"A patient with chronic renal failure is most at risk for which cardiac complication?",opts:["Atrial flutter","Hyperkalemia-induced dysrhythmias and cardiac arrest","Pulmonary embolism","WPW syndrome"],ans:1,exp:"Chronic kidney disease causes hyperkalemia (impaired potassium excretion) which causes life-threatening dysrhythmias — peaked T-waves, wide QRS, and cardiac arrest if untreated."},
{d:1,q:"Altered mental status can be remembered with the mnemonic AEIOU-TIPS, which includes:",opts:["Airway, Epiglottitis, Injury, Overdose, Uremia...","Alcohol/Acidosis, Epilepsy, Infection, Overdose, Uremia, Trauma, Insulin, Psychiatric, Stroke/Shock","All of the above","None of the above"],ans:1,exp:"AEIOU-TIPS: Alcohol/Acidosis, Epilepsy (seizure), Infection, Overdose, Uremia; Trauma, Insulin (glucose), Psychiatric, Stroke/Shock. A systematic approach to AMS causes."},
{d:1,q:"Which medication should always be available on an EMS unit for anaphylaxis?",opts:["Aspirin","Epinephrine auto-injector (EpiPen) or ampule","Diphenhydramine only","Albuterol only"],ans:1,exp:"Epinephrine is the only medication that reverses the life-threatening components of anaphylaxis (bronchospasm, vasodilation). Every ALS and BLS unit should carry epinephrine for anaphylaxis."},
{d:2,q:"A patient presents with new onset severe headache described as 'the worst headache of my life.' You should suspect:",opts:["Tension headache","Subarachnoid hemorrhage (SAH) — thunderclap headache","Migraine","Cluster headache"],ans:1,exp:"Thunderclap headache (sudden severe 'worst headache of life') is the classic presentation of subarachnoid hemorrhage from a ruptured cerebral aneurysm — a neurosurgical emergency."},
{d:2,q:"The GCS score of a patient who opens eyes to voice, is confused, and localizes pain is:",opts:["7","12","9","11"],ans:1,exp:"GCS: Eye opening to voice = 3; Verbal = confused = 4; Motor = localizes pain = 5. Total = 3+4+5 = 12. GCS ≤8 generally indicates severe TBI and inability to protect airway."},
{d:2,q:"Ectopic pregnancy presents with:",opts:["Normal menstruation continuing","Lower abdominal pain, vaginal bleeding, and positive pregnancy test in a woman of childbearing age","Painless bleeding only","High fever and rigors"],ans:1,exp:"Ectopic pregnancy: implantation outside the uterus (usually fallopian tube). Signs: lower abdominal pain (often unilateral), vaginal bleeding, positive pregnancy test. Rupture causes life-threatening hemorrhage."},
{d:1,q:"A patient with asthma who has 'tripod positioning' and cannot complete a sentence in one breath is experiencing:",opts:["Mild exacerbation","Severe or life-threatening exacerbation","Moderate exacerbation","Resolution of bronchospasm"],ans:1,exp:"Inability to speak in full sentences, accessory muscle use, and tripod positioning indicate severe bronchospasm. Silent chest (no wheeze), cyanosis, or altered mental status = life-threatening asthma."},
{d:2,q:"Spontaneous bacterial peritonitis (SBP) in a cirrhotic patient presents with:",opts:["Painless jaundice","Abdominal pain, fever, and AMS in a patient with known ascites","Hematemesis only","Normal vital signs with tense abdomen"],ans:1,exp:"SBP: infection of ascitic fluid in cirrhotic patients — fever, abdominal pain, and AMS. High mortality without antibiotics. Paracentesis is diagnostic; EMS should transport urgently."},
{d:3,q:"A patient with SLE (lupus) presents with pleuritic chest pain, fever, and a rash. The most important prehospital concern is:",opts:["Rash treatment","Excluding cardiac tamponade (lupus pericarditis/effusion) and PE","Administering steroids","Treating the fever"],ans:1,exp:"SLE can cause pericarditis (risk of tamponade), pleuritis, myocarditis, and antiphospholipid syndrome (thrombosis/PE). Prehospital: assess for tamponade signs, treat hypotension, 12-lead ECG, O₂, transport."},
,
{d:1,q:"The most common cause of preventable death in trauma is:",opts:["Airway obstruction","Uncontrolled hemorrhage","Brain injury","Spinal cord injury"],ans:1,exp:"Hemorrhage is the leading cause of preventable trauma death. This is why tourniquet application and wound packing are taught as immediate life-saving interventions."},
{d:1,q:"Clear fluid draining from the ear after head trauma suggests:",opts:["External ear infection","CSF leak from a basilar skull fracture","Normal finding","Ruptured eardrum only"],ans:1,exp:"Clear otorrhea after head trauma suggests CSF leak from a basilar skull fracture. This is a sign of significant base-of-skull injury requiring urgent evaluation."},
{d:2,q:"Kehr sign — referred left shoulder pain — in abdominal trauma suggests:",opts:["Liver injury","Splenic injury with blood irritating the diaphragm","Kidney injury","Pelvic fracture"],ans:1,exp:"Kehr sign: left shoulder pain from diaphragmatic irritation by blood, classically associated with splenic rupture. The C3-C5 dermatome explains the referred pain pattern."},
{d:1,q:"A patient ejected from a vehicle should be assumed to have:",opts:["Minor injuries only","Multisystem trauma with high risk of spinal and internal injuries","Isolated extremity fractures","Head injury only"],ans:1,exp:"Ejection increases mortality approximately eight times. These patients should be assumed to have serious multisystem trauma and managed accordingly."},
{d:2,q:"Epidural hematoma classically presents with:",opts:["Gradual neurological decline over weeks","A lucid interval after KO followed by rapid deterioration as the hematoma expands","Headache and vomiting only","Slow onset confusion"],ans:1,exp:"Epidural hematoma: arterial bleeding from the middle meningeal artery. Classic presentation is brief unconsciousness, lucid interval, then rapid neurological deterioration as pressure rises."},
{d:2,q:"Subdural hematoma is more common in:",opts:["Young athletes after concussion","Elderly patients due to cortical atrophy stretching bridging veins","Children only","Patients on stimulants"],ans:1,exp:"Subdural hematoma: venous bleeding between the dura and arachnoid. Chronic SDH is common in elderly and alcoholic patients due to cerebral atrophy and fragile bridging veins."},
{d:1,q:"Positive pressure ventilation BEFORE needle decompression in a tension pneumothorax will:",opts:["Relieve the tension","Worsen the tension pneumothorax by forcing more air into the pleural space","Have no effect","Provide temporary relief"],ans:1,exp:"PPV forces more air under tension into the pleural space, rapidly worsening the situation and causing cardiovascular collapse. Needle decompression must come first."},
{d:2,q:"A penetrating injury to the cardiac box requires:",opts:["Observation if vital signs are stable","High suspicion for cardiac or great vessel injury regardless of external appearance — emergent transport","All of the above","None of the above"],ans:1,exp:"The cardiac box — sternal borders, inferior clavicles, and costal margins — contains the heart and great vessels. Any penetrating injury here requires emergent transport for surgical evaluation."},
{d:1,q:"Chemical burns should be treated by:",opts:["Neutralizing with an acid or base","Continuous water irrigation for at least 20 minutes while removing contaminated clothing","Dry dressing only","Ice application"],ans:1,exp:"Chemical burns: brush off dry chemicals, then irrigate copiously with water for at least 20 minutes. Never use neutralizing agents — the heat of neutralization causes additional burns."},
{d:1,q:"Electrical burns are deceptive because:",opts:["They only affect the skin surface","Entry and exit wounds may appear minor but massive internal tissue destruction can occur along the current path","They always cause immediate death","The burns are painless only"],ans:1,exp:"High-voltage electrical burns: small entry and exit wounds mask devastating internal injury along the current path. Cardiac dysrhythmias, myoglobinuria, and rhabdomyolysis are serious complications."},
{d:2,q:"Retroperitoneal bleeding is difficult to detect prehospitally because:",opts:["It causes immediate peritonitis","The retroperitoneal space is large and non-tender — massive hemorrhage can occur with minimal external signs","All of the above","None of the above"],ans:1,exp:"Retroperitoneal hemorrhage from aorta, vena cava, kidneys, or pancreas can sequester liters of blood with minimal early peritoneal signs. Grey Turner and Cullen signs appear late."},
{d:3,q:"Damage control surgery prioritizes:",opts:["Definitive repair of all injuries immediately","Hemorrhage control and contamination control first, then ICU stabilization, then definitive repair in a planned return","All of the above","None of the above"],ans:1,exp:"Damage control surgery: abbreviated initial operation to stop bleeding and contamination, followed by ICU correction of the lethal triad, then planned definitive repair. This staged approach dramatically improves survival."},
{d:1,q:"Which type of shock presents with warm flushed skin early?",opts:["Hypovolemic shock","Distributive shock such as septic or anaphylactic shock due to vasodilation","All of the above","None of the above"],ans:1,exp:"Distributive shock causes vasodilation resulting in warm flushed skin early in the process. Hypovolemic and cardiogenic shock cause cold pale clammy skin due to vasoconstriction."},
{d:2,q:"Spinal shock differs from neurogenic shock in that:",opts:["They are the same condition","Spinal shock is temporary loss of all cord function below injury; neurogenic shock is cardiovascular instability from sympathetic disruption","All of the above","None of the above"],ans:1,exp:"Spinal shock: temporary flaccid paralysis and reflex loss below injury, resolving over days to weeks. Neurogenic shock: hypotension and bradycardia from loss of sympathetic tone — a cardiovascular problem."},
{d:1,q:"When is circumferential burn to an extremity an emergency?",opts:["Only when full thickness","Always — eschar formation creates a tourniquet effect requiring escharotomy to restore circulation","All of the above","None of the above"],ans:1,exp:"Circumferential full-thickness burns create inelastic eschar that constricts as underlying tissue swells, acting as a tourniquet. Distal pulses must be monitored. Escharotomy relieves constriction."}
,
{d:1,q:"The primary difference between a simple and tension pneumothorax is:",opts:["Amount of bleeding","Tension pneumothorax has ongoing air accumulation under pressure that does not escape — causing hemodynamic collapse","All of the above","None of the above"],ans:1,exp:"Simple pneumothorax: air in pleural space without pressure buildup. Tension: one-way valve effect causes progressive air accumulation under pressure, compressing heart and great vessels."},
{d:2,q:"Traumatic brain injury patients should be positioned with:",opts:["Flat supine","Head of bed at 30 degrees and head midline to facilitate venous drainage and reduce ICP","All of the above","None of the above"],ans:1,exp:"Head-of-bed elevation at 30 degrees and neutral head position facilitates cerebral venous drainage, reducing ICP. Avoid Trendelenburg and head rotation which impair venous outflow."},
{d:1,q:"The most appropriate initial treatment for a patient in neurogenic shock is:",opts:["Fluid restriction","IV fluid bolus to restore preload, then vasopressors if refractory","All of the above","None of the above"],ans:1,exp:"Neurogenic shock: loss of sympathetic tone causes vasodilation and relative hypovolemia. IV fluids restore preload. Vasopressors (norepinephrine, phenylephrine) restore vascular tone if fluids are insufficient."},
{d:2,q:"A pelvic binder or sheet wrap is used in suspected pelvic fracture to:",opts:["Immobilize the patient for transport","Reduce pelvic volume and tamponade venous bleeding","All of the above","None of the above"],ans:1,exp:"A pelvic binder (or improvised sheet wrap at the greater trochanters) reduces pelvic ring volume, compressing the fracture and tamponading venous hemorrhage. Effective for open-book pelvic fractures."},
{d:1,q:"Penetrating trauma to the abdomen with evisceration: you should NOT:",opts:["Apply a moist dressing","Attempt to replace the organs back into the abdomen","All of the above","None of the above"],ans:1,exp:"Never push eviscerated bowel back into the abdomen. Replacement risks further injury, contamination, and vascular compromise. Cover with a moist sterile dressing and transport urgently."}
,
{d:1,q:"The AVPU scale assesses:",opts:["Vital signs", "Level of consciousness: Alert, Voice, Pain, Unresponsive", "Blood pressure only", "Pain intensity"],ans:1,exp:"AVPU is a rapid neurological assessment: Alert (oriented), responds to Voice, responds to Pain only, or Unresponsive. More detailed assessment uses the GCS."},
{d:1,q:"Cushing triad indicates:",opts:["Tachycardia, hypotension, tachypnea", "Hypertension, bradycardia, and irregular respirations from severely elevated ICP", "Hypotension, tachycardia, fever", "Normal vital signs with confusion"],ans:1,exp:"Cushing triad is a late sign of severely elevated ICP with impending brainstem herniation. Hypertension maintains cerebral perfusion, bradycardia is a reflex response, and respirations become irregular."},
{d:1,q:"Hypoglycemia with BGL of 38 mg/dL is treated with:",opts:["Nothing and monitor", "Oral glucose if able to swallow or dextrose IV if not", "Insulin", "High-flow oxygen only"],ans:1,exp:"Hypoglycemia requires immediate treatment. If the patient can protect their airway and swallow, give oral glucose. If unconscious, give dextrose IV or IO or glucagon IM."},
{d:1,q:"Which medication reverses benzodiazepine overdose?",opts:["Naloxone", "Flumazenil", "Atropine", "Epinephrine"],ans:1,exp:"Flumazenil is a benzodiazepine antagonist that competitively blocks benzodiazepine receptors, reversing sedation and respiratory depression. It has a short half-life and resedation may occur."},
{d:1,q:"A patient with a seizure disorder seizes for 2 minutes and returns to baseline. You should:",opts:["No treatment needed", "Assess, check blood glucose, evaluate for triggers, and consider transport", "Transport immediately with lights and sirens", "Give diazepam immediately"],ans:1,exp:"Even typical seizures require assessment. Check blood glucose, evaluate for signs of infection or medication non-compliance. Prolonged or atypical seizures require transport."},
{d:1,q:"OPQRST is used to:",opts:["Assess blood pressure", "Fully characterize a patient's pain or chief complaint", "Document vital signs", "Determine medication dosing"],ans:1,exp:"OPQRST: Onset, Provocation and Palliation, Quality, Radiation, Severity, Time. This systematic approach fully characterizes pain and guides diagnosis and treatment."},
{d:1,q:"Signs of anaphylaxis include all EXCEPT:",opts:["Urticaria and angioedema", "Bronchospasm and stridor", "Bradycardia and hypertension", "Hypotension and tachycardia"],ans:2,exp:"Anaphylaxis causes distributive shock: urticaria, bronchospasm, stridor, hypotension, and tachycardia. Bradycardia and hypertension are not typical as anaphylaxis causes vasodilation and low BP."},
{d:1,q:"A patient with insulin excess and BGL of 44 mg/dL receives:",opts:["More insulin", "Oral glucose if conscious or dextrose IV if unconscious", "IV fluids only", "High-flow oxygen only"],ans:1,exp:"Insulin excess causes hypoglycemia. Oral glucose if the patient is conscious and can swallow safely. IV dextrose or glucagon IM if unconscious or unable to swallow."},
{d:1,q:"An anticoagulated patient falls and hits their head. With normal neuro exam you should:",opts:["Reassure and send home", "Transport for CT since anticoagulated patients have high risk of intracranial hemorrhage", "Only follow up with primary care", "Home observation is sufficient"],ans:1,exp:"Anticoagulated patients have significantly higher risk of intracranial hemorrhage after even minor head trauma. Transport for evaluation even if neurologically intact at the scene."},
{d:1,q:"Classic acute stroke signs include all EXCEPT:",opts:["Unilateral facial droop", "Arm drift", "Sudden fever above 104 F", "Slurred speech"],ans:2,exp:"Classic stroke signs are facial droop, arm weakness or drift, and speech abnormality in the Cincinnati Stroke Scale. Fever is not a typical acute stroke presentation."},
{d:1,q:"A patient with sudden onset heart racing at 180 bpm most likely has:",opts:["Sinus tachycardia from anxiety", "PSVT", "Ventricular tachycardia", "Atrial fibrillation"],ans:1,exp:"PSVT: sudden onset narrow complex tachycardia typically 150-250 bpm. The paroxysmal sudden onset is characteristic. A-fib is irregularly irregular. VT is usually wide complex."},
{d:1,q:"Hypertensive emergency is defined by severely elevated BP WITH:",opts:["Any symptom", "Acute end-organ damage such as stroke, MI, retinal changes, or encephalopathy", "BP above 140/90 alone", "BP above 160/100 only"],ans:1,exp:"Hypertensive emergency requires severely elevated BP plus acute end-organ damage. Without end-organ damage it is a hypertensive urgency."},
{d:1,q:"First-line treatment for anaphylactic shock is:",opts:["Diphenhydramine IV", "Epinephrine 1:1,000 IM to the anterolateral thigh", "Corticosteroids IV", "Albuterol nebulizer"],ans:1,exp:"Epinephrine 1:1,000 IM is the first and only primary treatment for anaphylaxis. It reverses bronchospasm, vasodilation, and urticaria. All other medications are adjuncts."},
{d:1,q:"DKA characteristically presents with:",opts:["Cold clammy skin and bradycardia", "Kussmaul respirations and fruity acetone breath", "Miosis and pinpoint pupils", "Normal vital signs"],ans:1,exp:"DKA: deep rapid Kussmaul respirations compensating for metabolic acidosis by blowing off CO2, and fruity breath from acetone in ketone metabolism."},
{d:1,q:"Definitive prehospital intervention for suspected STEMI is:",opts:["Aspirin and oxygen", "Rapid transport to a PCI-capable facility with cath lab pre-activation", "Nitroglycerin only", "Morphine and rest"],ans:1,exp:"The definitive treatment for STEMI is emergent PCI. Prehospital 12-lead transmission and pre-hospital cath lab activation dramatically reduces door-to-balloon time."},
{d:2,q:"Serotonin syndrome triad includes:",opts:["Hyperthermia, rigidity, bradycardia", "Mental status changes, autonomic instability, and neuromuscular abnormalities including clonus", "Hypothermia, bradycardia, miosis", "Hallucinations and bradycardia"],ans:1,exp:"Serotonin syndrome: altered mental status, autonomic instability with hyperthermia and tachycardia, and neuromuscular findings including clonus and hyperreflexia from excessive serotonergic activity."},
{d:2,q:"Organophosphate poisoning is treated with:",opts:["Naloxone", "Atropine to reverse cholinergic excess plus pralidoxime", "Flumazenil", "High-flow oxygen only"],ans:1,exp:"Organophosphates inhibit acetylcholinesterase causing SLUDGE: Salivation, Lacrimation, Urination, Defecation, GI upset, Emesis. Atropine blocks muscarinic receptors. Pralidoxime reactivates acetylcholinesterase."},
{d:2,q:"A dialysis patient with peaked T-waves and wide QRS most likely has:",opts:["Hypothermia", "Hyperkalemia from impaired renal potassium excretion", "WPW syndrome", "Normal ECG variant"],ans:1,exp:"Hyperkalemia ECG progression: peaked T-waves, PR prolongation, P wave flattening, wide QRS, sine wave, then asystole. Dialysis patients cannot excrete potassium."},
{d:2,q:"COPD exacerbation with RR 36 and SpO2 85% receives:",opts:["High-flow O2 via NRB at 15 L/min", "Titrated O2 targeting SpO2 88-92%, bronchodilators, and consider CPAP", "No oxygen", "Hyperventilation with BVM"],ans:1,exp:"COPD exacerbation: titrate O2 to 88-92%, nebulized bronchodilators, consider CPAP. Avoid high-flow O2 which worsens hypercapnia and suppresses hypoxic drive."},
{d:2,q:"Wernicke encephalopathy is caused by:",opts:["Alcohol toxicity directly", "Thiamine deficiency common in alcoholism and malnutrition", "Folic acid deficiency", "Glucose excess"],ans:1,exp:"Wernicke encephalopathy results from thiamine deficiency causing cell death in the thalamus and brainstem. Always give IV thiamine before glucose in suspected thiamine-deficient patients."},
{d:2,q:"Tearing back pain with BP difference between arms most likely represents:",opts:["ACS requiring aspirin and nitroglycerin", "Aortic dissection requiring avoidance of thrombolytics", "Pulmonary embolism", "Esophageal spasm"],ans:1,exp:"Aortic dissection: tearing or ripping pain radiating to the back, BP differential greater than 20 mmHg between arms. Thrombolytics and anticoagulants are absolutely contraindicated."},
{d:2,q:"HHS differs from DKA primarily by:",opts:["Lower blood glucose", "Absence of significant ketosis despite extreme hyperglycemia often above 600 mg/dL", "Younger patient age", "Faster onset"],ans:1,exp:"HHS (type 2 DM): extreme hyperglycemia often 600-1200 mg/dL, severe dehydration, AMS, but minimal ketosis because residual insulin prevents ketone production. Higher mortality than DKA."},
{d:2,q:"Acute angle-closure glaucoma presents with:",opts:["Bilateral vision loss gradually", "Severe unilateral eye pain, headache, nausea, halos, and fixed mid-dilated pupil", "Painless vision loss", "Bilateral halos only"],ans:1,exp:"Acute angle-closure glaucoma: sudden severe eye pain, frontal headache, nausea, blurred vision with halos, and a fixed mid-dilated pupil. Emergent treatment required to prevent permanent blindness."},
{d:2,q:"Wernicke triad consists of:",opts:["Confusion, hyperthermia, ophthalmoplegia", "Confusion, ataxia, and ophthalmoplegia", "Fever, nuchal rigidity, photophobia", "Nausea, vomiting, headache"],ans:1,exp:"Wernicke encephalopathy triad: confusion or AMS, ataxia, and ophthalmoplegia. Caused by thiamine deficiency. Immediate IV thiamine is required. Glucose alone without thiamine can worsen it."},
{d:3,q:"NMS differs from serotonin syndrome by:",opts:["NMS has faster onset", "NMS causes lead-pipe rigidity developing over days while serotonin syndrome causes clonus with rapid onset", "NMS occurs in younger patients", "NMS requires opioid use"],ans:1,exp:"NMS from antipsychotics: hyperthermia, lead-pipe muscular rigidity, AMS, and autonomic instability developing over days. Serotonin syndrome: clonus, hyperreflexia not rigidity, rapid onset over hours."},
{d:3,q:"SIRS progresses to sepsis when:",opts:["Temperature exceeds 38 degrees C", "There is suspected or confirmed infection causing life-threatening organ dysfunction", "Two SIRS criteria are met", "White blood cell count exceeds 12000"],ans:1,exp:"Sepsis-3: life-threatening organ dysfunction caused by a dysregulated host response to infection. SIRS criteria alone are insufficient for the diagnosis of sepsis."},
{d:3,q:"Massive PE causing cardiac arrest may warrant:",opts:["Preventing future clots", "Systemic thrombolysis to dissolve the obstructing clot when no contraindications exist", "Standard first-line for all PEA", "Replacement of CPR"],ans:1,exp:"Massive PE causing arrest may warrant systemic thrombolysis when PE is the suspected cause. CPR must continue for 60-90 minutes post-lytic to allow clot dissolution."},
{d:3,q:"Addisonian crisis presents with:",opts:["Hypertension, hyperkalemia, hypernatremia", "Refractory hypotension, hyponatremia, and hyperkalemia requiring hydrocortisone and IV fluids", "Hypertension and Cushingoid features", "Hyperglycemia and polyuria"],ans:1,exp:"Adrenal crisis: loss of cortisol and aldosterone causes refractory vasodilatory shock, hyponatremia, hyperkalemia, and hypoglycemia. IV hydrocortisone and fluid resuscitation are life-saving."}
],

operations: [
{d:1,q:"The FIRST priority on any EMS scene is:",opts:["Patient assessment","Scene safety","Calling medical direction","IV access"],ans:1,exp:"Scene safety is always first. An injured EMT cannot help patients and may require additional resources."},
{d:1,q:"Standard Precautions mean:",opts:["Treating all patients as if infectious","Only gloving for bloody patients","Using PPE only for known infectious patients","Wearing gown for all calls"],ans:0,exp:"Standard Precautions require treating all patients as potentially infectious — appropriate PPE regardless of known diagnosis."},
{d:1,q:"Online medical direction refers to:",opts:["Standing orders in protocol book","Real-time physician guidance by radio/phone","Hospital policies","QI review of patient care reports"],ans:1,exp:"Online (direct) medical direction = real-time physician communication during care. Offline = protocols and standing orders."},
{d:1,q:"Patient care reports should be completed:",opts:["Written from memory at station","As soon as possible after care","Only for serious calls","Within 24 hours"],ans:1,exp:"PCRs should be completed as soon as possible — accurate, timely documentation ensures continuity of care and legal protection."},
{d:1,q:"Implied consent applies when:",opts:["A competent adult refuses care","An unconscious patient needs emergency care","A patient signs a refusal form","Family requests treatment"],ans:1,exp:"Implied consent assumes an unconscious patient would consent to life-saving treatment if they were able."},
{d:1,q:"Informed refusal requires that the patient:",opts:["Has a physician present","Has decision-making capacity and understands risks of refusing","Has family member agreement","Is alert and oriented to person only"],ans:1,exp:"A valid informed refusal: patient has decision-making capacity and understands the potential risks, including death. Document thoroughly."},
{d:1,q:"START triage categorizes patients into:",opts:["Two categories","Three categories","Four categories: immediate, delayed, minor, deceased/expectant","Five categories"],ans:2,exp:"START: Red (immediate), Yellow (delayed), Green (minor/walking wounded), Black (deceased/expectant)."},
{d:1,q:"Negligence in EMS requires proving all EXCEPT:",opts:["Duty to act","Breach of duty","Patient's prior medical history","Damages caused by the breach"],ans:2,exp:"Negligence elements: duty, breach, causation, and damages. Prior medical history is not an element."},
{d:1,q:"An EMT encounters a patient with a valid DNR who arrests. The EMT should:",opts:["Begin full resuscitation","Honor the DNR and provide comfort care","Call medical direction first","Contact family first"],ans:1,exp:"A valid DNR instructs providers not to attempt resuscitation. Contact medical direction if validity is uncertain."},
{d:1,q:"For a patient who is competent and refuses transport, the EMT should:",opts:["Leave immediately","Explain consequences, attempt to persuade, document thoroughly, have patient sign refusal","Demand the patient sign AMA","Call law enforcement"],ans:1,exp:"Explain risks, attempt to persuade, ensure competence, offer alternatives, document thoroughly, have the patient sign the refusal form. Leave contact information."},
{d:1,q:"Mass Casualty Incident (MCI) is defined as:",opts:["Any call with more than 2 patients","An incident where the number of patients exceeds available resources","Only natural disasters","Only incidents with 10+ patients"],ans:1,exp:"An MCI is any event where patient numbers exceed available local EMS resources — triggers a tiered response activation."},
{d:1,q:"The EMS incident command system (ICS) uses which organizational structure?",opts:["Horizontal / flat","Vertical hierarchy with unified command","Democratic/voting-based","None — ad hoc"],ans:1,exp:"ICS uses a vertical hierarchy to manage resources and information efficiently. It's scalable for small incidents or large MCIs."},
{d:1,q:"Confidentiality of patient information is protected under:",opts:["EMTALA","HIPAA","ADA","OSHA"],ans:1,exp:"HIPAA (Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act) protects patient health information. EMS providers may only share PHI for treatment, payment, or operations without consent."},
{d:1,q:"The EMS term 'load and go' vs 'stay and play' refers to:",opts:["Equipment choices","Decision to transport rapidly vs. extensive on-scene treatment","Triage methods","MCI staging"],ans:1,exp:"'Load and go' prioritizes rapid transport (e.g., hemorrhagic shock, stroke, STEMI). 'Stay and play' stabilizes on-scene (e.g., airway management, cardiac arrest)."},
{d:2,q:"A patient is awake, alert, and competent but has been drinking alcohol. They refuse care. You should:",opts:["Accept the refusal immediately","Assess decision-making capacity carefully — intoxication may impair capacity","Leave without documentation","Force treatment"],ans:1,exp:"Alcohol intoxication may impair decision-making capacity. Carefully assess the patient. If capacity is questionable, err toward providing care and consult medical direction."},
{d:2,q:"Abandonment occurs when:",opts:["EMS is dispatched but doesn't arrive in time","An EMT transfers care to someone of equal or lesser training without consent","A patient refuses care","EMS leaves the scene after police arrive"],ans:1,exp:"Abandonment: unilaterally terminating care once started, or transferring to a lower-level provider without patient consent. This is negligent."},
{d:2,q:"Which best describes a duty to act?",opts:["EMS must respond to any call they hear on radio","Legal obligation based on employment or volunteer status to respond and provide care","EMTs must stop at all accidents they witness","Optional depending on jurisdiction"],ans:1,exp:"Duty to act arises from employment (paid EMS) or protocols (volunteers while on duty). Off-duty providers may have no legal duty to act in most jurisdictions."},
{d:2,q:"Quality Improvement (QI) in EMS includes:",opts:["Punishing providers for errors","Reviewing outcomes to identify system-wide improvements and training opportunities","Documentation review only","Annual recertification only"],ans:1,exp:"EMS QI is a continuous, non-punitive process to identify trends, reduce errors, and improve patient outcomes through education, feedback, and protocol updates."},
{d:2,q:"The JUMP START triage system is designed for:",opts:["Adult MCIs","Pediatric MCIs","Patients in cardiac arrest","Mass casualty with CBRN exposure"],ans:1,exp:"JumpSTART modifies START triage for pediatric patients — accounting for different normal vital signs, respiratory rates, and the fact that children may need a rescue breath before being tagged black."},
{d:2,q:"When writing a patient care report, objective information includes:",opts:["What the patient told you about symptoms","Vital signs, physical exam findings, observations","Your interpretation of the patient's condition","Patient's past medical history"],ans:1,exp:"Objective data is measurable and observable: vital signs, physical exam findings. Subjective data is what the patient reports. Keep them clearly separated in the PCR."},
{d:2,q:"Res ipsa loquitur ('the thing speaks for itself') in EMS law refers to:",opts:["Patient documentation","A legal concept where negligence is self-evident from the facts","Verbal consent","Scope of practice authorization"],ans:1,exp:"Res ipsa loquitur applies when an injury could not have occurred without negligence (e.g., a tourniquet left on for 8 hours). The burden shifts to the defendant to disprove negligence."},
{d:2,q:"An EMT discovers a patient being abused at home. The EMT's legal obligation is:",opts:["Confront the abuser","Document and report to appropriate authorities — mandatory reporter","Maintain confidentiality","Only intervene if the patient requests it"],ans:1,exp:"EMS providers are mandatory reporters for suspected abuse (child, elder, intimate partner). Report to the receiving facility and appropriate authorities; document objective findings."},
{d:2,q:"CBRN stands for:",opts:["Chemical, Biological, Radiological, Nuclear","Critical, Basic, Rapid, Necessary","Cardiac, Burns, Respiratory, Neurological","None of the above"],ans:0,exp:"CBRN: Chemical, Biological, Radiological, Nuclear — categories of hazardous material or WMD threats that require specialized response protocols."},
{d:3,q:"In a HAZMAT incident, EMS should stage in which zone?",opts:["Hot zone — to immediately treat patients","Warm zone — to receive decontaminated patients","Cold zone — to treat decontaminated patients","Any zone with appropriate PPE"],ans:2,exp:"EMS stages in the Cold Zone (clean zone). Decontamination occurs in the Warm Zone. Entry into the Hot Zone requires HAZMAT-trained personnel with appropriate PPE."},
{d:3,q:"Battery in EMS law is defined as:",opts:["Threatening a patient","Touching a patient without consent","Failing to provide care","Making false statements about care"],ans:1,exp:"Battery is unauthorized touching — treating a patient who has clearly refused or lacks consent. Assault is threatening action without actual contact."},
{d:3,q:"Which document allows an EMS provider to honor a patient's end-of-life wishes found at home?",opts:["A POLST or MOLST (Physician Orders for Life-Sustaining Treatment)","A living will alone","A verbal statement by family","Insurance card"],ans:0,exp:"POLST/MOLST are physician-signed medical orders valid across care settings, including prehospital. They carry more weight than living wills, which are advance directives requiring interpretation."},
{d:3,q:"The primary goal of medical oversight in EMS is:",opts:["To limit EMT scope of practice","To ensure high quality patient care through physician involvement","To manage billing","To handle legal disputes"],ans:1,exp:"Medical oversight (direction) exists to ensure the highest level of patient care — through protocol development, training, QI, and real-time guidance."},
{d:3,q:"When transporting a psychiatric patient against their will is legally permissible:",opts:["Whenever EMS believes it's best","When the patient is an imminent danger to themselves or others (involuntary hold)","With family consent only","Never — EMS cannot force transport"],ans:1,exp:"Involuntary psychiatric holds (5150, Baker Act, etc.) allow transport against a patient's will when they are determined to be an imminent danger to themselves or others — usually requiring police or physician authorization."},
,
{d:1,q:"EMS providers must maintain patient confidentiality except when:",opts:["Asked by media","Required for treatment, required by law, or patient consent given","The patient is unconscious","Family members request information"],ans:1,exp:"PHI may be shared: with other treating providers (treatment), with payers (payment), as required by law (mandatory reporting, subpoena), or with patient consent."},
{d:1,q:"Good Samaritan laws generally protect:",opts:["On-duty EMS providers","Off-duty medical personnel who provide emergency care in good faith without expecting compensation","All drivers at accident scenes","Hospitals"],ans:1,exp:"Good Samaritan laws protect off-duty individuals who voluntarily provide emergency care in good faith from civil liability (does not protect gross negligence or abandonment)."},
{d:1,q:"The National Incident Management System (NIMS) is used to:",opts:["Train individual EMTs","Standardize incident management across all agencies and jurisdictions","Manage hospital operations","Create EMS protocols"],ans:1,exp:"NIMS provides a national framework for consistent incident management across all jurisdictions and disciplines, regardless of size or type of incident."},
{d:1,q:"Dispatch triage in EMS prioritizes patients based on:",opts:["First come, first served","Chief complaint, caller information, and priority dispatch protocols","Distance from the hospital","Patient's age"],ans:1,exp:"Emergency Medical Dispatch (EMD) uses caller information and chief complaint with structured protocols (e.g., MPDS) to triage calls and dispatch appropriate resources."},
{d:1,q:"Scene size-up includes:",opts:["Patient assessment only","Scene safety, number of patients, MOI, need for additional resources","Vital signs and history","Equipment check only"],ans:1,exp:"Scene size-up: scene safety (BSI, hazards), nature of illness/MOI, number of patients, additional resources needed, and initial patient impression."},
{d:1,q:"HIPAA protects patients' right to:",opts:["Free emergency care","Privacy of health information","Refuse all treatment","Know ambulance response times"],ans:1,exp:"HIPAA (1996) establishes national standards for protecting patients' individually identifiable health information (PHI) — including verbal, written, and electronic formats."},
{d:1,q:"When a patient refuses care and signs a refusal form, the EMT should:",opts:["Leave immediately","Document everything, provide instructions on when to call back, leave contact info","Transfer care to bystanders","Call police to force treatment"],ans:1,exp:"A properly executed refusal includes: ensuring competency, informing of risks, attempting to persuade, documenting thoroughly (witness signature helpful), providing instructions for when to call 911 again."},
{d:1,q:"An EMT who falsely claims to have performed a procedure on a PCR has committed:",opts:["Abandonment","Fraud and falsification of medical records","Malpractice","Simple negligence"],ans:1,exp:"Falsification of medical records is fraud — a criminal offense and a violation of professional ethics. PCRs are legal documents."},
{d:1,q:"Which of the following is an example of expressed consent?",opts:["Treating an unconscious patient","A verbal 'yes' from a competent adult or a signed consent form","Treating a minor without parents present","Assuming a confused patient consents"],ans:1,exp:"Expressed consent is explicitly given — verbally or in writing by a competent adult who understands the proposed treatment."},
{d:1,q:"Scope of practice for EMTs is defined by:",opts:["Each individual EMT","State EMS laws and regulations and medical direction protocols","National EMS standards only","The hospital receiving the patient"],ans:1,exp:"Scope of practice defines what an EMT is legally authorized to do and is established by state law, medical direction, and local protocols. EMTs must practice within their scope."},
{d:2,q:"During an active shooter incident, EMS follows which protocol?",opts:["Immediately enter the scene to treat casualties","Stage in the cold zone until law enforcement secures the scene (Rescue Task Force concept)","Call medical direction before responding","Respond only after SWAT clears the scene"],ans:1,exp:"Active shooter/TECC: EMS stages in the cold zone. Rescue Task Force (RTF) pairs law enforcement with EMS to extract casualties from the warm zone. Avoid the hot zone without armed escort."},
{d:2,q:"A tactical EMS (TEMS) principle is that hemorrhage control in the warm zone uses:",opts:["Full BLS assessment","Massive hemorrhage control (tourniquets, wound packing) before airway","Standard primary survey order","Airway first, then hemorrhage"],ans:1,exp:"TCCC/TECC: Massive Hemorrhage control is the FIRST priority in the tactical environment (MARCH: Massive Hemorrhage, Airway, Respiration, Circulation, Hypothermia). Life-threatening bleeding kills faster than airway in tactical settings."},
{d:2,q:"The Medical Practices Act governs:",opts:["Hospital billing practices","Who may perform medical procedures and under what circumstances","Drug storage regulations","Ambulance licensing"],ans:1,exp:"The Medical Practices Act (varies by state) defines the scope of medical practice, protects against unlicensed practice, and governs how medical procedures may be performed and by whom."},
{d:2,q:"Proximate cause in a negligence claim means:",opts:["The duty to act","The breach directly caused the patient's injury or worsened outcome","Damages were financial","The provider was on duty"],ans:1,exp:"Proximate cause (causation): a direct causal link between the provider's breach of duty and the patient's harm. Without this link, negligence cannot be established."},
{d:2,q:"OSHA's bloodborne pathogen standard requires EMS agencies to provide:",opts:["Voluntary PPE for providers","Mandatory exposure control plan, hepatitis B vaccination, and post-exposure protocol","Basic gloves only","Annual blood draws only"],ans:1,exp:"OSHA 29 CFR 1910.1030: agencies must provide exposure control plans, offer hepatitis B vaccination, provide appropriate PPE, implement post-exposure follow-up, and conduct training."},
{d:3,q:"The concept of 'res gestae' in EMS documentation refers to:",opts:["Post-call documentation only","Statements made during an emergency by the patient — admissible as evidence","Radio communications","Witness statements only"],ans:1,exp:"Res gestae statements (part of the event) made by patients during an emergency may be admissible in legal proceedings as exceptions to hearsay rules. Documenting exact patient quotes can be legally significant."},
{d:3,q:"Medical futility in EMS prehospital context may allow withholding resuscitation when:",opts:["Any family member objects","Patient has obvious signs of death (rigor mortis, livor mortis, dependent lividity, decapitation) or valid DNR","Patient is elderly","Resuscitation has continued for 20 minutes"],ans:1,exp:"Providers may withhold or terminate resuscitation in the presence of obvious signs of irreversible death, valid advance directives, or per protocol after prolonged unsuccessful CPR with no reversible causes identified."},
,
{d:1,q:"Right-sided heart failure signs include:",opts:["Pulmonary edema and orthopnea","Peripheral edema, JVD, hepatomegaly, and ascites","Tachycardia and hypotension alone","Bilateral crackles only"],ans:1,exp:"Right heart failure causes systemic venous congestion: peripheral pitting edema, JVD, hepatomegaly, and ascites. Left heart failure causes pulmonary edema and dyspnea."},
{d:1,q:"Epistaxis is best initially managed by:",opts:["Tilting the head back","Pinching the soft part of the nose and leaning forward","Packing the nostril with dry gauze","Cold compress to the back of the neck"],ans:1,exp:"Pinch the soft nasal tissue and lean forward to prevent blood running into the throat. Maintain for 10-15 minutes of continuous pressure. Tilting back risks aspiration."},
{d:1,q:"Pulmonary embolism classically presents with:",opts:["Gradual bilateral leg swelling","Sudden pleuritic chest pain, dyspnea, and tachycardia","Gradual dull pressure","Bradycardia alone"],ans:1,exp:"PE: sudden onset pleuritic chest pain that worsens with breathing, dyspnea, tachycardia, and hypoxia. Risk factors include DVT, immobility, recent surgery, malignancy, and pregnancy."},
{d:1,q:"The worst headache of life requires suspicion for:",opts:["Tension headache","Subarachnoid hemorrhage — thunderclap headache from ruptured cerebral aneurysm","Migraine with aura","Cluster headache"],ans:1,exp:"Thunderclap headache described as the worst headache of life is the classic presentation of subarachnoid hemorrhage. This is a neurosurgical emergency requiring immediate evaluation."},
{d:2,q:"A GCS of 3 plus 4 plus 5 equals:",opts:["10","12","11","9"],ans:1,exp:"GCS: Eye opening to voice equals 3; Confused verbal equals 4; Localizes pain motor equals 5. Total equals 12. GCS 8 or less indicates severe TBI and likely inability to protect the airway."},
{d:2,q:"Ectopic pregnancy presents with:",opts:["Normal menstruation continuing","Lower abdominal pain, vaginal bleeding, and positive pregnancy test in a woman of childbearing age","Painless bleeding only","High fever and rigors"],ans:1,exp:"Ectopic pregnancy implants outside the uterus, usually in the fallopian tube. Signs: unilateral lower abdominal pain, vaginal bleeding, positive pregnancy test. Rupture causes life-threatening hemorrhage."},
{d:2,q:"Spontaneous pneumothorax most commonly occurs in:",opts:["Obese middle-aged patients","Tall thin young males due to apical blebs","Elderly women","Athletes of any body type"],ans:1,exp:"Primary spontaneous pneumothorax occurs most often in tall thin young males due to anatomical apical blebs. Secondary spontaneous pneumothorax occurs in patients with underlying COPD or asthma."},
{d:1,q:"A patient with asthma who has a silent chest is:",opts:["Improving — wheeze resolved","In severe or life-threatening bronchospasm with no air movement","Mildly distressed","Responding to treatment"],ans:1,exp:"A silent chest in asthma indicates no air movement and impending respiratory failure. Positive pressure ventilation and rapid transport are required. This is not an improvement."},
{d:2,q:"Acute angle-closure glaucoma can mimic stroke and presents with:",opts:["Bilateral vision loss gradually","Severe unilateral eye pain, headache, nausea, vision loss, and halos around lights","Painless monocular vision loss","Gradual bilateral blurring"],ans:1,exp:"Acute angle-closure glaucoma: severe eye pain, frontal headache, nausea, blurred vision with halos, and fixed mid-dilated pupil. Can cause permanent blindness. Requires emergent treatment."},
{d:2,q:"Wernicke encephalopathy is caused by:",opts:["Chronic alcohol toxicity alone","Thiamine deficiency commonly in alcoholism or malnutrition","Folic acid deficiency","Niacin deficiency"],ans:1,exp:"Wernicke triad: encephalopathy, ataxia, and ophthalmoplegia from thiamine deficiency. Common in alcoholics. Give IV thiamine before glucose in suspected thiamine deficiency to prevent precipitating Wernicke."},
{d:2,q:"Sepsis is defined as:",opts:["Fever and fast heart rate","Life-threatening organ dysfunction from a dysregulated host response to infection","Any bacterial infection","Positive blood cultures only"],ans:1,exp:"Sepsis-3 definition: life-threatening organ dysfunction caused by a dysregulated host response to infection. Septic shock adds vasopressor requirement and elevated lactate to the definition."},
{d:2,q:"Signs of inferior MI may include which rhythm complication?",opts:["Left bundle branch block","Bradycardia or AV block from RCA supply to SA and AV nodes","Atrial fibrillation only","Ventricular tachycardia always"],ans:1,exp:"Inferior STEMI involves the RCA which also supplies the SA and AV nodes. Bradycardia, first-degree, second-degree, or complete heart block are common complications."},
{d:1,q:"The AEIOU-TIPS mnemonic helps recall causes of:",opts:["Chest pain","Altered mental status — Alcohol, Epilepsy, Infection, Overdose, Uremia, Trauma, Insulin, Psychiatric, Stroke","All of the above","None of the above"],ans:1,exp:"AEIOU-TIPS: Alcohol or Acidosis, Epilepsy, Infection, Overdose, Uremia; Trauma, Insulin or glucose, Psychiatric, Stroke or Shock. A systematic approach to evaluating altered mental status."},
{d:1,q:"Naloxone reverses opioid overdose by:",opts:["Metabolizing the opioid faster","Competitively blocking opioid receptors — reversing respiratory depression and AMS","All of the above","None of the above"],ans:1,exp:"Naloxone is an opioid antagonist that displaces opioids from their receptors. Titrate carefully to restore breathing without precipitating acute withdrawal. Duration may be shorter than the opioid."},
{d:2,q:"Hypertensive emergency differs from hypertensive urgency by:",opts:["Only blood pressure numbers","The presence of acute end-organ damage — stroke, MI, aortic dissection, or encephalopathy","All of the above","None of the above"],ans:1,exp:"Hypertensive emergency: severely elevated BP with acute end-organ damage requiring immediate controlled reduction. Urgency: severely elevated BP without end-organ damage — reduce over hours to days."}
,
{d:1,q:"A patient with CHF and pulmonary edema will most likely prefer to sit in what position?",opts:["Supine with legs elevated","Upright — sitting position reduces venous return and decreases pulmonary congestion","All of the above","None of the above"],ans:1,exp:"CHF patients instinctively sit upright (orthopnea). Sitting reduces venous return, decreasing cardiac preload and pulmonary congestion. Always transport in position of comfort for CHF."},
{d:2,q:"Hypertensive emergency with neurological signs requires:",opts:["Rapid aggressive BP reduction in the field","Controlled gradual BP reduction — too rapid a drop causes cerebral ischemia from sudden loss of autoregulation","All of the above","None of the above"],ans:1,exp:"In hypertensive emergency with neurological signs, reduce MAP by no more than 20-25% in the first hour. Too rapid reduction risks cerebral ischemia in a brain adapted to high pressure."},
{d:1,q:"A patient with known sickle cell disease presents with severe bone pain. This is most likely:",opts:["Malingering","Vaso-occlusive crisis — sickled RBCs obstruct microvascular flow causing ischemic pain","All of the above","None of the above"],ans:1,exp:"Vaso-occlusive (pain) crisis is the most common acute complication of sickle cell disease. Treatment includes IV fluids, supplemental oxygen, and analgesia. Transport for definitive care."},
{d:2,q:"Organophosphate poisoning is treated with:",opts:["Naloxone","Atropine to reverse the cholinergic excess, plus pralidoxime if available and in scope","All of the above","None of the above"],ans:1,exp:"Organophosphate (nerve agent, pesticide) poisoning causes cholinergic excess (SLUDGE). Atropine blocks muscarinic receptors. Pralidoxime reactivates acetylcholinesterase if given early."},
{d:1,q:"A patient with a known seizure disorder who seizes for 2 minutes and returns to baseline requires:",opts:["No intervention — normal for epilepsy","Assessment, blood glucose check, and evaluation for breakthrough seizure triggers","All of the above","None of the above"],ans:1,exp:"Even a typical seizure in an epileptic requires assessment. Check glucose, assess for signs of infection or medication non-compliance. Prolonged or atypical seizures or failure to return to baseline require transport."},
{d:2,q:"Acute mountain sickness (AMS) occurs because:",opts:["Altitude causes infection","Reduced partial pressure of oxygen at altitude causes hypoxia and various compensatory responses","All of the above","None of the above"],ans:1,exp:"AMS occurs above 8000 feet from reduced inspired oxygen partial pressure. Symptoms: headache, nausea, fatigue, and dizziness. Severe AMS can progress to high-altitude pulmonary edema (HAPE) or cerebral edema (HACE)."}
,
{d:1,q:"The most important first step at any emergency scene is:",opts:["Patient assessment", "Establishing IV access", "Scene safety and BSI", "Calling medical direction"],ans:2,exp:"Scene safety is always the absolute first priority. An injured EMS provider becomes a patient themselves, requiring additional resources."},
{d:1,q:"Standard precautions require gloves for:",opts:["Only patients with known infections", "All patient contact regardless of known diagnosis", "Only when blood is visible", "Only for ALS procedures"],ans:1,exp:"Standard precautions treat all patients as potentially infectious. Gloves are required for all patient contact. Add mask, eye protection, and gown when splash or soiling is anticipated."},
{d:1,q:"A competent oriented patient refusing transport should receive:",opts:["Forced transport", "An explanation of risks, persuasion attempt, thorough documentation, and refusal form", "Immediate departure", "Police assistance to force transport"],ans:1,exp:"A competent adult has the right to refuse medical care. Ensure they understand the risks, document the refusal thoroughly, have them sign the form, and provide instructions for when to call 911."},
{d:1,q:"Implied consent allows EMS to treat:",opts:["Any patient who cannot speak", "Unconscious patients in life-threatening emergencies when expressed consent cannot be obtained", "Minors without parental consent always", "Patients who are simply confused"],ans:1,exp:"Implied consent assumes an unconscious or incapacitated adult in a life-threatening emergency would consent to treatment if able to do so."},
{d:1,q:"A patient care report is primarily:",opts:["A billing document only", "A legal medical record documenting assessment, care, and transport", "An administrative form only", "Internal EMS communication only"],ans:1,exp:"The PCR is simultaneously a legal document, medical record, communication tool, billing document, and quality improvement resource. Accuracy and completeness are critical."},
{d:1,q:"START triage tags immediate (red) patients based on:",opts:["Age", "Respiratory rate over 30, absent radial pulse or cap refill over 2 seconds, or inability to follow commands", "Chief complaint only", "Vital signs alone"],ans:1,exp:"START triage: Respirations over 30 per minute, Perfusion with no radial pulse or cap refill over 2 seconds, and Mental status unable to follow simple commands determine the Red (immediate) tag."},
{d:1,q:"HIPAA permits sharing patient health information:",opts:["Freely with anyone who asks", "For treatment, payment, and healthcare operations without specific consent", "Only with signed written consent always", "Never without a court order"],ans:1,exp:"HIPAA permits disclosure of PHI for treatment, payment, and healthcare operations without specific consent. All other disclosures require patient authorization or legal mandate."},
{d:1,q:"An EMT leaving a scene without transferring care properly has committed:",opts:["Negligence only", "Abandonment", "Battery", "Assault"],ans:1,exp:"Abandonment: unilaterally terminating care once initiated, or transferring to a lower-level provider without patient consent. This constitutes negligence and may have serious legal consequences."},
{d:1,q:"EMS providers practice medicine under:",opts:["Their own independent license", "A physician medical director's license through delegated authority", "Federal certification only", "State certification without physician oversight"],ans:1,exp:"EMS providers practice medicine under delegated authority from a physician medical director who is legally and ethically responsible for the clinical care provided by the EMS system."},
{d:1,q:"Black triage tag designates a patient who is:",opts:["Critical", "Deceased or unsurvivable with available resources", "Minor injuries", "Delayed treatment needed"],ans:1,exp:"Black tag: deceased or unsurvivable injuries in a resource-limited MCI. This allows available resources to focus on patients who can survive with treatment."},
{d:1,q:"Beneficence in EMS ethics means:",opts:["Do no harm", "Act in the patient's best interest", "Treat all patients equally", "Respect patient decisions"],ans:1,exp:"Beneficence: the duty to actively benefit the patient. Combined with non-maleficence, autonomy, and justice these form the four pillars of biomedical ethics."},
{d:1,q:"A valid DNR order directs EMS to:",opts:["Withhold all care including comfort measures", "Withhold resuscitation but allow comfort-focused care", "Ignore unless countersigned by the hospital", "Resuscitate if family requests it"],ans:1,exp:"A valid DNR instructs providers not to initiate resuscitation. It does not prevent comfort care, supplemental oxygen, positioning, or pain management."},
{d:1,q:"EMS mandatory reporting requirements include:",opts:["Any medical condition", "Suspected child, elder, and intimate partner abuse or neglect", "Only confirmed abuse with physical evidence", "Only when asked by law enforcement"],ans:1,exp:"EMS providers are mandatory reporters in all jurisdictions for suspected abuse or neglect of children, elderly, and dependent adults. Report suspicions to appropriate authorities."},
{d:1,q:"Quality improvement in EMS is designed to be:",opts:["Punitive for individual providers", "Non-punitive and system-focused to improve patient outcomes", "Only for administrative purposes", "Required only after adverse events"],ans:1,exp:"QI is a non-punitive, continuous process that reviews patient care data, identifies trends and opportunities for improvement, and develops system-wide education and protocol updates."},
{d:1,q:"NIMS provides:",opts:["State-specific protocols", "A standardized national framework for incident management across all agencies", "Only federal agency guidance", "Medication administration guidelines"],ans:1,exp:"NIMS establishes consistent terminology, organizational structures, and procedures enabling all levels of government and private organizations to work together effectively during any incident."},
{d:2,q:"Active shooter incidents follow which EMS protocol?",opts:["Immediately enter the hot zone", "Stage in the cold zone until secured \u2014 RTF moves into warm zone with law enforcement", "Enter the scene with law enforcement always", "Treat only after all threats are neutralized"],ans:1,exp:"TECC protocol: Threat suppression, Hemorrhage control, Rapid Extrication, Assessment, Transport. EMS stages in cold zone. RTF pairs medical providers with armed officers for warm zone rescue."},
{d:2,q:"POLST differs from a living will because:",opts:["They are identical documents", "POLST is an immediately actionable physician medical order while a living will requires interpretation", "POLST requires court approval", "Living wills are more legally binding"],ans:1,exp:"POLST is a physician-signed medical order immediately actionable across care settings. A living will is an advance directive expressing preferences that requires physician interpretation to translate into orders."},
{d:2,q:"Res ipsa loquitur in EMS law means:",opts:["Patient documentation standards", "Negligence is self-evident from the facts and the burden shifts to the defendant", "Verbal consent validity", "Scope of practice boundaries"],ans:1,exp:"Res ipsa loquitur (the thing speaks for itself) applies when an injury could not have occurred without negligence, making causation obvious and shifting the legal burden to the defendant."},
{d:2,q:"In a HAZMAT incident, EMS providers without specialized training should:",opts:["Enter the warm zone with appropriate PPE", "Stage in the cold zone and treat decontaminated patients only", "Enter the hot zone with a partner", "Treat patients before decontamination"],ans:1,exp:"EMS without HAZMAT training stages in the cold zone. Only specially trained HAZMAT teams enter the hot zone. EMS receives and treats patients after decontamination in the warm zone."},
{d:2,q:"Involuntary psychiatric hold allows transport against will when:",opts:["Any family member requests it", "The patient is an imminent danger to themselves or others", "The patient is confused", "The patient refuses all care"],ans:1,exp:"Involuntary holds permit transport of unwilling patients who are determined to be an imminent danger to themselves or others. Requirements vary by jurisdiction."},
{d:2,q:"Proximate cause in negligence means:",opts:["The duty to act existed", "The provider's breach of duty directly caused or worsened the patient's injury", "Damages were financial only", "The provider was on duty"],ans:1,exp:"Proximate cause: a direct causal link between the provider\'s breach of duty and the patient\'s harm. All four elements must be proven: duty, breach, causation, and damages."},
{d:2,q:"EMR (Emergency Medical Responder) role in EMS is to:",opts:["Replace EMTs", "Provide first response care before higher-level EMS arrives", "Administrative oversight", "Hospital triage only"],ans:1,exp:"EMRs are trained first responders who provide initial stabilizing care before transporting EMS units arrive. They bridge the critical first minutes of a medical emergency."},
{d:2,q:"EMTALA requires hospital EDs to:",opts:["Provide free care to all patients", "Perform a medical screening exam and provide stabilizing treatment for anyone presenting regardless of ability to pay", "Accept all transferred patients", "Only treat citizens"],ans:1,exp:"EMTALA (1986) requires Medicare-participating hospitals to provide a medical screening exam and necessary stabilizing treatment to anyone presenting to the ED."},
{d:3,q:"The Medical Practices Act governs:",opts:["Ambulance vehicle standards", "Who may perform medical procedures and what constitutes unauthorized practice", "Drug storage and labeling", "Billing practices"],ans:1,exp:"The Medical Practice Act defines the scope of medical practice and establishes the legal framework under which EMS providers may practice under physician delegation."},
{d:3,q:"Evidence-based practice led to abandonment of which EMS intervention?",opts:["Tourniquet use for extremity hemorrhage", "Aggressive IV fluid resuscitation in penetrating hemorrhagic shock", "Defibrillation for VF", "Aspirin for ACS"],ans:1,exp:"Large randomized trials showed aggressive crystalloid resuscitation in penetrating hemorrhagic shock worsens coagulopathy and re-bleeds clots. Permissive hypotension is now standard."},
{d:3,q:"Battery in medical law is defined as:",opts:["Threatening a patient with treatment", "Intentional harmful or offensive touching without consent including treating a patient who has clearly refused", "Failure to provide adequate care", "Documentation falsification"],ans:1,exp:"Battery equals unauthorized touching. Treating a patient who has expressly refused constitutes battery regardless of good intent. Assault equals threatening action without contact."},
{d:3,q:"Critical incident stress management is most effective when:",opts:["Applied immediately in the field", "Used as structured team-based debriefing within 24-72 hours after critical incidents", "Applied only to providers who request it", "Used in place of professional mental health treatment"],ans:1,exp:"CISM is most effective as a structured group debriefing 24-72 hours post-incident, allowing emotional processing, normalizing reactions, and identifying providers who need additional support."}
],

pediatric: [
{d:1,q:"The Pediatric Assessment Triangle (PAT) evaluates:",opts:["Pulse, pupils, perfusion","Appearance, work of breathing, circulation to skin","Airway, breathing, circulation","BP, HR, SpO₂"],ans:1,exp:"PAT: Appearance (TICLS), Work of Breathing, and Circulation to skin — a rapid visual assessment before hands-on exam."},
{d:1,q:"Normal respiratory rate for an infant (<1 year) is approximately:",opts:["12–20/min","20–30/min","30–60/min","60–80/min"],ans:2,exp:"Infants breathe 30–60 times/min normally. A rate of 20/min in an infant may indicate respiratory failure."},
{d:1,q:"Recommended compression depth for infant CPR is:",opts:["1 inch","About 1.5 inches (4 cm)","2 inches","2.5 inches"],ans:1,exp:"For infants, compress ~1.5 inches (4 cm) — approximately 1/3 of the chest AP diameter."},
{d:1,q:"A child with complete airway obstruction (cannot speak, cough, or cry) should receive:",opts:["Back blows only","Abdominal thrusts (Heimlich)","Blind finger sweeps","BVM ventilation"],ans:1,exp:"For children >1 year with complete obstruction, abdominal thrusts are performed. Infants receive back blows + chest thrusts."},
{d:1,q:"The Broselow tape is used to:",opts:["Estimate a child's age","Estimate weight-based dosing and equipment size","Assess developmental milestones","Calculate fluid requirements"],ans:1,exp:"The Broselow tape uses length as a proxy for weight to quickly determine drug dosages and equipment sizes in pediatric emergencies."},
{d:1,q:"Febrile seizures most commonly occur in children aged:",opts:["0–1 month","6 months to 5 years","6–12 years","Adolescents"],ans:1,exp:"Febrile seizures occur most often between 6 months and 5 years. Generally benign but require assessment to rule out serious causes."},
{d:1,q:"Signs of respiratory distress in a child include:",opts:["Slow regular breathing","Nasal flaring and retractions","Pink skin","Normal muscle tone"],ans:1,exp:"Nasal flaring and retractions (intercostal, suprasternal) indicate the child is working hard to breathe — significant distress requiring intervention."},
{d:1,q:"When pediatric abuse is suspected, the EMT should:",opts:["Confront the parents","Withhold suspicion from report","Document objectively and report to appropriate authorities","Refuse transport"],ans:2,exp:"EMS are mandated reporters. Document objective findings and report to receiving facility and appropriate authorities. Do not accuse or confront."},
{d:1,q:"Appropriate oxygen delivery for an alert child with moderate respiratory distress is:",opts:["Non-rebreather mask","Nasal cannula","Blow-by O₂ or pediatric NRB mask","BVM with O₂"],ans:2,exp:"Alert children may not tolerate tight-fitting masks. Blow-by O₂ or pediatric NRB allows supplemental O₂ delivery with better tolerance."},
{d:1,q:"Normal heart rate for a toddler (1–3 years) is approximately:",opts:["60–100 bpm","90–150 bpm","120–180 bpm","40–80 bpm"],ans:1,exp:"Toddlers normally have a heart rate of 90–150 bpm. Pediatric normal HR ranges are higher and decrease with age toward adult values."},
{d:1,q:"The most common cause of cardiac arrest in children is:",opts:["Primary cardiac dysrhythmia","Respiratory failure leading to hypoxic arrest","Trauma","Sepsis"],ans:1,exp:"Unlike adults, pediatric cardiac arrests are predominantly caused by respiratory failure — making airway management and ventilation critical priorities."},
{d:1,q:"Croup is characterized by:",opts:["Fever, drooling, inability to swallow","Barky seal-like cough, inspiratory stridor, low-grade fever","Silent cough, fever, respiratory failure","Expiratory wheezing and cyanosis"],ans:1,exp:"Croup (laryngotracheobronchitis) presents with a barky seal-like cough, inspiratory stridor, and low-grade fever. Usually viral, responds to cool mist and epinephrine in severe cases."},
{d:1,q:"Epiglottitis is a life-threatening emergency characterized by:",opts:["Barky cough, runny nose","High fever, drooling, tripod position, muffled voice","Low fever, gradual onset cough","Expiratory wheeze"],ans:1,exp:"Epiglottitis: high fever, severe sore throat, drooling (can't swallow), tripod sitting (forward-leaning), muffled/hot potato voice. Do NOT examine the throat — may precipitate complete obstruction."},
{d:1,q:"For infant CPR with two rescuers, the preferred compression technique is:",opts:["Two-finger technique","Two-thumb encircling technique","Heel of one hand","Full hand"],ans:1,exp:"Two-thumb encircling generates better compression force and depth for infants when two rescuers are present."},
{d:2,q:"A child's blood pressure is considered hypotensive when systolic BP is below:",opts:["90 mmHg","70 + (2 × age in years) mmHg","80 mmHg","100 mmHg"],ans:1,exp:"Minimum acceptable systolic BP in children: 70 + (2 × age in years). Values below this threshold indicate hypotension and impending decompensated shock."},
{d:2,q:"In pediatric shock, which sign appears LAST as compensation fails?",opts:["Tachycardia","Altered mental status","Hypotension","Pallor"],ans:2,exp:"Children compensate remarkably well — maintaining BP until they are severely depleted. Hypotension in a child is a preterminal sign of decompensated shock."},
{d:2,q:"The TICLS mnemonic for appearance assessment stands for:",opts:["Temperature, Injury, Color, Level, Sensation","Tone, Interactivity, Consolability, Look/gaze, Speech/cry","Tachycardia, Infection, Confusion, Level, Shock","None of the above"],ans:1,exp:"TICLS: Tone (muscle), Interactivity, Consolability, Look/gaze, Speech/cry — five components of the appearance leg of the PAT."},
{d:2,q:"A neonate born at home is apneic. Your first step is:",opts:["Intubation","Chest compressions","Warm, dry, stimulate, position airway","Administer epinephrine"],ans:2,exp:"Neonatal resuscitation: warm (dry, stimulate) and position the airway first. Most apneic neonates respond to these simple steps. Progress to PPV if still apneic."},
{d:2,q:"Bronchiolitis, most common in infants, is typically caused by:",opts:["Streptococcus pneumoniae","Respiratory syncytial virus (RSV)","Influenza A","Haemophilus influenzae"],ans:1,exp:"RSV is the leading cause of bronchiolitis in infants, causing lower airway inflammation, wheezing, and respiratory distress. Supportive care is the mainstay of treatment."},
{d:2,q:"A child is found in cardiac arrest. You deliver 2 minutes of CPR before applying the AED. The AED advises 'no shock.' You should:",opts:["Stop CPR — no shockable rhythm","Resume CPR for 2 more minutes","Check for pulse","Give epinephrine"],ans:1,exp:"Continue CPR. PEA and asystole (non-shockable rhythms in pediatric arrest) require high-quality CPR and treatment of reversible causes. Do not stop after a no-shock advisory."},
{d:2,q:"A toddler ingested household cleaner. Signs include drooling and white patches in the mouth. This suggests:",opts:["Opioid ingestion","Caustic/corrosive ingestion","Aspirin overdose","Antihistamine ingestion"],ans:1,exp:"Caustic ingestion (lye, drain cleaners, bleach) causes chemical burns to the mouth and throat — presenting with drooling, pain, and visible burns. Do NOT induce vomiting."},
{d:2,q:"Sudden Infant Death Syndrome (SIDS) is defined as:",opts:["A cardiac cause of infant death","Unexpected death of infant <1 year, unexplained after thorough investigation","Death during sleep from aspiration","Vaccine-related infant death"],ans:1,exp:"SIDS: unexplained death of an apparently healthy infant under 1 year, remaining unexplained after thorough investigation including autopsy. Risk is reduced by back-sleeping."},
{d:3,q:"A child with a tracheal foreign body that is causing complete obstruction and is unresponsive. After failed back blows and chest thrusts, you should:",opts:["Finger sweep the mouth regardless","Attempt laryngoscopy to visualize and remove the object if trained","Tracheotomy","Perform abdominal thrusts"],ans:1,exp:"If trained, direct laryngoscopy to visualize and remove a visible foreign body in an unresponsive child is appropriate. Do NOT perform blind finger sweeps in children."},
{d:3,q:"Neonatal resuscitation: after 30 seconds of effective PPV with no improvement, the next step is:",opts:["Administer surfactant","Check heart rate — if <60 bpm, begin chest compressions","Increase FiO₂ to 100%","Administer epinephrine"],ans:1,exp:"If HR <60 bpm after 30 seconds of effective PPV, begin chest compressions at 3:1 ratio with ventilations. Epinephrine is given if HR remains <60 after CPR."},
{d:3,q:"Non-accidental trauma (child abuse) is suggested by:",opts:["Consistent, plausible history with injury","Injuries inconsistent with developmental stage, multiple bruises in varying stages of healing, delayed presentation","Single fracture in a walking child","Accidental bruising over bony prominences"],ans:1,exp:"Red flags for abuse: injuries inconsistent with the history or developmental stage, injuries in non-ambulatory children, unexplained bruising, bruising in unusual patterns, delay in seeking care."},
{d:3,q:"A 3-year-old with suspected meningococcal septicemia has a petechial rash rapidly becoming purpuric. Priority treatment includes:",opts:["Acetaminophen and monitoring","Rapid fluid resuscitation, O₂, and urgent transport — consider antibiotics if in scope","Epinephrine IM","Dextrose IV"],ans:1,exp:"Meningococcal septicemia with purpuric rash is a time-critical emergency with 20–30% mortality. Rapid fluid resuscitation, O₂, and emergent transport are critical. Early antibiotics improve survival."},
{d:3,q:"In pediatric patients, intraosseous (IO) access is indicated when:",opts:["IV access is established","IV access fails after two attempts or is critically time-delayed in an unstable patient","Only in cardiac arrest","Only in neonates"],ans:1,exp:"IO access provides rapid reliable vascular access in critically ill pediatric patients when IV access fails. All IV medications and fluids can be administered via IO."},
,
{d:1,q:"Normal blood pressure for a school-age child (6–12 years) is approximately:",opts:["70/40 mmHg","90–110/60–70 mmHg","120/80 mmHg","140/90 mmHg"],ans:1,exp:"School-age children have BP approximately 90–110/60–70 mmHg. BP increases with age toward adult values. Use age-appropriate cuffs for accurate measurement."},
{d:1,q:"The most important difference in pediatric CPR compression-to-ventilation ratio with 2 rescuers is:",opts:["30:2 same as adults","15:2 (reflecting the higher proportion of respiratory arrests in children)","10:1","20:2"],ans:1,exp:"Two-rescuer pediatric CPR uses a 15:2 ratio, recognizing that ventilation is relatively more important in pediatric arrest (often respiratory in origin) compared to adults."},
{d:1,q:"Pyloric stenosis in infants typically presents with:",opts:["Bilious (green) vomiting","Projectile non-bilious vomiting causing dehydration","Bloody diarrhea","Abdominal distension without vomiting"],ans:1,exp:"Pyloric stenosis (2–6 weeks of age, male predominance): hypertrophied pylorus causes projectile non-bilious vomiting after feeding, leading to dehydration and metabolic alkalosis."},
{d:1,q:"A child with stridor at rest should be treated as:",opts:["Mild croup — discharge home","Potentially serious — monitor closely and prepare for deterioration","Normal variant in toddlers","Asthma exacerbation"],ans:1,exp:"Stridor at rest (not only with crying/activity) indicates significant upper airway compromise. These children can deteriorate rapidly — oxygen, position of comfort, and transport with minimal agitation."},
{d:1,q:"Meconium-stained amniotic fluid at birth indicates:",opts:["Normal fetal maturity","Possible fetal distress — be prepared for resuscitation","Always requires intubation","No additional concern"],ans:1,exp:"Meconium-stained fluid may indicate fetal hypoxia. Modern guidelines: if the infant is vigorous (good tone, crying, HR >100), routine resuscitation. If not vigorous, intubation and suctioning may be needed."},
{d:1,q:"Normal blood glucose in a newborn is:",opts:["<40 mg/dL","40–80 mg/dL","80–120 mg/dL","120–200 mg/dL"],ans:1,exp:"Neonatal hypoglycemia is defined as BGL <40–45 mg/dL. Newborns are at risk due to limited glycogen stores, especially if premature, small for gestational age, or born to diabetic mothers."},
{d:1,q:"Foreign body airway obstruction in an infant is treated with:",opts:["Heimlich maneuver","5 back blows + 5 chest thrusts, alternating","Blind finger sweeps","BVM ventilation immediately"],ans:1,exp:"Infant FBAO: 5 back blows (face down) alternating with 5 chest thrusts (face up) until the object is expelled or the infant becomes unconscious."},
{d:1,q:"When is a pediatric patient considered 'compensated' shock?",opts:["Blood pressure is low","Blood pressure is maintained by compensatory tachycardia and vasoconstriction","The patient is unresponsive","SpO₂ is below 90%"],ans:1,exp:"Compensated shock: the body maintains blood pressure through tachycardia, vasoconstriction, and increased contractility. Recognize early signs (tachycardia, delayed cap refill, mottling) before BP drops."},
{d:1,q:"In pediatric assessment, 'mottled' skin color indicates:",opts:["Normal skin pattern in infants","Patchy skin perfusion — sign of circulatory compromise","Bruising from trauma","Normal post-cry appearance"],ans:1,exp:"Mottling (blotchy, lace-like skin pattern) indicates poor peripheral perfusion, often seen in sepsis, shock, or hypothermia."},
{d:1,q:"RSI (Rapid Sequence Intubation) in pediatrics uses pretreatment with atropine in children <8 years because:",opts:["It prevents vomiting","It prevents bradycardia from laryngoscopy stimulation","It relaxes bronchospasm","It reduces secretions"],ans:1,exp:"Laryngoscopy stimulates the vagus nerve, causing bradycardia — children are particularly susceptible. Atropine pretreatment prevents symptomatic bradycardia during RSI in children <8 years (some protocols <1 year)."},
{d:2,q:"A 2-year-old with sudden onset stridor and no fever, no URI prodrome, was playing with small toys. The most likely diagnosis is:",opts:["Croup","Epiglottitis","Foreign body airway obstruction","Anaphylaxis"],ans:2,exp:"Sudden onset stridor in a toddler with no URI or fever, particularly after playing with small toys, strongly suggests foreign body aspiration until proven otherwise."},
{d:2,q:"Which finding in a neonate requires immediate resuscitation?",opts:["HR 120, pink, crying","HR <100, blue, limp, not breathing","HR 100, mildly cyanotic, good tone","HR 90, crying loudly"],ans:1,exp:"HR <100, central cyanosis, hypotonia, and apnea indicate a neonate requiring immediate intervention: warmth, stimulation, and positive pressure ventilation (PPV)."},
{d:2,q:"In pediatric burns, the rule of nines is modified because:",opts:["Children feel less pain","The head represents a larger percentage of BSA and the legs less in younger children","Burn depth differs in children","Children have thicker skin"],ans:1,exp:"In infants/young children, the head = 18% BSA (vs 9% adults) and each leg = 13.5% (vs 18% adults). Lund and Browder charts or pediatric-specific modifications should be used for accurate TBSA calculation."},
{d:2,q:"ALTE (Apparent Life-Threatening Event) now called BRUE (Brief Resolved Unexplained Event) is:",opts:["A definitive diagnosis of SIDS","An episode of color change, tone change, altered breathing, or consciousness changes in infants that fully resolves","A type of seizure","Caused by specific cardiac arrhythmia"],ans:1,exp:"BRUE: brief (<1 min), fully resolved episode in infants <1 year of: color change (cyanosis/pallor), abnormal breathing, tone change, or altered responsiveness. May indicate serious underlying pathology — requires evaluation."},
{d:2,q:"Pediatric sepsis differs from adult sepsis in that children:",opts:["Have the same diagnostic criteria","Maintain BP longer (compensated) and may not show hypotension until severely decompensated","Show hypotension earlier","Rarely develop sepsis"],ans:1,exp:"Children compensate remarkably well in septic shock — maintaining BP until late decompensation. Tachycardia, prolonged cap refill, altered mental status, and mottling may be the only early signs."},
{d:3,q:"In pediatric cardiac arrest, epinephrine dosing is:",opts:["1 mg IV regardless of weight","0.01 mg/kg IV/IO (1:10,000)","0.1 mg/kg IV/IO","1:1,000 IM only"],ans:1,exp:"Pediatric epinephrine for cardiac arrest: 0.01 mg/kg IV/IO of 1:10,000 solution (= 0.1 mL/kg of 1:10,000). Use Broselow tape for weight estimation."},
{d:3,q:"Hypercyanotic 'Tet spells' in children with Tetralogy of Fallot are treated with:",opts:["High-flow oxygen only","Knee-chest position + high-flow O₂ + IV morphine/beta-blockers","Defibrillation","Fluid restriction"],ans:1,exp:"Tet spells (hypercyanotic episodes): knee-chest position (increases SVR, reduces R→L shunting), 100% O₂, IV morphine (reduces SVR/anxiety), beta-blockers (reduce RVOT spasm). Avoid procedures that agitate the child."},
{d:3,q:"Non-accidental head trauma (shaken baby syndrome) is suspected when:",opts:["There is a clear trauma history","Retinal hemorrhages, subdural hematoma, and no adequate explanation for injuries in a pre-mobile infant","The infant has a fever","The anterior fontanelle is flat"],ans:1,exp:"Abusive head trauma: retinal hemorrhages + subdural hematoma in infants with no adequate history, especially pre-mobile children. Rib fractures and metaphyseal fractures are highly specific for abuse."},
,
{d:1,q:"The anterior fontanelle in infants should normally be:",opts:["Bulging and tense","Flat and soft","Sunken","Pulsatile and bulging"],ans:1,exp:"The anterior fontanelle should be flat, soft, and slightly pulsatile. Bulging = increased ICP (meningitis, hydrocephalus, intracranial hemorrhage). Sunken = dehydration."},
{d:1,q:"Pyloric stenosis most commonly presents at what age?",opts:["Birth","2–6 weeks of age","6–12 months","2–3 years"],ans:1,exp:"Pyloric stenosis typically presents at 2–6 weeks of age with progressive projectile non-bilious vomiting. Male infants are predominantly affected (4:1 male to female ratio)."},
{d:1,q:"A child who is alert but has extreme reluctance to move their neck and fever should raise concern for:",opts:["Mild URI","Meningitis or epiglottitis — both require urgent evaluation","Normal childhood behavior","Muscle strain"],ans:1,exp:"Nuchal rigidity (stiff neck) + fever in a child is meningitis until proven otherwise. Do not force neck flexion. Assess for petechiae, rash, and AMS. Urgent transport."},
{d:1,q:"The correct padiatric epinephrine dose for anaphylaxis (auto-injector) by weight threshold is:",opts:["0.1 mg for all children","0.15 mg for <30 kg; 0.3 mg for ≥30 kg","0.5 mg for all children","0.01 mg/kg via IV only"],ans:1,exp:"Pediatric EpiPen Jr (0.15 mg) for children 15–30 kg; regular EpiPen (0.3 mg) for ≥30 kg. For children <15 kg, weight-based dosing (0.01 mg/kg IM) using epinephrine 1:1,000 is used."},
{d:2,q:"Intussusception classically presents in infants with:",opts:["Bilious vomiting and distension","Colicky abdominal pain, drawing up of knees, vomiting, and 'currant jelly' stools","Profuse watery diarrhea","Fever and bloody diarrhea only"],ans:1,exp:"Intussusception (telescoping of bowel): episodic colicky pain (knees drawn up), inconsolable crying, then normal periods, vomiting, and 'currant jelly' (blood + mucus) stools."},
{d:1,q:"Which pediatric patient requires the most urgent airway intervention?",opts:["Croup with barky cough, mild stridor","Epiglottitis with drooling and respiratory distress","Asthma with mild wheezing","Bronchiolitis with mild tachypnea"],ans:1,exp:"Epiglottitis can cause complete airway obstruction with any agitation. These patients need calm, positioning of comfort, and immediate transport to a facility capable of surgical airway if needed."},
{d:2,q:"A premature infant at 28 weeks gestation is at risk for respiratory distress syndrome (RDS) because:",opts:["Their airways are too small","Surfactant production is insufficient before 34–36 weeks gestation","They breathe too fast","Their diaphragm is weak"],ans:1,exp:"Surfactant (produced by type II pneumocytes) reduces alveolar surface tension and prevents collapse. Premature infants lack sufficient surfactant, causing alveolar collapse and respiratory failure (RDS)."},
{d:1,q:"In pediatric emergencies, the Broselow tape uses which parameter to estimate weight?",opts:["Head circumference","Body length (height)","Estimated age","Abdominal girth"],ans:1,exp:"Broselow tape: measured from head to heel, correlated with color-coded zones that correspond to weight-based equipment sizes and drug doses."},
{d:2,q:"A toddler has been found unconscious near a bottle of cleaning agents. Your first priority is:",opts:["Determine what was ingested","Ensure scene safety and your own protection, then assess the patient","Call poison control immediately","Induce vomiting"],ans:1,exp:"Scene safety first — toxic exposures may release harmful vapors or present ongoing contact hazards. Then assess the patient, call poison control (1-800-222-1222), and transport. Never induce vomiting for caustics."},
{d:1,q:"When should you call a pediatric trauma alert?",opts:["Only for visible injuries","Based on anatomical injury, physiological criteria, and high-energy mechanism of injury","Only for children under 2 years","Only when directed by dispatch"],ans:1,exp:"Pediatric trauma alert criteria: physiological (GCS <14, RR <10 or >29, SBP <90), anatomical (penetrating injury, burns, flail chest), or mechanism (high-energy MOI, fall >10 ft, death in same vehicle)."},
{d:3,q:"In neonatal resuscitation, if HR remains <60 bpm after 30 seconds of PPV, you should:",opts:["Increase O₂ flow only","Begin chest compressions at 3:1 ratio (compressions:ventilations)","Administer epinephrine immediately","Check glucose"],ans:1,exp:"NRP (Neonatal Resuscitation Program): if HR <60 after 30 sec of effective PPV → begin chest compressions at 3:1 C:V ratio. If HR remains <60 after 60 sec of compressions → administer epinephrine 0.01–0.03 mg/kg IV/IO."},
{d:3,q:"Turner syndrome and Down syndrome patients may have increased risk of which EMS-relevant condition?",opts:["Tension pneumothorax","Atlantoaxial instability (C1–C2 subluxation) — be cautious with C-spine manipulation","Anaphylaxis","Coagulopathy"],ans:1,exp:"Down syndrome (trisomy 21) patients have a 10–30% prevalence of atlantoaxial instability — excessive C1–C2 movement that risks cord injury with forced neck flexion. Use extreme care with cervical spine management."},
,
{d:1,q:"Normal capillary refill time in children is:",opts:["Less than 1 second","Less than 2 seconds","Less than 4 seconds","Any time is acceptable"],ans:1,exp:"Normal capillary refill time in children is less than 2 seconds. Delayed CRT greater than 2 seconds indicates poor peripheral perfusion from septic shock, hypovolemia, or hypothermia."},
{d:2,q:"A child with fever and petechial rash should be treated as:",opts:["Viral illness — reassurance only","Meningococcal septicemia until proven otherwise — emergent transport and antibiotics if in scope","All of the above","None of the above"],ans:1,exp:"Non-blanching petechial rash plus fever equals meningococcal disease until proven otherwise. Mortality approaches 20% without treatment. Rapid fluid resuscitation and transport are critical."},
{d:2,q:"In a drowning patient, your first priority after removal from water is:",opts:["Spinal immobilization","Assess responsiveness and breathing — begin CPR with rescue breaths if absent","All of the above","None of the above"],ans:1,exp:"Drowning: the primary insult is hypoxia. Begin rescue breaths immediately and standard CPR. C-spine consideration is based on mechanism — most drownings do not involve significant spinal injury."},
{d:2,q:"Bilateral retinal hemorrhages in an infant with AMS and no adequate history of trauma suggests:",opts:["Normal variant","Abusive head trauma — shaken baby syndrome — until proven otherwise","All of the above","None of the above"],ans:1,exp:"Retinal hemorrhages plus subdural hematoma in a pre-mobile infant without adequate trauma history are highly specific for abusive head trauma. Document objectively and report to appropriate authorities."},
{d:1,q:"Bilious green vomiting in a neonate is an emergency because:",opts:["It is normal for newborns","It indicates obstruction distal to the duodenum such as malrotation or volvulus","All of the above","None of the above"],ans:1,exp:"Bilious vomiting in a neonate requires emergent evaluation. Causes include malrotation with volvulus — which can cause complete bowel ischemia within hours if untreated."},
{d:2,q:"Intraosseous access in a pediatric patient is indicated when:",opts:["IV access is already established","IV access fails after two attempts or is critically time-delayed in an unstable patient","All of the above","None of the above"],ans:1,exp:"IO access provides rapid reliable vascular access when IV fails. All IV medications and fluids can be administered via IO. It is the standard backup for critically ill pediatric patients."},
{d:1,q:"The recommended initial fluid bolus for pediatric septic shock is:",opts:["10 mL per kg","20 mL per kg of isotonic crystalloid over 5-10 minutes with reassessment","50 mL per kg","100 mL per kg"],ans:1,exp:"Pediatric septic shock: 20 mL per kg IV or IO isotonic crystalloid over 5-10 minutes. Reassess after each bolus. Repeat based on response while watching for signs of fluid overload."},
{d:2,q:"Status epilepticus in a pediatric patient is treated prehospitally with:",opts:["IV phenobarbital first","A benzodiazepine — IV lorazepam, IM or intranasal midazolam, or rectal diazepam per protocol","All of the above","None of the above"],ans:1,exp:"Benzodiazepines are first-line for pediatric status epilepticus. Use the most readily available route: IV or IO lorazepam, IM or intranasal midazolam, or rectal diazepam when IV access is unavailable."},
{d:2,q:"A toddler who cannot bear weight after a reported minor fall requires:",opts:["Reassurance — toddlers fall often","Careful evaluation for fracture and possible non-accidental trauma — fractures in pre-mobile children are suspicious","All of the above","None of the above"],ans:1,exp:"Any fracture in a child under 3 years who is not yet ambulatory, or injuries inconsistent with developmental stage or the stated history, requires careful evaluation for non-accidental trauma."},
{d:1,q:"A child with Down syndrome presenting with neck pain after minor trauma requires:",opts:["Standard cervical assessment only","Extra caution for atlantoaxial instability — spinal motion restriction and urgent evaluation","All of the above","None of the above"],ans:1,exp:"Trisomy 21 has a 10-30% prevalence of atlantoaxial instability. Even minor trauma can cause C1-C2 subluxation and spinal cord injury. Apply spinal motion restriction and transport urgently."},
{d:2,q:"Pediatric anaphylaxis may predominantly present with:",opts:["Urticaria only","Respiratory symptoms including wheezing and stridor — treat with IM epinephrine regardless","All of the above","None of the above"],ans:1,exp:"Pediatric anaphylaxis may manifest primarily with respiratory symptoms. Treatment is identical to adult anaphylaxis: IM epinephrine to the anterolateral thigh, oxygen, IV access, and fluid if hypotensive."},
{d:1,q:"The anterior fontanelle is sunken in:",opts:["Increased intracranial pressure","Dehydration — indicating significant fluid deficit","All of the above","None of the above"],ans:1,exp:"Sunken fontanelle indicates dehydration. Bulging tense fontanelle indicates increased intracranial pressure from meningitis, hydrocephalus, or intracranial hemorrhage."},
